one": true, "hidden": true}], "sources": [{"source": {"id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df", "user_id": "e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9", "name": "Justin's Knowledge", "description": "This is information about Justin, and relevant research.", "meta": null, "access_control": {"read": {"group_ids": [], "user_ids": []}, "write": {"group_ids": [], "user_ids": []}}, "created_at": 1768337776, "updated_at": 1768337788, "user": {"id": "e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9", "name": "Pluto System", "role": "admin", "email": "system@pluto.local"}, "write_access": true, "type": "collection"}, "document": ["WDAs and abstraction hierarchies are consumed during design by using the EID approach [29,48]. Our abstraction hierarchy will support system designers by properly articulating the ecosystem and clinician decision-making in context. The model supports system thinking and can help articulate how changes may impact the ecosystem through linear and ripple effects. [49]. Based on our analysis, the decision support requirements for primary care system are actually quite complex. The challenge for system engineers will be to determine how electronic systems could be support, and not hinder, the treatment process in primary care and to support SDM in its designs.\\nLimitations", "The abstraction hierarchy is a modelling tool that describes the results of a WDA [17]. The abstraction hierarchy is intended to be a full depiction of the necessary constraints that need to be taken into consideration in order for the system to achieve its purpose, while describing the system's underlining ecology and limitations [32]. Using abstraction hierarchies can help bridge the psychology-culture-medicine gap in healthcare. These hierarchies can be used to develop representations of patient care that are align with biomedical knowledge, support medical problem solving and act as a frame of reference [8]. As a structured approach to WDA, the abstraction hierarchy includes a layer to describe the system's functional purposes, abstract functions, generalized functions, physical functions and physical forms. Lines are shown between each layer to show means-end or how-why relationships [32].\\nWork Domains, Patients and Patient Care", "Conclusions: Our abstraction hierarchy links treatment goals, decision making constraints and task workflows. This model can be used by system developers who would like to use Ecological Interface Design to improve systems in primary care. Our hierarchy is the first in a future set that is needed to fully articulate Shared Decision Making. Future hierarchies could model the patient as a controller and could be useful for mobile application development. Incorporating Shared Decision Making concepts in team Cognitive Work Analysis could also prove valuable in trying to understand interdisciplinary teams.\\nKeywords: Clinical decision-making, knowledge support systems, and theory; health services research; modelling; patient decision aids; qualitative research; shared decision making\\nIntroduction"], "metadata": [{"source": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx", "name": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx", "created_by": "e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9", "file_id": "f2adc271-6177-44a2-a173-ade8713b2323", "start_index": 0, "hash": "437b1676e9a7323cf386390cc4e48440642c5eb19e52ec1c1a012072575f0c24", "embedding_config": {"engine": "ollama", "model": "nomic-embed-text"}}, {"source": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx", "name": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx", "created_by": "e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9", "file_id": "f2adc271-6177-44a2-a173-ade8713b2323", "start_index": 0, "hash": "437b1676e9a7323cf386390cc4e48440642c5eb19e52ec1c1a012072575f0c24", "embedding_config": {"engine": "ollama", "model": "nomic-embed-text"}}, {"source": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatmen