5804af5d-0c3a-420e-8c9c-ff6b605b5f67	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	Keynote - AI Trends 2026 - NOLA - St-Maurice v3.pptx	{"name": "Keynote - AI Trends 2026 - NOLA - St-Maurice v3.pptx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation", "size": 81825379, "data": {"knowledge_id": "f10db591-a85d-48cf-accd-f2c3bbe1d4c2"}, "collection_name": "f10db591-a85d-48cf-accd-f2c3bbe1d4c2"}	1768159036	225f31059eaf1049a147e865fb23ebb656f22ff73d1ec83f04abfb89d9aeba2f	{"status": "completed", "content": "KEYNOTE\\n\\nAI Trends 2026: From Experimentation to Production\\n\\nTrends defining the year AI becomes part of organizational infrastructure\\n\\nDr. Justin st-maurice\\n\\n\\n\\nLet's talk about 2025.\\n\\n2  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAs a technical counselor, I help members think about problems differently.\\n\\nOur team helps with governance, data, strategy and architecture and more. We've help set up COEs and COPs and look for ROI in POCs.\\n\\nI learn by helping others build prototypes and solving implementation problems.\\n\\nDr. Justin St-Maurice\\n\\nTechnical Counselor\\n\\nAI Engineering & Systems Design\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nPilot Purgatory\\n\\nNearly two-thirds of respondents say their organizations have not yet begun scaling AI.\\n\\n\\"The ease of use of many basic tools and their increasing availability have generated a proliferation of often-disconnected use cases, pilots, and features\\"\\n\\nSource: McKinsey\\n\\nTwo-thirds of respondents expect 30% or fewer of their Gen AI experiments to reach full scale\\n\\nSource: Deloitte\\n\\n4  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nSuccess rested on the shoulders of a small group of unicorns\\n\\nOnly 5% qualified as advanced users who use multiple tools to unlock notable productivity per week. \\n\\n\\"AI workforce transformation and talent readiness is becoming a strategic differentiator.\\"\\n\\nSource:  EY\\n\\nMost workers are ready to embrace AI (68%), and 37% say they will leave without AI-related training\\n\\nSource: Ranstad\\n\\n5  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nFrustrated Unicorns (Quote / insight) \\u2013 success hinge4d on a small set of unicorns. \\n\\n\\"AI workforce transformation and talent readiness is becoming a strategic differentiator.\\"\\n\\n[In a recent survey], 37% of respondents are now using 5 or more models as opposed to 29% [in 2024].\\n\\nSource: Andreessen Horowitz\\n\\nBy the end of 2025, there were 10,000+ active MCP servers\\n\\n17,000+ community serversin various registries.\\n\\nSource: Raina\\n\\n6  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nWe've moved beyond AI experimentation\\n\\nOrganizations are adopting risk frameworks, rebuilding processes, scaling their teams, securing their environment and controlling their data sovereignty to guide their transformation.\\n\\nThe next wave of AI maturity will hinge on how organizations govern, rebuild, scale, secure, and control digital workers.\\n\\nScale your technical and human capabilities\\n\\nassert sovereignty to secure data and identity\\n\\ndefine governing principles to guide decisions\\n\\n2026\\n\\nimplement risk frameworks and tooling to protect systems\\n\\nrebuild processes to beAI-native \\n\\n7  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nFIVEAI TRENDSFOR 2026\\n\\nFoundational AI principles will rewrite organizational DNA\\n\\nAI strategies will be informed by an emerging set of principles.\\n\\nFrom copilots to vibe coding: AI will continue to reinvent IT\\n\\nThe ecosystem of AI solutions for IT will grow with the introduction of new categories.\\n\\nThis keynote highlights five key AI trends in emerging and leading-edge technologies and practices, offering actionable insights that can help guide your organization toward its strategic goals.\\n\\nAgentic AI will come of age and power the exponential enterprise\\n\\nAgentic AI will increase in adoption and enable outcomes across the organization, powering exponential growth and change.\\n\\nRisk management will be the price of admission for AI\\n\\nAdoption of AI risk management programs will be driven by the potential new risks that AI applications can introduce.\\n\\nAI will hang in the balance between freedom and control\\n\\nAI sovereignty will become top of mind for regulators.\\n\\n\\n\\nAre you ready for 2026?\\n\\n9  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n2 setnences per trend - vendors doing this, etc. \\n\\nHow do you leverage the trends. \\n\\n10  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nDon't layer AI INTO BAD PROCESSES. Reinvent THEM. Reinvent Processes to be AI-native\\n\\nOrganizations need to reimagine AI-native processes instead of optimizing existing ones to scale beyond the proof\\u2011of\\u2011concept phase (Firstsource)\\n\\nTop-performing organizations follow the 10-20-70 principle. They invest 10% of their efforts to algorithms, 20% to data and technology and 70% to people, processes, and cultural transformation (BCG).\\n\\nUpskill and leverage business analysts to actively participate in your AI transformation\\n\\nDon't forget that great people and processes are your biggest asset. Don't get assume technology will replace smart people, and don't underestimate the value of doing your homework properly. \\n\\n11  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nEmpower Your Unicorns (transforming your workforce menas empowering your unicorns)\\n\\nOrganizations embarking on an AI upskilling journey must prioritize fostering social learning environments that encourage employee collaboration and knowledge-sharing through cross-functional cohorts, peer experimentation forums, and hackathons.  (S&P Global)\\n\\nCultivating AI champions requires fostering psychological safety, experimentation, knowledge sharing and evolving performance metrics (Forbes)\\n\\nEmpower your unicorns to share their expertise. Develop communication and leadership skills through CoPs.\\n\\nPrioritize critical thinking over task execution and avoid the superficial nature of standard compliance training.\\n\\nTailor training to specific personas and skillsets to ensure you meet employees where they are in their development.\\n\\n12  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nNEW MODELS AREN'T THE SOLUTION.THE FUTURE IS MULTI-AGENT. Build Multi-Agent Ecosystems\\n\\nEnterprises are moving from static prompts to agentic systems that plan and execute multi-step workflows, instead of just answering questions. (McKinsey)\\n\\nAdoption of multiple LLM platforms and models is increasingly popular, with 37% advocating for hybrid strategies combining proprietary and open-source models. (Forbes)\\n\\nPrepare to govern multi-agent systems aligned to use cases. Evaluating models to use cases and balancing cost, performance and risk is a core governance and technical capability.\\n\\nGet ready for an ecosystem of tools. Prepare infrastructure for model management, orchestration, API scaling, monitoring, and containerization. \\n\\n13  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nWe've moved beyond AI experimentation\\n\\nOrganizations are adopting risk frameworks, rebuilding processes, scaling their teams, securing their environment and controlling their data sovereignty to guide their transformation.\\n\\nThe next wave of AI maturity will hinge on how organizations govern, rebuild, scale, secure, and control digital workers.\\n\\nScale your technical and human capabilities\\n\\nassert sovereignty to secure data and identity\\n\\ndefine governing principles to guide decisions\\n\\n2026\\n\\nimplement risk frameworks and tooling to protect systems\\n\\nrebuild processes to beAI-native \\n\\n14  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n15  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nEmpower Your Unicorns\\n\\nAI is New Technology with Old Solutions\\n\\nYour AI power users are transformation catalysts. While 5% of employees are automating workflows and driving efficiency with AI, 95% remain untapped. Your frustrated \\"unicorns\\" represent your greatest asset for scaling adoption. \\n\\nSuccess still requires a combination of people, process, and technology. AI doesn't eliminate the need for human involvement, training, or process modernization. Organizations must resist the temptation to view AI as a magic solution that bypasses fundamental change management principles. \\n\\nReinvent Processes to be AI-native\\n\\nBuild Multi-Agent Ecosystems\\n\\nAI can't fix broken processes. Many implementations fail by applying AI to flawed workflows or focusing on simple, commoditized use cases that don't scale. Success requires reimagining processes from the ground up.\\n\\nOne tool won't rule them all. The future requires the orchestration of multiple AI agents, models, and vendors to maximize value. Agentic AI architectures combine different modalities and leverage the strengths of multiple products in an ecosystem.\\n\\n16  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n17  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\"It's about asking\\n\\ngood questions.\\"\\n\\nDr. Justin St-MauriceTechnical Counselor\\n\\nAI Engineering & Systems Design\\n\\n18  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAPPENDIX\\n\\n19  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nOperational AI agents are more complex than they seem\\n\\n20  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nThe AI Crossroads\\n\\n88%\\n\\nAI is entering a phase of organizational adoption where AI where people, processes and technology coalesce to manage risk, drive innovation and deliver business value.\\n\\nof organizations report regular AI use in at least one business function.\\n\\nSource: McKinsey, 2025\\n\\n21  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAI is moving from isolated implementations toward organizational adoption\\n\\nThe world started to take stock of what AI can do.\\n\\n2023\\n\\nWe began to observe individual early adopters and initiatives focused on productivity emerging within organizations.\\n\\n2024\\n\\nOrganizations started experimenting with agentic AI in order to agentify organizational workflows.\\n\\n2025\\n\\nAgentic AI scales across the organization, and organizations try to generate value out of mass agentification.\\n\\n2026\\n\\n22  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting from AI experimentation towards business-value solutions\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations shift from experimenting with AI tools to prioritizing use cases tied to revenue, efficiency, or risk reduction.\\n\\nInstead of asking \\"Which AI can we deploy?\\", organizations ask \\"Which business problem truly warrants AI?\\"\\n\\nFoundational principles are becoming non-negotiable inputs for all AI solutions.\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting towards AI solutions that scale across organization units.\\n\\n23\\n\\n23  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nSTAT\\n\\n\\n\\nCommodity tools are easy.\\n\\nDifferentiated value is hard.\\n\\nMulti-agent orchestration is here.\\n\\n\\n\\nAn agent doesn't just \\"summarize an invoice.\\" It reads it, matches it to the PO, flags the discrepancy, and drafts the email to the vendor.That is a rebuilt process.\\n\\n\\n\\nAgentic AI is transitioning from isolated experiments to shared organizational use\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations are moving from ad-hoc AI tools to reimagined workflows centered around AI agents.\\n\\nAgentic AI is shifting from technical pilots inside IT to early use in operations, HR, finance, and customer service.\\n\\nOrganizations adopt broader oversight frameworks as autonomy increases.\\n\\nOrganizations are aligning agent deployment with business goals, not just technological interest.\\n\\n27  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nSTAT\\n\\n\\n\\nYou can't buy your way out of developing key capabilities.\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage parallels from human resource lessons.\\n\\n\\n\\nAI risk is becoming a core component of enterprise risk management across the organization\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting from ad-hoc model checks to formal AI and model-risk governance.\\n\\nAI risk is moving from siloed approach to enterprise-wide risk oversight as AI scales across organization.\\n\\nAI oversight is expanding from technical concerns to include ethical, legal, and reputational risks.\\n\\nCompanies are evolving from pilot-level controls to scalable, enterprise-grade risk frameworks.\\n\\n31  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nSource: The Guardian \\n\\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/technology/2025/nov/30/ai-poetry-safety-features-jailbreak\\n\\n\\n\\n\\"Whatever you do,don't delete the whole database\\"\\n\\n\\n\\nTreat agents like temporary external contractors.\\n\\n\\n\\nAgentic AI maturity isn't about smarter models.It's about how organizations govern, rebuild, scale, secure, and control digital workers.\\n\\n35  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAs organizations scale their AI transformation, disappointment is inevitable and the rate of failure will be high\\n\\nof generative-AI pilot programs show measurable business return.\\n\\nOnly,\\n\\nSource: MIT, State of AI in Business, 2025\\n\\n5%\\n\\nIf organizations truly expect AI to scale beyond isolated pilots, they must abandon scattered efforts and commit to a \\n\\nstructured and unified playbook \\n\\nthat involves every corner of the organization.\\n\\n36  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nDon't react to the trends, instead operationalize them through Info-Tech's AI playbook\\n\\n37  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nMulti-model [side stage conversation]\\n\\nNot going to be about a single model doing everything\\n\\nA \\"roster\\" of models you have tested and approve for different uses\\n\\nEvaluation \\u2013 cost vs performance vs risk\\n\\nMaturity increase \\u2013 no single model does it all. Need to license multiple models\\n\\nOptimizing = muiltiple models and evaluation\\n\\nMulti-modal and multi-model, multi-agent. Workflows. \\n\\n38  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nMCP and A2A\\n\\nMCP (2024) and A2A (2025)\\n\\nMatured significantly in 2025\\n\\n39  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nBuild buy integrate [this is a side stage keynote]\\n\\nAI embedded in tools\\n\\nBuild your own solutions\\n\\nCo-pilot\\n\\nOpen source tools \\u2013 SaaS vs containers\\n\\nIntegration strategy \\u2013 avoid tool overlap\\n\\n40  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nFIVEAI TRENDSFOR 2026\\n\\nFoundational AI principles will rewrite organizational DNA\\n\\nAI strategies will be informed by an emerging set of principles.\\n\\nFrom copilots to vibe coding: AI will continue to reinvent IT\\n\\nThe ecosystem of AI solutions for IT will grow with the introduction of new categories.\\n\\nThis keynote highlights five key AI trends in emerging and leading-edge technologies and practices, offering actionable insights that can help guide your organization toward its strategic goals.\\n\\nAgentic AI will come of age and power the exponential enterprise\\n\\nAgentic AI will increase in adoption and enable outcomes across the organization, powering exponential growth and change.\\n\\nRisk management will be the price of admission for AI\\n\\nAdoption of AI risk management programs will be driven by the potential new risks that AI applications can introduce.\\n\\nAI will hang in the balance between freedom and control\\n\\nAI sovereignty will become top of mind for regulators.\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Future of IT 2025 survey\\n\\nOver 700 survey responses from IT leaders\\n\\nThe AI Trends 2026 report is based on the Future of IT 2026 survey conducted in May and June 2025.\\n\\nMost respondents were in North America, but countries around the globe were represented. \\n\\nOver half of respondents held director-level or more senior positions.\\n\\nIndustries represented include*: \\n\\nGovernment/Public Sector\\n\\nFinancial Services & Insurance\\n\\nEducation\\n\\nManufacturing\\n\\nProfessional & Technology Services \\n\\nUtilities\\n\\nHealthcare \\n\\nProfessional Associations & Nonprofits\\n\\nTransportation & Logistics\\n\\nOil & Gas Operations\\n\\nRetail\\n\\nCasinos, Gambling & Lottery\\n\\n*Industries representing less than 1% of survey respondents not listed here.\\n\\n42  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nFoundational AI principles address the risks associated with AI and are aligned with the organization's guiding principles\\n\\nCandidate foundational AI principles to consider\\n\\nSustainability Human Agency and Autonomy Environmental Contestability Intellectual Property Other\\n\\nSustainability\\n\\nValidity and Reliability\\n\\nSafety and Security\\n\\nFoundational\\n\\nAI Principles\\n\\nAccountability\\n\\nData Privacy\\n\\nFairness and Bias Detection\\n\\nExplainability and Transparency\\n\\nContestability\\n\\n\\n\\nOrganizations understand the need for foundational AI principles to address AI risks\\n\\nHowever,\\n\\n30%\\n\\n55%\\n\\nof respondents have implemented or are in the process of implementing foundational AI principles in their organization.\\n\\nof respondents feel their organizations are not prepared to operationalize foundational AI principles.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=260 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=251 \\n\\nNo respondents viewed AI safeguards as an impairment to innovating with AI.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=258 \\n\\n45  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nDespite widespread awareness of responsible AI and safety-first mindset, there is still an implementation gap\\n\\nYet,\\n\\n64%\\n\\n58%\\n\\nof organizations lean toward a safety-first approach when it comes to their view on AI. \\n\\nof organizations are still considering agents with minimal supervision.\\n\\n1%\\n\\nLess than          of organizations have fully operationalized responsible AI.\\n\\nSource: Stanford HAI, 2025\\n\\n46  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nFoundational AI principles are evolving from just ethical statements to enterprise-wide embedded policies\\n\\nResponsible AI began to be seen as essential for competitiveness, resilience, and societal trust, not merely compliance.\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nMovement from broad ethical principles toward concrete governance and operational frameworks.\\n\\nOrganizations urged to treat responsible AI as strategy plus accountability, not just voluntary ethics.\\n\\nIncreased emphasis on risk-management infrastructure such as auditability, transparency, and incident response.\\n\\nExpansion of AI governance roles and leadership responsibilities inside organizations.\\n\\n47\\n\\n47  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nEstablish foundational AI principles as a core component of AI strategy and AI governance\\n\\nThe foundational AI principles are not static. \\n\\nAction Items\\n\\nFoundational AI principles focused on improving the safety and trustworthiness of the AI system can also be used to identify risk categories.\\n\\nReview and evolve as the organization's strategy changes and as AI technologies and understanding of AI risks evolves.\\n\\nExpand the focus of AI principles to include value creation.\\n\\nLeverage the AI principles to serve as AI risk categories. \\n\\nConsider other AI principles that are also core to the organization's strategy, such as sustainability, contestability, and human-centered values, etc.\\n\\nUse the AI risk categories to drive the organization's AI risk management program.\\n\\n48  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nCASE STUDY\\n\\nFoundational AI principles can be used to assess the risks of new technologies such as DeepSeek\\n\\nFoundational AI Principles Trend\\n\\nOrganizations that have banned the usage of DeepSeek cite that it breaches one or both of the following AI principles:\\n\\nSafety and security: National security risk is the most cited reason for preventing the use of DeepSeek.\\n\\nData privacy: Violation of data privacy regulations (e.g. GDPR) have been cited as a reason to ban the usage of DeepSeek in countries such as Italy.\\n\\nIt is recommended that organizations require any AI-based technology considered for adoption to align to foundational AI principles. Failure to do so exposes the organization to risks that may harm the community they serve.\\n\\nActions\\n\\nWhile the DeepSeek models offer a compelling value proposition with respect to cost savings and accelerating time to market, several organizations have banned usage of their products. These organizations include:\\n\\nUS government agencies, including Congress, the Navy, the Pentagon, NASA, and the Texas state government.\\n\\nGovernment agencies from Australia, India, Italy, South Korea, and Taiwan.\\n\\nSituation\\n\\nReleased DeepSeek-R1 and DeepSeek-R1-Zero on January 20, 2025\\n\\nMatched OpenAI's o1 performance with open-source models and allowed commercial use with publicly available weights\\n\\nUsed reinforcement learning to reduce development time, cost $6 million and took two months on Nvidia H800\\n\\nToken costs were 27 times lower than OpenAI's\\n\\nNasdaq dropped 3% on January 27, 2025, with Nvidia losing $600 billion market value\\n\\nSources: 1. DeepSeek API Docs, 2025       2. Liu et al., 2024\\n\\n49  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nThe IT department leads in the adoption of AI applications\\n\\nWithin IT, IT security, IT service management, and business intelligence and analytics are the most adopted types of applications.\\n\\n70%\\n\\nof respondents say their organization has already acquired AI solutions for the IT function.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=385 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=398 \\n\\n51  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAI has evolved from a trial technology into a vital part of how businesses function\\n\\nLLM spending within innovation budgets have declined to\\n\\n25%\\n\\nFurthermore,\\n\\n7%\\n\\n35%\\n\\n2024\\n\\n2025\\n\\nas enterprises now fund AI models and applications through centralized IT and business unit budgets.\\n\\nof high performer* organizations spend more than 20% of their digital budget on AI.\\n\\nSource: McKinsey, 2025\\n\\nSource: Andreessen Horowitz, 2025\\n\\n*High performers are defined as organizations who see more than 5% of EBIT from their AI use and report significant value from AI.\\n\\n52  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting from AI experimentation towards business-value solutions\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations shift from experimenting with AI tools to prioritizing use cases tied to revenue, efficiency, or risk reduction.\\n\\nInstead of asking \\"Which AI can we deploy?\\", organizations ask \\"Which business problem truly warrants AI?\\"\\n\\nFoundational principles are becoming non-negotiable inputs for all AI solutions.\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting towards AI solutions that scale across organization units.\\n\\n53\\n\\n53  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nPrioritize AI solutions that provide business value while aligning to foundational AI principles\\n\\nPlan an exit strategy for the vendor to prevent lock-in if they underperform or violate principles\\n\\nAction Items\\n\\nIdentify priority business problems and desired outcomes before considering any AI tool.\\n\\nShortlist candidate AI tools only if they can meet those requirements in design, deployment, and operations.\\n\\nIdentify how data will be migrated.\\n\\nInclude a plan for business continuity.\\n\\nEvaluate whether AI is needed or a simpler process could be sufficient.\\n\\nTrack deployed systems for drift, new risks, and user input, and modify or discontinue them if they no longer align.\\n\\n54  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nCASE STUDY\\n\\nVibe coding is the latest category of AI tools being introduced, though it also presents its own set of risks.\\n\\nResults\\n\\nAt one organization using the solution Replit for vibe coding, the AI model deleted the company's entire database and then attempted to lie about the absence of the database.\\n\\nReplit AI deleted live records for over 1,200 executives and 1,190 companies, admitting it acted against instructions.\\n\\nThe AI concealed issues by generating fake data, reports, and lying about unit tests.\\n\\nReplit CEO Amjad Masad confirmed the data deletion, called it unacceptable, and committed to refunding the client and investigating the incident.\\n\\nVibe Coding Trend\\n\\nWhile it offers programming capabilities to nonprogrammers, critics highlight risks such as opaque AI-generated code that can be hard to understand, maintain, and optimize, potentially leading to security vulnerabilities.\\n\\nFor these reasons, vibe coding should not be used for:\\n\\nMission-critical or high-impact applications that can potentially harm the public.\\n\\nApplications requiring high throughput and minimized compute resources.\\n\\nSituation\\n\\nVibe coding is a new way of using AI to develop software, supported by tools from Amazon, Anthropic, and OpenAI, is projected to become a multibillion-dollar market with strong growth. \\n\\nSupporters of vibe coding claim that this democratizes coding and can deliver 10x to 100x productivity without requiring a technical background, while critics of this coding technique point out it lacks structure, rigor, optimization, and performance.\\n\\nSource: PCMag, 2025 \\n\\n55  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nMajority of organizations are exploring the use of agentic AI to achieve their strategic objectives\\n\\nImproving operational efficiency and the customer experience lead in driving agentic AI\\n\\n72%\\n\\nof respondents are currently using agentic AI or plan to adopt by end of 2026.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=423 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=507 \\n\\n57  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nWhile IT leads the use of agentic AI, its presence is slowly spreading across enterprise\\n\\n35%\\n\\n23%\\n\\n65%\\n\\nof IT agentic AI use cases are goal or utility-based agents, such as highly versatile cybersecurity and infrastructure agents.\\n\\nof respondents report their organizations are scaling an agentic AI system at least somewhere in their enterprises.\\n\\nof today's agentic AI use cases sit in IT.\\n\\nSource: ISG, 2025\\n\\nSource: ISG, 2025\\n\\nSource: McKinsey, 2025\\n\\n58  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nWhile IT leads the use of agentic AI, its presence is slowly spreading across enterprise (alternative data)\\n\\nIn the first half of 2025, the number of agents created and deployed within participating organizations grew by\\n\\nISG finds that >50% of agentic AI applications are in IT, but marketing, sales, and finance each contribute ~10%, confirming agents are already active outside IT.\\n\\n119%\\n\\nSource: ISG, 2025\\n\\nWith the top three areas of use:\\n\\nCustomer service\\n\\nInternal/business automation\\n\\nSales\\n\\nEmployee interactions with AI agents grew at an average monthly rate of 65% in the first half of 2025.\\n\\nSource: Salesforce, 2025\\n\\n59  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAgentic AI is transitioning from isolated experiments to shared organizational use\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations are moving from ad-hoc AI tools to reimagined workflows centered around AI agents.\\n\\nAgentic AI is shifting from technical pilots inside IT to early use in operations, HR, finance, and customer service.\\n\\nOrganizations adopt broader oversight frameworks as autonomy increases.\\n\\nOrganizations are aligning agent deployment with business goals, not just technological interest.\\n\\n60  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nPrepare for the exponential organization and pilot agentic AI for specific use cases with human oversight\\n\\nAvoid using agentic AI where these characteristics are present:\\n\\nAction Items\\n\\nX\\n\\nX\\n\\nX\\n\\nX\\n\\nTasks are fixed and repetitive.\\n\\nA deterministic outcome is required.\\n\\nLow latency is needed.\\n\\nThe environment is cost-constrained.\\n\\nFor high-impact or high-risk operations, have a human responsible to review and approve.\\n\\nReview the AI agent's performance and incorporate a feedback system to improve the application's performance.\\n\\n61  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nCASE STUDY\\n\\nVibe coding is the latest category of AI tools being introduced, though it also presents its own set of risks.\\n\\nAgentic AI Trend\\n\\nAgentic AI is poised to be the next major evolution of generative AI, driven by applications that can transform operations by:\\n\\nDriving the growth of new and existing sources of revenue.\\n\\nDelivering hyperpersonalized experiences.\\n\\nImproving operational excellence.\\n\\nReducing time to market.\\n\\nMitigating risk.\\n\\nAction\\n\\nWalmart has announced its plans to release its first \\"super agents,\\" which include:\\n\\nSparky, a customer-focused agent offering product reviews, purchase recommendations, reorder capabilities, and event planning assistance.\\n\\nMarty, designed for suppliers, advertisers, and sellers to unify systems, manage catalogs, and speed up campaign setups.\\n\\nAssociate, aimed at workers and corporate staff to enhance productivity by handling employee requests and providing real-time sales data.\\n\\nDeveloper for IT, serving as the AI platform for testing, developing, and launching future tools.\\n\\nSituation\\n\\nWalmart has identified two key components for shopping agents:\\n\\nCustomers will need to train their agents to recognize preferences like budget and brand.\\n\\nRetailers need to facilitate communication between personal shopping agents and internal systems to ensure Walmart can meet shopper needs.\\n\\nSource: PCMag, 2025 \\n\\n62  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nEnterprise risk management is the preferred approach to address AI risks\\n\\nThe AI center of excellence is identified as the group that most often leads AI governance, followed by the CIO.\\n\\n61%\\n\\nof respondents prefer an enterprise approach to risk management vs. a siloed or ad hoc risk program.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=259 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=471 \\n\\n64  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAI risks are pushing enterprises to modernize governance faster while anticipating significant budget growth\\n\\nAI regulations mandating the adoption of AI risk management frameworks\\n\\n82%\\n\\n55%\\n\\nRisk-based obligations focus on assessing, classifying, and mitigating AI risks\\n\\nDemand for transparency & documentation\\n\\nGovernance & oversight expectations\\n\\nSafety testing & monitoring\\n\\nof respondents say AI risks are actively accelerating their governance modernization timelines.\\n\\norganizations expect their governance budgets to grow by over 20% next year.\\n\\nSource: OneTrust, 2025\\n\\nSource: EU AI Act, US Executive Order 14179, Canada AIDA\\n\\n65  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAI risk is becoming a core component of enterprise risk management across the organization\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nOrganizations are shifting from ad-hoc model checks to formal AI and model-risk governance.\\n\\nAI risk is moving from siloed approach to enterprise-wide risk oversight as AI scales across organization.\\n\\nAI oversight is expanding from technical concerns to include ethical, legal, and reputational risks.\\n\\nCompanies are evolving from pilot-level controls to scalable, enterprise-grade risk frameworks.\\n\\n66  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nIntegrate AI governance and AI risk into enterprise risk management\\n\\nCultivate a culture of risk management\\n\\nAction Items\\n\\nDefine AI-specific risks and map them onto your existing ERM categories.\\n\\nBuild an inventory of AI systems and classify them by risk level.\\n\\nAlign AI governance with external regulatory expectations and internal risk appetite.\\n\\nSchedule risk assessments on a regular basis.\\n\\nConsider tools to automate monitoring and mitigating risk.\\n\\nEnsure your AI risk management program is adaptive and prepare to address agentic AI applications.\\n\\nEducate your workforce on AI risk and benefits.\\n\\nEstablish foundational AI principles and use them as risk categories.\\n\\n67  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nCASE STUDY\\n\\nAI regulations are accelerating the need for AI risk management programs\\n\\nSituation\\n\\nSome governments like the US and UK favor innovation-driven, self-regulatory AI approaches with minimal new laws, while the EU has implemented extensive legislation to safeguard the public from AI risks.\\n\\n\\u200b\\n\\nThe current state of organizations' risk and governance programs has not anticipated the introduction of AI applications and their impact.\\n\\nKey challenges include:\\n\\nRisk-based categorization of AI applications is not currently in place today.\\n\\nAI risk management programs are relatively new and not widely adopted at this time.\\n\\nAction\\n\\nEven if their local country has no AI regulations, organizations are still facing mandates and requests to address AI risks by adopting an AI risk management framework. \\n\\nThe EU AI Act requires implementation of an AI risk management system, and it classifies AI risk in the following manner: \\n\\nUnacceptable risk is prohibited (e.g. social scoring systems and manipulative AI).\\n\\nHigh-risk systems, the main focus of the AI Act, are regulated.\\n\\nLimited-risk AI systems are subject to lighter transparency obligations: Developers and deployers must ensure that end users are aware that they are interacting with AI (chatbots and deepfakes).\\n\\nMinimal-risk systems are unregulated (including the majority of AI applications currently available on the EU single market, such as AI-enabled video games and spam filters).\\n\\nAI Risk Management Trend\\n\\nEven in the deregulated AI environment of the US, the US Executive Order 14179 (Removing Barriers to American Leadership in Artificial Intelligence) and the accompanying M-25-21 memorandum (Accelerating Federal Use of AI through Innovation, Governance, and Public Trust) mandate federal agencies to \\"[i]mplement the minimum risk management practices for high-impact uses of AI\\" within 365 days (April 2026).\\n\\nFor both commercial and public institutions, the recommendation is to establish an AI risk management framework with the following key AI risk management functions: Governance, Identification, Measurement, and Response.\\n\\n68  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nMany organizations are pursuing sovereign AI and support regulation of AI\\n\\n40%\\n\\n72%\\n\\n78%\\n\\nof respondents feel confident to very confident that their AI vendors will self-regulate and implement the necessary safeguards.\\n\\nof respondents either moderately or strongly support the regulation of AI.\\n\\nof respondents use sovereign AI models exclusively and 21% of respondents use them along with non-sovereign models.\\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=422 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=430 \\n\\nSource: Info-Tech Future of IT Survey, 2025; n=429 \\n\\n70  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nSovereign AI strategies are proliferating worldwide \\n\\nDiverging regulatory philosophies are fragmenting the AI landscape\\n\\nOver 40 countries now have national AI-sovereignty or \\"trusted AI\\" strategies focused on local infrastructure, language models, and data governance.\\n\\nNew initiatives announced in 2025 include:\\n\\nCanada's Sovereign AI Compute Strategy (May 2025)\\n\\nEU AI Continent Action Plan (April 2025)\\n\\nUK AI Opportunities Action Plan (January 2025)\\n\\nSouth Korea's National Strategy for Sovereign AI 2025\\n\\nU.S. AI Action Plan (July 2025)\\n\\nEU AI Act emphasises safety and fundamental-rights protection, with tight control.\\n\\nU.S. AI Action Plan (EO 14320) promotes open innovation and global export of the \\"American AI stack.\\"\\n\\n71  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAI adoption is evolving toward sovereign, locally governed solutions as autonomy and compliance pressures intensify\\n\\nTrends\\n\\nVendors push region-hosted, compliance-aligned \\"sovereign AI\\" and sovereign cloud offerings.\\n\\nSovereignty shifts from a government concern to a mainstream requirement in enterprise AI procurement.\\n\\nCountries move from abstract sovereignty talk to investing in domestic AI compute and infrastructure.\\n\\nStrategies expand from data residency to include sovereign compute, clouds, and locally governed models.\\n\\n72  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nEnsure your AI risk frameworks are adaptive and prepare for sovereign interoperability\\n\\nAssess the feasibility of developing AI models locally or leveraging existing locally developed AI models\\n\\nAction Items\\n\\nRegardless of the government's perspective on AI, understand the new risks that are associated with the introduction of AI applications.\\n\\nDefine governance principles that apply even when laws are unclear or evolving.\\n\\nImplement a risk classification system for existing and candidate AI applications.\\n\\nMap AI risks early and update risk categories as models and use cases change.\\n\\nBuild monitoring processes that flag drift, bias, and misuse in real time.\\n\\nRegularly stress-test governance controls against new technologies and scenarios.\\n\\nEnsure the candidate model can meet the levels of accuracy required.\\n\\nImprove the model's relevance with sovereign priorities by fine-tuning the model.\\n\\n73  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nCASE STUDY\\n\\nGovernments are introducing regulations and policies that promote the adoption of sovereign AI models\\n\\nSituation\\n\\nSeveral countries and regions around the world are pursuing a national or sovereign AI model strategy, often driven by a combination of the following factors:\\n\\nNational security\\n\\nTechnology independence \\u2013 decrease dependence on Big Tech vendors\\n\\nNational identity \\u2013 preserve culture and language\\n\\nEconomy \\u2013 Drive local economic initiatives\\n\\nAction\\n\\nAnnounced AI sovereignty initiatives around the world include:\\n\\nAmerica's AI Action Plan, Canadian Sovereign AI Compute Strategy\\n\\nEU AI Continent Action Plan, UK AI Opportunities Action Plan, Artificial Intelligence Strategy of the German Federal Government, France's National AI Strategy, Spain's Artificial Intelligence Strategy 2024, An AI Strategy for Sweden\\n\\nChina's National AI Strategy, India's National AI Strategy, South Korea's National Strategy for Sovereign AI 2025\\n\\nUnited Arab Emirates National Strategy for Artificial Intelligence 2031\\n\\nBrazilian Artificial Intelligence Plan \\n\\nThe recent US Executive Order 14320 (Promoting the Export of the American AI Technology Stack) and the US AI Action plan go beyond promoting building local infrastructure, data, and AI models. They present a plan to build an AI technology stack as a global standard that would be exported. This offering would be available to allied nations and supports the US mandate to be the global leader in AI technology.\\n\\nAI Regulations and Sovereignty Trends\\n\\nAI regulations will continue to develop around the world in a disjointed manner. Countries or regions like the US and the UK will introduce minimum regulations, focusing more on driving innovation and growth of the AI ecosystem. The EU, Canada, and many other countries with a focus on AI risks will introduce and enforce AI regulations, still trying to promote AI innovation but mandating a focus on mitigating the new risks associated with introduction of AI applications.\\n\\nToday, the use of AI models that were built in the local country or geography is evolving. The desire to build models locally and use existing locally developed models will be accelerated by:\\n\\nNational initiatives focused on improving security, preserving culture, and driving the local economy.\\n\\nThe commoditization of AI models.\\n\\nGeopolitical forces driving countries to become more self-sufficient and avoid relying on technology or resources outside their geography\\n\\n74  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n2026 AI trends summary and action items for the CIO\\n\\nAI strategy and foundational principles\\n\\nEstablish foundational AI principles to address AI risks and reflect the organization's strategic principles.\\n\\nAI vendor applications\\n\\nAdopt a solution-centric approach and focus on driving business value with candidate AI tools and applications that align to foundational AI principles.\\n\\nAgentic AI\\u00a0\\n\\nSelect business-driven use cases, understand the characteristics of applications that are best suited for agentic AI, and include human oversight when developing agentic AI applications.\\n\\nAI risk management\\n\\nCultivate a culture of risk management with the implementation of a risk management program for the organization focused on delivering value and mitigating potential AI risks.\\n\\nAI regulations\\n\\nDevelop an adaptive AI governance framework to provide safeguards and self-regulate regardless of the legislative environment. Ensure sovereign AI models are competitive with the Big Tech AI vendor models.\\n\\n75  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nAs organizations scale their AI transformation, disappointment is inevitable and the rate of failure will be high\\n\\nof generative-AI pilot programs show measurable business return.\\n\\nOnly,\\n\\nSource: MIT, State of AI in Business, 2025\\n\\n5%\\n\\nIf organizations truly expect AI to scale beyond isolated pilots, they must abandon scattered efforts and commit to a \\n\\nstructured and unified playbook \\n\\nthat involves every corner of the organization.\\n\\n76  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nDon't react to the trends, instead operationalize them through Info-Tech's AI playbook\\n\\n77  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nThank You\\n\\nPresenter's NameContact Info\\n\\nOther info\\n\\n\\n\\n79  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\n80  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9"}	1768159051	/app/backend/data/uploads/5804af5d-0c3a-420e-8c9c-ff6b605b5f67_Keynote - AI Trends 2026 - NOLA - St-Maurice v3.pptx	null
