yer on your stream dashboard, click the cog wheel Settings button to set up your camera and microphone prior to participating in the roundtable.When the presenters are ready to take attendee volunteers, please click the Hand icon to raise your hand and indicate that you wish to participate!\\n\\n\\n\\nDo You Want To Participate?\\n\\nIf you have been selected, you will receive a pop-up window asking to accept the presenter handing you the microphone and camera. Click Accept to enter the discussion!\\n\\nPlease remember that this event is simultaneously a live and recorded broadcast and intended to be used in further educational or promotional materials.\\n\\n\\n\\nClosed Captioning\\n\\nTo turn on captions for this\\u00a0Roundtable, use your Media Player controls to adjust settings.\\n\\nTurn ON/OFF the captions via the CC icons that are in the Media Player as shown\\n\\nCC button\\n\\nRoundtable will start at 11:00am ET.\\u200b\\n\\n\\n\\nRoundtable:\\n\\nAlign Technology Services With Your Cyber Insurance Lifecycle Needs\\n\\nTrends in Cyber Insurance, Opportunities for Technology Service Providers and the Impacts on Policy Holders\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group Inc. is a global leader in providing IT research and advice.\\u00a0 Info-Tech's products and services combine actionable insight and relevant advice with\\u00a0 ready-to-use tools and templates that cover the full spectrum of IT concerns.\\n\\n\\u00a9 1997-2023 Info-Tech Research Group Inc.\\n\\n\\n\\nRoundtable Objectives\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group produces research to help leaders make strategic, timely, and well-informed decisions. We partner with your teams to provide actionable tools to analyst guidance, ensuring they deliver measurable results for the organization.\\n\\nBetter Research Than Anyone\\n\\nDrive Measurable Results\\n\\nLeverage Industry Best Practices\\n\\n\\n\\nHousekeeping\\n\\nUse the Q&A function to post questions. Please setup your camera microphone prior to participating.\\n\\n01\\n\\n02\\n\\nWe will select a few common questions to be answered by our panelists at the end of the session.\\n\\n03\\n\\nWe will send out the slides and recording after the Roundtable.\\n\\n\\n\\nRoundtable \\u00a0\\n\\nPresenters\\n\\nFritz Jean-Louis\\n\\nPrincipal Advisor\\n\\nCybersecurity\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nMichel H\\u00e9bert\\n\\nPractice Lead\\n\\nIndustry Research\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nValence Howden\\n\\nAdvisory Fellow\\n\\nCIO Advisory\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nJustin St-Maurice\\n\\nTechnical Counselor\\n\\nInfrastructure & Operations\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nTechnology Service Providers are Key Players in the Cyber Insurance landscape\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nProtect\\n\\nMonitor\\n\\nRespond\\n\\nRenew\\n\\nNegotiate\\n\\nPolicyholder\\n\\nFor technology service providers, cyber insurance is both an opportunity and a risk.\\n\\nProviders that excel at managing cyber risk with mature processes and services will prosper, whereas smaller ad hoc teams are a serious risk. \\n\\nSecurity Controls\\n\\nArtificial Intelligence\\n\\nRisk\\n\\nEstimation\\n\\nRiskManagement\\n\\nTechnologyServiceProvider\\n\\nTechnologyServiceProvider\\n\\nValidate\\n\\nInvestigate\\n\\nAssess\\n\\nTest\\n\\nReport\\n\\nCyber Insurer\\n\\nINSURANCE POLICY\\n\\nCompliance Requirements\\n\\nOrganizational Maturity\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   11\\n\\n\\n\\nSupport customers throughout the cyber insurance lifecycle\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nCoordinate with cyber insurers and policyholders by adopting insurance language.\\n\\nAlign service offerings with specific lifecycle stages to help contextualize your value proposition. \\n\\nRisk Assessment\\n\\nPolicy Renewal\\n\\nPolicy Selection\\n\\nClaims Management\\n\\nUnderwriting\\n\\nIncident Response\\n\\nImplementation and Maintenance\\n\\n\\n\\nCYBER INSURANCE BY THE NUMBERS\\n\\nCyber insurance growth and evolution\\n\\nIn a survey conducted in 2024:\\n\\n33% of senior executives cited the prohibitive cost of cyber insurance as the key reason for not adopting coverage, underscoring affordability challenges within the industry (\\"Senior Executives' Reasons,\\" Statista, 2024). \\n\\n66% of executives highlighted the desire to bundle network security with cyber insurance policies and signaled a desire to move toward more integrated service models (\\"Opinion of Senior Executives,\\" Statista, 2024).\\n\\nThe estimated global cost of cybercrime projected to escalate to US$15.63 trillion by 2029, leaving insurers little choice other than to tighten policy terms and increase premiums to mitigate their exposure (\\"Cybercrime,\\" Statista, 2024).\\n\\nThe global cyber insurance market is expected to reach US$22.5 billion by 2025 and reflects an ongoing demand for risk transfer products in a more volatile digital landscape (\\"Global Cyber Insurance Market Size,\\" Statista, 2023).\\n\\nPercentage of executives citing high price as main reason for not having cyber insurance.\\n\\n(Munich Re, 2024)\\n\\n33%\\n\\nPercentage of executives  that stated network security should be provided as a service with cyber insurance.\\n\\n(Munich Re, 2024)\\n\\n66%\\n\\nUS$22.5 billion\\n\\nUS$15.63 trillion\\n\\nProjected global cost of cybercrime by 2029\\n\\nGlobal cyber insurance market size by 2025\\n\\n(\\"Cybercrime,\\" Statista, 2024)\\n\\n(\\"Global Cyber Insurance Market Size,\\" Statista, 2023)\\n\\n\\n\\nCYBER INSURANCE BY THE NUMBERS\\n\\nTrends in underwriting, policies, and claims\\n\\nIn 2016, enterprise risk management capabilities were the primary consideration for underwriters assessing cyber risk and underwriting policies (Deloitte University Press, 2017). \\n\\nFactor influencing cyber insurance risk and payouts remains multifaceted, influenced by regulatory compliance, third-party exposure, company size, and the sensitivity of the data being protected (UpGuard, 2024).\\n\\nClaim denials remain a challenge for many businesses, with some reports indicating as many as 44% of claims in 2023 were rejected due to noncompliance with security requirements (Accent Consulting, 2024; Your Policy, 2024). \\n\\nEmerging risks related to AI are increasingly on the radar, with nearly 700 potential risks identified in just the last two years (MIT Technology Review, 2024). These risks pose new challenges for insurers as AI systems become more advanced and complex.\\n\\nIn 2024, the average cost of breaches associated with a high-skill shortages jumped by 7.1% to US$5.74 million (\\"Average Cost of a Data Breach,\\" Statista, 2024).\\n\\nBy mid-2023, claim frequency had decreased to 1.64% while the global average cyber insurance claim amount was US$86,592 (\\"Average Claim Amount,\\" Statista, 2024).\\n\\n\\n\\nCYBER INSURANCE BY THE NUMBERS\\n\\nRecord holders in the cyber insurance industry\\n\\nMOST IMPROVED\\n\\nLOSS RATIO\\n\\nBIGGEST EVER CYBER INCIDENT\\n\\nBIGGEST BREACH CLAIMS 3+ YEARS\\n\\nThe United States continues to bear the highest costs for data breaches, with an average cost per breach reaching $9.36 million as of early 2024. The US remains a critical focus area for insurers due to its large-scale digital infrastructure and frequent high-profile breaches. This has led to increased premiums and stricter policy terms, especially in industries like healthcare and finance that are more vulnerable to cyberattacks (\\"Average Cost of a Data Breach,\\" Statista, 2024; S&P Global, 2022).\\n\\nIn France, the cyber insurance industry saw dramatic improvements in recent years. The market underwent significant transformation after a challenging period where loss ratios spiked to 167% in 2020. However, by 2022, insurers in France adapted their pricing models and tightened underwriting practices, successfully lowering the loss ratio to just 22%. This reduction was driven by more disciplined risk management strategies\\u200b (\\"Loss Ratio,\\" Statista, 2023; Commercial Risk, 2024).\\n\\nOne of the most severe attacks on the US healthcare system resulted in damages exceeding $1 billion, setting a record and illustrating the significant impact of large-scale cyber incidents (Insurance Business, 2024).\\n\\n\\n\\nEXPERT INSIGHTS ON MARKET SHIFTS\\n\\nReal-world stories and fables from experts highlight subjectivefactors relating the two interconnected industries.\\n\\n\\n\\nAI vs. AI? Advanced automation and AI may become conditions of cyber insurance\\n\\nAt a conference, the president of a major vendor confides, \\"Cyber insurers are gearing up to require the use of artificial intelligence in security defenses.\\"\\n\\nShe elaborates that cybercriminals are unleashing AI-driven attacks, and the only effective countermeasure is deploying AI on the defense side too. \\"It's becoming a battle of AIs versus AIs,\\" she muses. \\"If you don't have AI guarding your systems, you might soon find yourself uninsurable.\\"\\n\\nCyber Insurer\\n\\nGenerated with ChatGPT 4o (September 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nStay in your lane. Cyber insurers estimate and assume risks while technology service providers mitigate and avoid them  \\n\\nAt a recent cybersecurity roundtable, a confident MSSP took the floor and made a bold offer: \\"If you use our cybersecurity services, we'll underwrite any security breaches you might face, and we'll handle finding reinsurers!\\"\\n\\nThe room fell silent as attendees exchanged glances. Was this guy serious? Surely anyone who understands risk will know that assuming that level of risk is a very bad idea\\u2026 \\n\\nOur elephantsecurity controls are so good, I'll underwrite it myself!\\n\\nGenerated with ChatGPT 4o (September 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nFriend or foe? The insurer-client relationship can start to look more adversarial, with competing interests at play\\n\\nAt a cybersecurity meetup, a CISO shared an unexpected twist in his dealings with their cyber insurer. \\"Out of nowhere, we discovered that our insurer had hired an external firm to test our defenses,\\" he said.\\n\\n\\"They came back with a list of vulnerabilities and a set of strict conditions we had to meet to keep our coverage. It was adversarial, and we felt the need to have our own representation just to navigate the situation.\\"\\n\\nFind anythingsurprising?\\n\\nI wasn't expecting a surprise inspection\\u2026\\n\\nGenerated with ChatGPT 4o (September 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nThe end of cyber insurance? Though it is a common safety net that many require, it might soon vanish\\n\\nOver an early morning coffee, a risk management guru leaned back and confidently declared, \\"Cyber insurance is on its deathbed.\\" \\n\\n\\"Think about it,\\" he continued. \\"With cyberthreats evolving faster than ever and 'unknown unknowns' lurking around every corner, insurers can't predict risks anymore. And if they can't predict risk, they can't insure against them. Anyone who knows anything about risk knows they shouldn't assume unknown risk. Cyber insurance as we know it is dead.\\"\\n\\nToo\\n\\nmany\\n\\nunknown\\n\\nunknowns\\n\\nGenerated with ChatGPT 4o (September 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nSupport customers throughout the cyber insurance lifecycle\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nCoordinate with cyber insurers and policyholders by adopting insurance language.\\n\\nAlign service offerings with specific lifecycle stages to help contextualize your value proposition. \\n\\nRisk Assessment\\n\\nPolicy Renewal\\n\\nPolicy Selection\\n\\nClaims Management\\n\\nUnderwriting\\n\\nIncident Response\\n\\nImplementation and Maintenance\\n\\n\\n\\nAlign services with the cyber insurance lifecycle\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nInsurance Life Cycle\\n\\nTechnology and Consulting Service Opportunities\\n\\nPolicy Selection\\n\\nTranslate risk assessments into financial terms andrecommend policies that meet risk transfer needs.\\n\\nMonetize the need to make organizations insurable.\\n\\nContribute to 