riteria, Cost Expectations.\\n\\n\\n\\nJustin\\n\\nContact your account representative for more information.workshops@infotech.com   1-888-670-8889\\n\\nDEVELOP YOUR AGENT PROTOTYPEWorkshop Agenda\\n\\nSESSION 0 Use Case Alignment & Readiness SESSION 1 Business Requirements & SESSION 2 Map your Agent Capabilities & Workflow SESSION 3 Define your Prototype Orchestration & Governance SESSION 4 Define your Agent Evaluation Criteria WHO Leaders Leaders, Business Stakeholders, Technical Teams Technical Teams Technical Teams Technical Teams + Leaders ACTIVITIES Initial use case/workflow discussion and scoping OUTCOMES Agreed upon high-value use case\\n\\n\\n\\nJustin\\n\\nContact your account representative for more information.workshops@infotech.com   1-888-670-8889\\n\\nSCALE YOUR AI AGENT Workshop Agenda\\n\\nSESSION 0 Use Case Alignment & Readiness SESSION 1 Business Requirements & SESSION 2 Map your Agent Capabilities & Workflow SESSION 3 Define your Prototype Orchestration & Governance SESSION 4 Define your Agent Evaluation Criteria WHO Leaders Leaders, Business Stakeholders, Technical Teams Technical Teams Technical Teams Technical Teams + Leaders ACTIVITIES OUTCOMES\\n\\n\\n\\nLeaders achieve tangible assets and clear decisions; teams gain an executable plan\\n\\nUsers of this research can expect to accomplish:\\n\\nTangible Assets Decisions Locked Functional agent prototype (scoped) Target use case and success criteria (KPIs/SLAs) Prompt and tooling playbook Model choice and routing rules Safety and observability baseline dashboard Guardrails and human-in-the-loop points Data source inventory and integration plan Data sources prioritized for RAG/memory FinOps plan with token budget and alerts Cost optimization and usage monitoring thresholds Benchmark and performance report Rollout gates, staffing, and RACI Scaling and implementation roadmap Investment and operating model next steps\\n\\n\\n\\nUse Info-Tech expertise to avoid failure patterns that derail prototype projects\\n\\nSix major challenges must be mitigated:\\n\\nUnclear \\"Good\\"\\n\\nAnalysis Paralysis\\n\\n01.\\n\\n02.\\n\\nNo shared KPIs, thresholds, or decision gates Instead: Define success metrics upfront\\n\\nStrategy docs without working software\\n\\nInstead: Build to learn rapidly\\n\\nLate Data Gaps\\n\\nTool Sprawl\\n\\n03.\\n\\n04.\\n\\nRAG/memory blocked at the end\\n\\nInstead: Validate data access early\\n\\nOpaque behavior and incidents\\n\\nInstead: Build tracing from day one\\n\\nBolted-on Governance\\n\\nToken Surprises\\n\\n05.\\n\\n06.\\n\\nCompliance rewrites the plan\\n\\nInstead: Embed guardrails early\\n\\nQuality/cost trade-offs unmanaged\\n\\nInstead: Monitor costs proactively\\n\\n\\n\\nDeliver a prototype that unlocks a scalable agentic AI program for the enterprise\\n\\nDemo-Ready Agent\\n\\nTechnical Performance Metrics\\n\\nProve value on real scenarios with functional capabilities\\n\\nMeasure and optimize accuracy, latency, containment, and unit cost.\\n\\nLocked Decisions\\n\\nRepeatable Method\\n\\nConfirm model/tooling, guardrails, data scope, and rollout gates\\n\\nImplement a proven approach to expand to new teams and use cases\\n\\nPrototype\\n\\nAlignment\\n\\nEvidence\\n\\nScale\\n\\n\\n\\nCase Study #1\\n\\nINDUSTRY\\n\\nSOURCE\\n\\nFinance\\n\\nArxiv\\n\\nEnterprise Expense Automation\\n\\nChallenge\\n\\nA Korean conglomerate struggled to efficiently process high-volume, unstructured expense receipts. Existing rule-based Robotic Process Automation (RPA) systems were inadequate for handling diverse exceptions, leading to manual bottlenecks and significant delays.\\n\\nApproach\\n\\nA hybrid workflow was deployed, combining OCR/IDP for initial data extraction, Generative AI for intelligent interpretation and categorization, and an automation agent for orchestrating the overall process. A critical human-in-the-loop mechanism was integrated to manage and learn from exceptions.\\n\\nResults\\n\\nExpense report processing became 80% faster.\\n\\nAchieved lower error rates, directly contributing to higher employee satisfaction.\\n\\nEstablished a continuous learning loop, enabling the system to evolve and improve based on human feedback for exception cases.\\n\\n\\n\\nCase Study #2\\n\\nINDUSTRY\\n\\nSOURCE\\n\\nHealthcare\\n\\nUiPath\\n\\nAccounts Receivables Processing\\n\\nChallenge\\n\\nOmega Healthcare process 250 million medical documents annually. Manual billing and claims processes led to slow turnaround times and high operational costs, hindering efficiency and increasing administrative burden.\\n\\nApproach\\n\\nThe company deployed UiPath AI Document Understanding technology integrated with automation agents. This solution was designed to automatically extract critical data from diverse medical documents and intelligently route transactions for billing and claims processing.\\n\\nResults\\n\\n15,000 staff hours saved monthly.\\n\\nApproximately 40% reduction in documentation processing time.\\n\\nAchieved 50% faster turnaround with a 99.5% accuracy rate.\\n\\n\\n\\nCase Study #3\\n\\nSOURCE\\n\\nINDUSTRY\\n\\nGlean\\n\\nTelecommunications\\n\\nKnowledgebase Search and Retrieval\\n\\nChallenge\\n\\nDeutsche Telekom sought to automate internal HR queries and streamline order processing. Their goal was to enhance operational efficiency and free up human resources from repetitive, rule-based tasks.\\n\\nApproach\\n\\nThe company partnered with Glean to build AskT, an AI-powered employee conversational chatbot. Employees can access company knowledge for a range of use cases beyond HR: call center, finance, service desk, and so on, More sources are added every month to AskT, making AskT more comprehensive over time. \\n\\nResults\\n\\nReduced search time from over two minutes to 18 seconds.\\n\\nAskT takes 3.8 seconds to summarize 150+ documents.\\n\\n\\n\\nPhase 1\\n\\nBusiness Requirements & Value Alignment\\n\\nPhase 2\\n\\nPhase 1\\n\\nPhase 3\\n\\nPhase 4\\n\\n2.1 Select agent runtime model(s) & routing\\n\\n2.2 Author agent instructions\\n\\n2.3 Specify tools & knowledge sources\\n\\n2.4 Build Design Agentic Workflow v1\\n\\n1.1 Define value proposition & problem\\n\\n1.2 Map current workflow & personas\\n\\n1.3 Set business goals \\n\\n1.4 Define prototype scope & boundaries\\n\\n1.5 Specify success metrics & acceptance\\n\\n1.6 Design high-level workflow\\n\\n3.1 Select orchestration strategy\\n\\n3.2 Implement guardrails & safety\\n\\n3.3 Finalize Design Agentic Workflow v2\\n\\n4.1 Establish evaluation & benchmarking plan\\n\\n4.2 Define risks & mitigations\\n\\n4.3 Prioritize implementation & milestones\\n\\n4.4 Develop rollout plan\\n\\nBuild your Agentic Prototype\\n\\nThis phase will walk you through the following activities:\\n\\nDefining the problem and capturing baselines (volume, SLAs, cost, error).\\n\\nMapping personas and the as-is workflow (pain points, handoffs, systems).Setting business goals and documenting explicit non-goals.\\n\\nDefining scope & boundaries (in/out, thresholds, approvals, rollback).Specifying success metrics & acceptance (targets, methods, owners, ship/no-ship).\\n\\nDesigning the high-level workflow using Input \\u2192 Steps + Logic \\u2192 Output and flagging [Reasoning] steps.\\n\\n\\n\\nLarge language models (LLMs) are closed systems of interconnected parameters. The most recent ancestor of LLM technology is simple autocorrect technology on cellphones. In the last decade, the technology has gone from taking small text inputs to predict the mostappropriate word to come next in a sentence to accepting millions of words (prompts) to predict the content of entire essays. The exact mechanisms that allow an LLM to accept a prompt, understand it, and generate a unique response are not understood (Futurism, 2024).\\n\\nSolutions leveraging generative AI can deliver experiences that were previously impossible\\n\\nUnleash novel ideas with the unprecedented interactive capabilities of generative AI (Gen AI).\\n\\nPreviously impossible? \\n\\nOld technology, more parameters\\n\\nContext-aware content generation: Gen AI produces rich, context-aware content adapted to cultural nuances, social contexts, and user needs. \\n\\nBrainstorming and decision-making support: Gen AI can analyze and synthesize huge amounts of data to provide insights and assessments that support brainstorming activities and decision-making.\\n\\nPersonalization at scale: Gen AI can personalize user experiences in real time by catering to individual preferences, needs, and behaviors. \\n\\nChatGPT prompt [June 2024]: Draw me a picture of an LLM. Emphasize the chaotic nature of the LLM, its social interface and its advanced technology underpinnings.\\n\\n\\n\\nIt's a new type of human/computer interaction\\n\\nWHY IS INTERACTING WITH GEN AI SOLUTIONS CHALLENGING?\\n\\nThey produce complex sociotechnical impacts. Generally, information systems interact with people and impact multiple domains through complex interdependencies. Healthcare systems, for example, simultaneously impact data, patient care, physician collaboration, and regulatory requirements. Gen AI components further complicate these interactions.\\n\\nThey are dynamic, evolving pieces of technology. The underlying LLM models evolve with new data sets and will change with societal shifts in values, culture, and knowledge. At their core, they are not rule-based solutions and are difficult to manage with traditional technology controls.\\n\\nThey are nondeterministic systems. Gen AI is not designed to simply handle predetermined inputs. Its strength is its ability to accept input from any user and flexibly cater to different requests. Gen AI can infinitely customize experiences, and the integrity of such solutions requires new types of boundaries. \\n\\nThey need to incorporate responsible principles. While processing inputs, Gen AI solutions need to navigate ethical dilemmas and governance constraints. Data privacy, algorithmic bias, and the responsible use of AI are central to viable designs, where accountability becomes both a technical and a social challenge.\\n\\nReview Get Started With AI in Requirements Management to learn more about the evolving human/computer interface.\\n\\n\\n\\nMisaligning the human/computer experience is a recipe for failure\\n\\nMisalignments between humans and technology occur in both buy and build scenarios. A sociotechnical systems lens is helpful in both approaches to designing integrated solutions. Selecting the right solution ensures that its implementation supports and advances the strategic objectives of the organization, regardless of whether the solution is engineered in-house or purchased off the shelf.\\n\\nBUY OR BUILD?\\n\\nMisalignments between technological capabilities and social elements lead to failure, despite the intrinsic quality of the technology or the strategic soundness of the goals.\\n\\nAccurate models that act contrary to responsible principles will not be trusted. \\n\\nPoor data will degrade the user experience.\\n\\nSimple interfaces incorporated into complex workflows will hinder team productivity.\\n\\nSlow hardware that takes too much time to deliver a response will lower the value to the user.\\n\\n\\n\\nEmbrace a sociotechnical systems approach to drive solution alignment\\n\\nSocial requirements are an important part of solution design. Sociotechnical systems (STS) theory is based on the idea that communities function through technology use, and that people work through software using hardware. \\n\\nSTSs are an intersection of multiple sciences:\\n\\nSociologists see\\u00a0social\\u00a0systems\\n\\nPsychologists\\u00a0see cognitive\\u00a0systems\\n\\nComputer scientists\\u00a0see information\\u00a0systems \\n\\nEngineers\\u00a0see hardware\\u00a0systems\\n\\nAn STS approach sees multiple system types as interconnected and recognizes the union of people and technology as a natural evolution of both social and technical systems (Interaction Design Foundation, 2024).\\n\\nUse an STS approach to:\\n\\nExplore the interrelationships between people, technology, and the organizational environment of solutions.\\n\\nSystematically align humans and technology to manage the interaction between them. \\n\\nIncorporate a balance between technically-advanced solutions and social responsibility by giving equal weight to human and technology elements.\\n\\nInitial ChatGPT prompt [June 2024]: Draw me a picture of a socio-technical system.\\n\\n\\n\\nA design pattern is a description or template for how to solve a software engineering problem in many different situations. A design pattern is generally narrowly focused and offers a detailed, reusable solution (Source Making, 2021).\\n\\nA design methodology offers a structured framework that addresses broader system challenges and is adaptable to the unique requirements and complexities of many situations. A design methodology facilitates a systematic exploration of needs, design, and implementation through a holistic approach (IBM, 2023).\\n\\nUsing systems design methodologies to manage complex sociotechnical systems is a well-known and well-published domain of engineering science.\\n\\nAlign human and technical elements using systems design principles and tools \\n\\nUse Info-Tech's methodology to align the human and technical elements of your innovative Gen AI solutions.\\n\\nIdentify the human or organizational need.\\n\\nDecompose solutions requirements with human and technical lenses.\\n\\nDescribe the human-technology interaction.\\n\\nWhat is a design methodology?\\n\\n\\n\\nInfo-Tech's human-centered wireframe methodology for AI solutions\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nDesign solutions with a sociotechnical lens.\\n\\nConsider not only the technology but also the social systems within which the solution will be embedded to manage requirements and constraints.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo develop a core understanding of the solution value from a human perspective and ensure the solution is rooted in addressing real, specific human or organizational needs.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA problem statement that clearly and concisely describes the issue being addressed by the solution.\\n\\nProblem statements should be supported by concrete data. \\n\\nProblem statements should not prematurely suggest solutions.\\n\\nPotential activities\\n\\nInterview users and key stakeholders.\\n\\nDistribute surveys to get insights on organizational needs and pain points.\\n\\nAnalyze current systems and workflows to identify gaps and areas for improvement.\\n\\nReview social, technological, economic, and environmental factors that influence the need for the solution.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\n\\n\\nDevelop a problem statement\\n\\nFocus on understanding the problem fully before jumping into solutioning. In sociotechnical design, technology solutions need to address a specific human, social, or organizational need. \\n\\nWhy create a problem statement?\\n\\nIt establishes a human-centric focus, emphasizing the user needs and contexts before defining technology requirements, and ensures solutions are tailored to actual human use cases.\\n\\nIt mitigates technology-centric thinking and reduces the risk of developing solutions that are technically sound but fail to address real-world problems. Avoid technology for the sake of technology.\\n\\nIt enhances solution adoption and increases the likelihood of user acceptance and satisfaction by aligning solution functionalities with specific user needs and expectations.\\n\\n\\n\\nSpecific: Clearly define the problem with specific data and insights and avoid vague descriptions. Use quantifiable metrics to highlight the severity and impact of the problem.Relevant: Ensure the problem is directly related to stakeholder needs and aligns with organizational goals. Make it clear why this problem needs urgent attention.User-centric: Consider the human or societal impact of the problem by showing how the issue affects individuals or communities. Define the human need.Scoped: Scope the problem without making it too broad or too narrow, which would lead to more focused and effective solution development.\\n\\nClearly describe the problem\\n\\nA problem statement should clearly and concisely describe the issue being addressed, outline the impact of the problem, and hint at possible outcomes without suggesting specific solutions prematurely. \\n\\nGood problem statements\\n\\nBad problem statements\\n\\n\\n\\nSupport your statement with data\\n\\nA problem statement should include references to data and be grounded in facts. \\n\\nExamples from different industries:\\n\\nHealthcare: \\"Hospital readmission rates for heart failure patients have increased by 20% over the last year, leading to higher healthcare costs and reduced patient satisfaction. A solution is needed to identify contributing factors and reduce these rates.\\"\\n\\nEducation: \\"Local high school students are showing a 30% lower proficiency in math compared to national averages, affecting their readiness for college-level courses and future employment opportunities.\\"\\n\\nTechnology: \\"Our company's software deployment process takes, on average, 30% longer than the industry benchmark, leading to delays in updates, decreased productivity, and client dissatisfaction.\\"\\n\\nRetail: \\"Customer foot traffic in our main store has declined by 15% quarter-over-quarter, significantly impacting sales and threatening long-term business sustainability.\\"\\n\\n\\n\\nSpecific, relevant, user-centric, and scoped\\n\\nExample of a well-written problem statement for an LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library:\\n\\n\\"Public libraries play a pivotal role in engaging communities with great and diverse literature, but with over 130 million books worldwide, finding a good book can be daunting. Advanced readers in particular face challenges in discovering new titles that resonate with their varied interests, especially readers from different cultural backgrounds. There is a need for an effective system within public libraries that can navigate the literary landscape without influence from marketplaces that can intelligently match readers with books that not only pique their interest but also expand their cultural understanding.\\"\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Current SOPs/policies. Problem statement (including top three pain points). Materials Participants PRD template. Prototype Sponsor\\n\\n1.1 Define the problem statement\\n\\n45-75 minutes\\n\\nAs a group, define the problem to solve and the value of solving it. Record your findings in Phase 1, Section 1 of our Agentic PRD Template.\\n\\nReview the process. Define the problem to solve, who's impacted, and why now is the right time to solve it. Identify the top three pain points for users or customers in the process.\\n\\nIdentify by what measures the current process fails (e.g. speed, cost, quality, risk, experience).\\n\\nExplain why rules-based automation isn't sufficient to solve the problem.\\n\\nDocument any existing baseline metrics that will be improved if you solve the problem (e.g. volumes, SLAs, error/variance, costs), and the expected degree of improvement.\\n\\nConsider the following:\\n\\nWhich steps are judgment-heavy vs. mechanical? Judgement-heavy steps are more difficult to automate through rules-based automation. \\n\\nWhat happens if we do nothing for 6\\u201312 months? Establish the impact of doing nothing can help you articulate the value of solving the problem. \\n\\nTo do\\n\\nDownload your copy of Info-Tech's \\n\\nGeneral Purpose Agent Prototype \\u2013 PRD Framework\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   40\\n\\n\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution \\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo structure and define the solution in a way that aligns technological capabilities with human needs and organizational objectives, ensuring that the solution is both technologically feasible and human-centered.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA solution with detailed requirements and constraints. Based on systematic analysis and according to the human-tech ladder lens, the solution:\\n\\nProvides an opportunity for input from a wide range of stakeholders.\\n\\nDefines a successful solution.\\n\\nActivities\\n\\nHold brainstorming sessions (e.g. whiteboarding sessions, tabletop exercises) with business and technical leaders.\\n\\nUse multiple iterations of activities to finalize the solution details based on input.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage a human-tech ladder to define requirements\\n\\nWhat is a human-tech ladder?\\n\\nVicente (2003) presented a human-tech ladder to describe technology uses at different levels of abstraction, including physical, psychological, team, organizational, and social levels. This methodology has been used in areas such as aviation, nuclear power generation, and healthcare to make technology safe for human interaction and useful for end users.\\n\\nInfo-Tech's adaptation of the human-tech ladder decomposes AI solutions into their social and technological components to emphasize and manage the complexity of integrating AI systems within social and technical contexts. The modified ladder introduces layers specifically dedicated to AI, data, software, and hardware to help development a wholistic understanding of solution requirements involving AI.\\n\\nThe human-tech ladder can help you systematically consider both the social (human) and technical challenges at each stage of solution design and technology implementation to ensure a more holistic and integrated approach to developing complex sociotechnical systems.\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage the human-tech ladder to deliver great solutions\\n\\nWhy use the human-tech ladder?\\n\\nSystematically assess potential challenges and specific requirements from multiple perspectives. Each level is a different type of challenge to manage and requires different competencies. Remember that managing people, policies, and organizational behavior is a different discipline than optimizing bits, bytes, and performance.\\n\\nSimultaneously integrate solutions into multiple complex systems. Acknowledge and consider multiple impacts of the solution's introduction and ensure that systems are aligned to drive an effective implementation.\\n\\nInvolve and engage multiple stakeholders and decision-makers in the design process and ensure that the needs and expectations of various stakeholders are met. Improve satisfaction among users, teams, and organizational leaders by designing solutions with their specific requirements in mind.\\n\\n\\n\\nSystematically consider human and technical challenges\\n\\nHumanfactors\\n\\nOrganization: How will the solution align with organizational strategies and goals?\\n\\nTeam: How will the solution impact team collaboration, dynamics, and roles?\\n\\nUser: How will users interact with the solution?\\n\\nHardware\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nModel\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nData\\n\\nUser\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nModel: How will the underlying models and algorithms process and interpret data?\\n\\nData: How will underlying data support the solution accurately and consistently? \\n\\nSoftware: How will the solution integrate with other systems and components?\\n\\nHardware: How will the solution interact with the real world? \\n\\nTechnologyconstraints\\n\\n\\n\\nDefine your solution requirements\\n\\nOrganizational criteria\\n\\nTeam criteria\\n\\nModel criteria\\n\\nData criteria\\n\\nHardware criteria\\n\\nUser criteria\\n\\nSoftware criteria\\n\\nOrganizational constraints\\n\\nTeam constraints\\n\\nUser constraints\\n\\nModel constraints\\n\\nData constraints\\n\\nSoftware constraints\\n\\nHardware constraints\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nDecompose solutions using the human-tech ladder\\n\\nDefine solution requirements\\n\\nUser\\n\\nBrainstorm\\n\\nideas andconcepts\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nDecomposed requirements\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Respect intellectual property laws and ethically source book content and metadata. Augment the library team's capability to deliver high-quality customer service, both online and offline. Allow users of any age to comfortably and securely talk about their book preferences. Be able to ask users interactive questions in a friendly way to understand their preferences on genres and favorite books. Use validated, opensource book content or a metadata database. Provide a seamless experience and integrate with the existing book reservation system. Run with minimal costs in the cloud and scale without excessive cost increases.\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nMore examples in the solution library\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Policy constraints, technical/integration limits, risk posture. In/Out table, approval thresholds, rollback notes. Materials Participants Scope board template; threshold ladder. Product Owner/PM, Ops Lead, Security/GRC, Data Owner, Engineering Lead.\\n\\n1.2 Define Prototype Scope & Boundaries\\n\\n45-75 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nIn scope / Out of scope (channels, geos, amounts, segments).\\n\\nData sources & environments (sandbox vs. prod); approvals/thresholds.\\n\\nExit/handoff rules and rollback conditions.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nCan a newcomer understand scope in 60 seconds?\\n\\nWhat exclusions will stakeholders ask about\\u2014and why?\\n\\nWhich human approvals remain, and at what thresholds?\\n\\nWhat's the rollback path if an action is blocked/uncertain?\\n\\nWhat PII is read/written/logged?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   48\\n\\n\\n\\nAI has gone agentic\\n\\nWhile traditional software enables users to automate workflows, LLM-powered agents are autonomous systems that independently accomplish tasks on your behalf.\\n\\nAspect Traditional Software AI Agents Logic flow Predetermined if/then branches Dynamic reasoning based on context Input handling Structured, validated fields Natural-language understanding Decision making Deterministic rules Probabilistic with reasoning Adaptability Code changes required Learns from instructions/examples Error handling Specific error codes Contextual recovery strategies User interaction Forms, buttons, static APIs Conversational and intuitive\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nIt's important to distinguish agents from other LLM-integrated applications. Simple chatbots, single-turn LLMs, or sentiment classifiers, which do not control multi-step workflow execution, are not agents. Make sure to confirm with your provider how they understand what 'agent' means, beyond the marketing.\\n\\nKey characteristics of an agent include:\\n\\n\\n\\nAgentic systems go beyond generative AI\\n\\nThe evolution from generative AI to advanced agentic capabilities involves a progression through increasing levels of autonomy and complexity.\\n\\nA\\n\\nStep 2: Single-Agent Autonomy\\n\\nStep 3: Multi-Agent Autonomy\\n\\nStep 1: Assist\\n\\nHuman prompts the AI, which then drafts content or uses tools, often with RAG. \\n\\nThe human retains control for execution. No autonomous ReACT cycle is completed by the AI.\\n\\nA single agent plans and acts across various tools based on a human-set goal. \\n\\nKey steps may require human approval, but the agent drives the workflow; execution can be by human or agent.\\n\\nMultiple agents collaborate with a specified orchestration method to achieve complex business outcomes. \\n\\nThis system leverages distributed intelligence for execution, with or without human intervention.\\n\\n\\n\\nAI agents demand deep integration and meticulous design \\n\\nWhile users often perceive the simple interface and outputs of an AI agent as the \\"tip of the iceberg,\\" a vast and complex infrastructure operates beneath the surface.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMost agent deployment failures stem from overestimating the simplicity and speed of reaching production. True value comes from meticulous design and robust integration.\\n\\nGoal and Scope\\n\\nUnder the surface, an agent's foundation includes:\\n\\nSophisticated model orchestration\\n\\nSeamless tool integration\\n\\nRobust safety systems \\n\\nContinuous monitoring \\n\\nSignificant operational complexity\\n\\nData and Knowledge\\n\\nAgent Tasks & Functions\\n\\nWorkflow & Orchestration\\n\\nModel & Tooling Strategy\\n\\nSecurity & Guardrails\\n\\nTesting & Observability\\n\\nDeployment & Scaling\\n\\nSuccess Metrics & ROI\\n\\n\\n\\nWhile complex, agentic AI unlocks new ways for organizations to attain value\\n\\nAgents excel where traditional rule-based automation fails to handle complex, ambiguous problems. Value-add can be found in scenarios that have:\\n\\nComplex Decision-Making\\n\\nDifficult-to-Maintain Rules\\n\\nHeavy Reliance on Unstructured Data\\n\\nWorkflows involving nuanced judgment, exceptions, or context-sensitive decisions.\\n\\nSystems that have become unwieldy due to extensive and intricate rulesets, making updates costly or error-prone.\\n\\nScenarios that involve interpreting natural language, extracting meaning from documents, or interacting with users conversationally.\\n\\nExample: Refund approval in customer service workflows\\n\\nExample: Performing vendor security reviews\\n\\nExample: Processing a home insurance claim\\n\\n\\n\\nAI is not the silver bullet for all use cases\\n\\nWhile agents offer powerful automation, they are not a universal solution. Consider these scenarios where agents may not be the optimal approach:\\n\\nSimple Tasks\\n\\nDeep Domain Expertise\\n\\nTight Budgets\\n\\nHuman Emotion & Creativity\\n\\nAgents are overkill for simple, efficient tasks with existing manual or software solutions.\\n\\nExample: Sending automated email notifications or basic data entry tasks.\\n\\nTasks requiring nuanced human judgment or specialized knowledge (e.g., medical diagnoses) are safer and higher quality with human experts.\\n\\nExample: Medical diagnosis or legal contract review requiring specialized knowledge.\\n\\nHigh development and operational costs of robust agents may outweigh benefits for projects with severe resource constraints.\\n\\nExample: Small-scale internal tools or one-time data processing tasks with limited funding.\\n\\nAgents cannot replicate human emotion, intuition, or creativity, essential for fields like psychotherapy or creative writing.\\n\\nExample: Psychotherapy sessions or composing original works of fiction.\\n\\n\\n\\nTo achieve value, define what \\"success\\" for AI agents looks like\\n\\nProject failure is guaranteed without clear, cross-functional alignment on what outcomes the organization wants the agent to achieve.\\n\\nA\\n\\nGoal\\n\\nMetrics\\n\\nGates\\n\\nLock the use case, audience, and non-negotiables (risk, privacy, compliance)\\n\\nSet prototype KPIs and target thresholds to prevent scope creep\\n\\nEstablish decision gates that move us from idea to prototype to pilot\\n\\n\\n\\nAs AI capabilities advance, so do the model's operational requirements\\n\\nThe lifecycle management of AI systems has evolved from traditional machine learning. With each evolution, new considerations for reliability, safety, and performance arise.\\n\\nFocuses on automating and standardizing the lifecycle of traditional ML models, from data ingestion and model training to deployment, monitoring, and governance.\\n\\nMLOps (Machine Learning Operations)\\n\\nExtends MLOps to address the unique challenges of generative models, including prompt engineering, fine-tuning, token management, and ensuring responsible AI outputs.\\n\\nGenAIOps (Generative AI Operations\\n\\nEmerges to manage LLM-powered agents through tool integration, dynamic orchestration, guardrails, and human-in-the-loop controls for autonomous systems.\\n\\nAgentOps (Agent Operations)\\n\\nImage: Evolution of operational practices from DevOps into the AI era\\n\\nSource: Agents Companion, Google, 2025\\n\\n\\n\\nControlled progression and operational monitoring is crucial to prevent \\"prototype drift\\" and project shutdown\\n\\nSuccess metrics for AI prototype launch should be tied to decision gates.\\n\\n3.\\n\\n1.\\n\\n2.\\n\\nGate DO: Ready to Prototype \\n\\nGate D1: Prototype Exit\\n\\nGate D2: Pilot Go/No Go \\n\\nKPI targets within tolerance\\n\\nRunbook drafted\\n\\nUse case, KPIs, scope signed\\n\\nSafety incidents = 0 critical\\n\\nMonitoring live\\n\\nData owners identified\\n\\nBudget on track\\n\\nHuman-in-the-loop defined\\n\\nRisk sign-off to build\\n\\nDemo approved\\n\\nRACI staffed\\n\\n\\n\\nSuitability Check for Agentic AI\\n\\nBefore investing in an LLM-powered agent, evaluate these criteria for optimal impact and successful deployment:\\n\\n1\\n\\n4\\n\\nTask Viability\\n\\nCompliance and Security\\n\\n01\\n\\n04\\n\\nIs the task frequent, high-volume, and complex enough for automation? Agents excel where rule-based systems falter due to ambiguity.\\n\\nAre there privacy, security, or regulatory requirements? Ensure the agent design incorporates safeguards and audit trails.\\n\\n2\\n\\n5\\n\\nAdaptability and Learning\\n\\nCost-Benefit Analysis\\n\\n02\\n\\n05\\n\\nDoes the task involve changing conditions the agent can learn from? Agents thrive in dynamic environments requiring continuous adaptation.\\n\\nDoes the agent's efficiency and ROI justify the investment? Quantify potential savings versus development and maintenance costs.\\n\\n3\\n\\n6\\n\\nPerformance Requirements\\n\\nScalability and Integration\\n\\n03\\n\\n06\\n\\nCan AI meet accuracy needs and handle nuanced judgment? Assess acceptable error rates and human oversight feasibility.\\n\\nCan the agent scale and integrate seamlessly with existing workflows? Consider the technical feasibility of deployment and maintenance.\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Problem statement, baselines, leadership priorities. Approved goals list Materials Participants Sticky notes/Miro, dot stickers, Executive Sponsor, Product Owner/PM, Finance/FinOps, Operations, CX/Service, Risk/Compliance.\\n\\n1.3 Set Business Goals\\n\\n30-45 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\n3\\u20135 business outcomes (value, efficiency, experience, risk/compliance).(Keep latency/accuracy/decision error out; those go to Success Criteria.)\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nIf we hit only these, is the pilot a win?\\n\\nWhich goals map to Finance/Ops/CX/Risk?\\n\\nWhat can we measure quickly during a limited pilot?\\n\\nAre any outcomes blocked by integrations we won't have?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   58\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Baseline metrics, observability tooling, capacity/finance constraints. Metrics table with targets & methods, explicit acceptance gate, metric owners. Materials Participants 4-column metrics grid; ownership matrix. PM/PO, AI/ML Lead, Engineering & SRE, Operations, Risk/Compliance, Finance/FinOps.\\n\\n1.5 Success Metrics & Acceptance Criteria\\n\\n45-60 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nMetric \\u2192 baseline \\u2192 target \\u2192 measurement method (offline set, A/B, live monitoring).\\n\\nSafety & quality gates; ship/no-ship acceptance criteria.\\n\\nMonitoring (dashboards, alerts, sampling) and owners.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nMinimum quality to launch a canary?\\n\\nHow will we detect drift/regressions quickly?\\n\\nWhich violations are P0 (block) vs P1 (warn)?\\n\\nWho owns each metric week-to-week during pilot?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   59\\n\\n\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo describe the solution in enough detail to demonstrate the human-technical interactions to business and technical stakeholders and gain buy-in for the human and technical elements of the solution.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA solution diagram depicting the human-technology interaction with details of the core human actions, technology functions, components, and experiences.\\n\\nNovel aspects of the solution do not need to be fully defined if the intended behavior is clearly understood. \\n\\nThe solution diagram should tell the story in one page.\\n\\nActivities \\n\\nMap out activities and functions with various stakeholders.\\n\\nDescribe specific workflow and/or priority use cases.\\n\\nBreak down the solution into technical components.\\n\\nDefine prototype scope and solution boundaries\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\n\\n\\nDevelop the human-technology story\\n\\nDocument the human-technology experience.\\n\\nBreak down the technical components.\\n\\nTell the human-technology story. \\n\\nMap out human activities and technology functions.\\n\\nList human activities involved in using the system.\\n\\nMap human activities to specific technology functions to describe how technology supports or enhances human activities. \\n\\nUse a flowchart or use cases (or other techniques) to describe the intended interactions between users and technology.\\n\\nInclude decision points, loops, and conditional paths that reflect human-technology interactions.\\n\\nBreak down technology into abstrac