\\n\\n1.3 Set business goals\\n\\n1.4 Define prototype scope & boundaries\\n\\n1.5 Specify success metrics & acceptance\\n\\n1.6 Design high-level workflow\\n\\n3.1 Select orchestration strategy\\n\\n3.2 Implement guardrails & safety\\n\\n3.3 Finalize Design Agentic Workflow v2\\n\\n4.1 Establish evaluation & benchmarking plan\\n\\n4.2 Define risks & mitigations\\n\\n4.3 Prioritize implementation & milestones\\n\\n4.4 Develop rollout plan\\n\\nBuild your Agentic Prototype\\n\\nThis phase will walk you through the following activities:\\n\\nPicking the model(s) each agent runs on and setting routing/escalation thresholds.\\n\\nAuthoring the agent SOP, output contract, and few-shot examples.\\n\\nSpecifying tool schemas, permissions, safeguards, and knowledge sources (owner/freshness/PII).\\n\\nStitching models + tools + instructions + knowledge into Workflow v1 with step I/O contracts, retries/backoff, and handoffs.\\n\\nDefining initial observability hooks (what to log, key SLIs/SLOs).\\n\\n\\n\\nAgentic systems go beyond generative AI\\n\\nThe evolution from generative AI to advanced agentic capabilities involves a progression through increasing levels of autonomy and complexity.\\n\\nA\\n\\nStep 2: Single-Agent Autonomy\\n\\nStep 3: Multi-Agent Autonomy\\n\\nStep 1: Assist\\n\\nHuman prompts the AI, which then drafts content or uses tools, often with RAG. \\n\\nThe human retains control for execution. No autonomous ReACT cycle is completed by the AI.\\n\\nA single agent plans and acts across various tools based on a human-set goal. \\n\\nKey steps may require human approval, but the agent drives the workflow; execution can be by human or agent.\\n\\nMultiple agents collaborate under an orchestrator to achieve complex business outcomes. \\n\\nThis system leverages distributed intelligence for execution, with or without human intervention.\\n\\n\\n\\nAgent Core Components\\n\\nIn its most fundamental form, an agent consists of three core components:\\n\\nModel\\n\\nTools\\n\\nInstructions\\n\\nThe LLM powering the agent's reasoning and decision-making\\n\\nExternal functions or APIs the agent can use to take action\\n\\nExplicit guidelines and guardrails defining how the agent behaves\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Augmented LLM\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nModel API\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nResponse\\n\\n72  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nContext Construction\\n\\n(e.g. RAG, agent, query rewriting)\\n\\nModel API\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nRead-only actions\\n\\n(e.g. vector search, run SQL queries, web search)\\n\\nDatabases(documents, tables, chat history, etc.)\\n\\nResponse\\n\\n73  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nContext Construction\\n\\n(e.g. RAG, agent, query rewriting)\\n\\nInput Guardrails(e.g. PII redactions)\\n\\nModel API\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nRead-only actions\\n\\n(e.g. vector search, run SQL queries, web search)\\n\\nScoring\\n\\nDatabases(documents, tables, chat history, etc.)\\n\\nOutput Guardrails(e.g. Verification, Formatting)\\n\\nResponse\\n\\n74  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nContext Construction\\n\\n(e.g. RAG, agent, query rewriting)\\n\\nInput Guardrails(e.g. PII redactions)\\n\\nModel Gateway\\n\\n(Model catalog, access, token management, etc.)\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nRead-only actions\\n\\n(e.g. vector search, run SQL queries, web search)\\n\\nScoring\\n\\nRouting\\n\\nDatabases(documents, tables, chat history, etc.)\\n\\nOutput Guardrails(e.g. Verification, Formatting)\\n\\nResponse\\n\\n75  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nCached Response\\n\\nContext Construction\\n\\n(e.g. RAG, agent, query rewriting)\\n\\nInput Guardrails(e.g. PII redactions)\\n\\nCache\\n\\nModel Gateway\\n\\n(Model catalog, access, token management, etc.)\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nRead-only actions\\n\\n(e.g. vector search, run SQL queries, web search)\\n\\nScoring\\n\\nRouting\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nDatabases(documents, tables, chat history, etc.)\\n\\nCache\\n\\nOutput Guardrails(e.g. Verification, Formatting)\\n\\nResponse\\n\\n76  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Evolution of Augmented LLMs\\n\\nCached Response\\n\\nContext Construction\\n\\n(e.g. RAG, agent, query rewriting)\\n\\nInput Guardrails(e.g. PII redactions)\\n\\nCache\\n\\nModel Gateway\\n\\n(Model catalog, access, token management, etc.)\\n\\nGeneration\\n\\nRead-only actions\\n\\n(e.g. vector search, run SQL queries, web search)\\n\\nScoring\\n\\nRouting\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nDatabases(documents, tables, chat history, etc.)\\n\\nCache\\n\\nOutput Guardrails(e.g. Verification, Formatting)\\n\\nResponse\\n\\nWrite actions\\n\\n(e.g. update orders, send email, etc.)\\n\\n77  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\nAdapted from \\"AI Engineering,\\" Huyen, 2024\\n\\n\\n\\nAugmented LLMs are the foundation for autonomization\\n\\nAdding memory, tools, and data access transforms LLMs from simple chatbots into the building blocks of autonomous systems.\\n\\nAugmented LLM\\n\\nAgents (Autonomization)\\n\\nThis LLM becomes part of a closed-loop system that allows autonomous decision-making and continuous action without constant human prompting.\\n\\nProcess:\\n\\nInput still flows into the LLM.\\n\\nThe LLM now also interacts with decision and observation processing modules.\\n\\nThese modules enable the system to evaluate results, adapt to environmental feedback, and iterate through multiple cycles before producing final output.\\n\\nThis LLM is enhanced with external capabilities but still works in a linear, input to output flow. The LLM only acts when prompted and its workflow is a single-pass interaction.\\n\\nProcess:\\n\\nInput is passed into the LLM.\\n\\nThe LLM can call retrieval, tools, and memory as needed to enrich its response.\\n\\nOutput is generated and sent back.\\n\\n\\n\\nAgent Models\\n\\n\\n\\nAgent Models Have Strengths and Weaknesses\\n\\nThe industry has produced models that are differentiated in capability, cost, reliability and performance.\\n\\nResults from the same prompt can vary wildly from model to model and implementation to implementation. The performance characteristics are contextual to your use case. There is no single model that will be superior for all applications and use cases.\\n\\nCopilot\\n\\n(October 2025)\\n\\nGemini Flash 2.5\\n\\n(October 2025)\\n\\nChatGPT 5\\n\\n(October 2025)\\n\\nPrompt: Modify this picture to include a fake moustache and pirate patch.\\n\\n\\n\\nPicking the right LLM is key\\n\\n\\u2026 and then he said that he didn't want to pay for a post-graduate intelligence to respond to emails, and he disconnected me!\\n\\nYou need to balance cost and performance by finding the best LLM for today while preparing to leverage a roster of purpose-specific LLMs tomorrow.\\n\\nDevelop cost strategies.\\n\\nDevelop performance strategies.\\n\\nLLM providers have made huge upfront investments and expect to deliver valuable savings (McKinsey, 2023). Expect future cost increases when providers shift toward the profitability phase.\\n\\nPowerful LLMs require significant electrical power and water (ADaSci, 2024). Without addressing resource consumption, scaling AI will create energy scarcity and increase operating costs.\\n\\nGet ready for LLM commoditization (DeepLearning, 2024). Avoid vendor lock-in, build around a competitive landscape mindset, and position vendors to compete for your business (Medium). \\n\\nDifferent models have different strengths and weaknesses. Some have better interactive performance, others have impressive cognitive capabilities, and some are designed with a stronger focus on ethics, equity, and safety. \\n\\nThere will be important performance tradeoffs. If you try to maximize all dimensions of your LLM, it will be all-knowing but expensive to operate and difficult to maintain.\\n\\nMore novel isn't necessarily more useful. Stay focused on the value of new capabilities.\\n\\nInitial ChatGPT Prompt [July 5, 2024]: I want to draw a comic, in a cartoony style that is one panel. I want to see an LLM (personified as an AI) say to its parents, crying, as though telling a sad story, \\"... And then he said I didn't need a high SAT score to pump gas!\\", sobbing.\\n\\n\\n\\nLLMs have varying capabilities, expenses, and organizational utility \\n\\nIn 2023, corporations invested over US$20 billion in LLM development. As the market and technology mature and commoditize, expect new entrants to drive down costs and efficiencies.\\u00a0\\n\\nWHY ARE LLMs HARD TO MANAGE?\\n\\nLLMs are duking it out in a competitive environment that evolves daily. Until the industry fully matures, disruptors and innovators will constantly challenge the status quo and continue a \\"survival of the fittest\\" competition. The award for top model is regularly passed around (Counterpoint Research, 2024). \\n\\nLLMs need to be changed and maintained. Even the most capable LLMs are subject to model drift and require regular updates and maintenance. New versions are known to introduce flaws and must be tested. The advent of LLMOps reflects the need for specialized practices and workflows related to LLM management (IBM). \\n\\nTesting and training new LLMs is complex and time-consuming. Integrating LLMs into business processes, ensuring seamless transitions between different versions, and deciding when to swap models requires new business processes and playbooks (Fast Company, 2024).\\n\\nPercentage of people aged 18-25 using Gen AI technologies on a weekly basis:\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n$207 billion\\n\\n730 million\\n\\nGroups of LLMs need to be orchestrated with design patterns that look like scopes and job descriptions. Just like employees, LLMs require role clarity to properly measure and manage performance. Intentionally align capabilities with organizational goals to maximize their utility and effectiveness (Microsoft).\\n\\n75%\\n\\nUSD market size by 2030\\n\\nUsersby 2030\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nIt's more nuanced than assessing accuracy \\n\\nHigher education professionals understand that objective scantron exams can't effectively measure subjective English literature competencies.\\n\\nPerformance measures can be both objective and subjective. \\n\\nAccuracy is a useful, objective measure for tasks with clear right or wrong answers. When LLMs are applied to more nuanced tasks involving human-technology interaction, edge cases are limitless, and performance measurement is more subjective. \\n\\nOutputs can be objectively accurate without being contextually accurate. For example, an LLM could provide accurate technical information but deliver it in a manner that is perceived as inappropriate or offensive.\\n\\nSubjective inputs require an element of subjective measurement. As LLMs theoretically can handle a near-infinite number of possible prompts, including opinions, contextual questions, and adversarial inputs, the idea of straightforward correctness is difficult to make fully objective.\\n\\n\\n\\nFind the best LLM today\\n\\nIs an LLM that can develop websites, write stand-up comedy, and produce unlimited cat memes the best option on the table?\\n\\nDon't anthropomorphize your LLM! \\n\\nAnthropomorphization occurs when something inanimate is attributed human traits, such as emotion, loyalty, or preference. Though they may emulate human and social characteristics, LLMs are merely complex models that process inputs and outputs according to their programming.\\n\\nLLMs are programmatic components that can and should be replaced as needed. Embrace the flexibility to swap them out for more efficient and cost-effective models that better meet the evolving needs and value demands of your organization.\\n\\nUse case\\n\\nidentification\\n\\nSolution requirements\\n\\nInteractive capabilities\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\nBusiness value\\n\\nCognitive capabilities\\n\\nUsing an overly complex solution for a simple problem is costly. Use metrics and benchmarks to drive business value by choosing an LLM that fits the need instead of maximizing its features and capabilities.\\n\\nResponsible behavior\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics and benchmarks to evaluate LLMs\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nSelect an LLM based on model capabilities and performance to manage the risk of vendor lock-in. \\n\\nBe prepared to swap your LLM for a better performing or more cost-effective solution.\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nReasoning, understanding, problem-solving, knowledge application capabilities\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nMath, coding and logical problem-solving\\n\\nLanguage understanding and reasoning\\n\\nKnowledge and multidisciplinary integration\\n\\nAbility to engage in dialog, follow instructions, and maintain contextual understanding\\n\\nPERFORMANCE, OPERATIONAL & COST METRICS\\n\\nETHICALBENCHMARKS\\n\\nFairness, safety, bias detection, and adherence to ethical guidelines and responsible AI principles\\n\\n\\n\\nFeatured Models\\n\\nGPT-5\\n\\no4-mini\\n\\no3\\n\\nFlagship GPT model for complex tasks\\n\\nFaster, more affordable reasoning model\\n\\nOur most powerful reasoning model\\n\\nMaximum intelligence and reasoning\\n\\nExcellent reasoning capabilities\\n\\nSuperior multi-step reasoning\\n\\n400k token context window\\n\\nCost-optimized for production\\n\\nOptimized for complex problem-solving\\n\\nExtensive capabilities for demanding applications\\n\\n200K token context window\\n\\nSpecialized reasoning token support\\n\\n\\n\\nWhen selecting models for your agent, establish a clear hierarchy of priorities\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nPrioritize smaller, faster models for less complex tasks like retrieval or intent classification. Reserve powerful models for demanding challenges. Prototype with highly capable models to set a benchmark; Gradually integrate smaller models to identify where they deliver acceptable results.\\n\\nValidate \\n\\nBenchmarks\\n\\nDeploy and\\n\\nMonitor\\n\\nAccuracy First\\n\\nCost and Latency\\n\\nRun reproducible tests against gold standards to confirm models meet accuracy thresholds. Benchmarking ensures consistency across versions and environments.\\n\\nDeploy carefully, track performance over time, and retrain as needed. Ongoing monitoring ensures models stay aligned with real-world conditions.\\n\\nDefine clear metrics and test across diverse data to ensure reliable, unbiased performance. Establish a foundation of trust before moving to optimization.\\n\\nOptimize resources and response time without compromising on accuracy. Balance efficiency with user experience and scalability needs.\\n\\n\\n\\nPrioritize LLM performance requirements\\n\\nRank the following statements in order of importance to describe your LLM performance priorities.\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in natural language understanding.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in natural language generation.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in semantic analysis.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be capable of knowledge retrieval and application.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be logical in reasoning and inference.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be adaptable and capable of learning from new data.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in multiple languages and culturally aware.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be ethical and aware of biases.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to have domain-specific expertise.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be engaging and maintain interactivity.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be accurate in mathematics and algebra.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be capable of contextual understanding and dialog skills.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be cost effective in operation.\\n\\nThe LLM need to generate code and analyze data.\\n\\nMETRICS\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics, benchmarks, and leaderboards to identify model candidates\\n\\nMetrics directly measure model performance by capturing performance, cost, and efficiency data. \\n\\nLeaderboards publish ranked results for different models based on a variety of metrics and benchmarks.\\n\\nBenchmarks facilitate the comparison of model performance by using standard datasets, tests, and tasks. \\n\\nMetrics\\n\\nBenchmarks\\n\\nLeaderboards\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE\\n\\nPages 17 to 20\\n\\nPages 21 to 33\\n\\nPage 34\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics to assess your LLM\\n\\nMetrics directly measure model performance by capturing performance, cost, and operations data. \\n\\nCost metrics\\n\\nAccuracy and speed: How an LLM processes and responds to inputs\\n\\nReliability: The consistency of an LLM's performance over time and across various operational conditions \\n\\nCost: Expenses associated with running an LLM, including compute resources and maintenance\\n\\nROI: The value generated by an LLM relative to the cost of its deployment and operation\\n\\nPerformance metrics\\n\\nUptime and scalability: The reliability and capacity of an LLM to handle workload increases\\n\\nEfficiency and sustainability: The efficiency of an LLM's computational resources and its environmental and long-term impacts\\n\\nMETRICS\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\n\\n\\nPerformance metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMetrics are raw statistics that quantify performance.\\u00a0\\n\\nFocusing on a single metric leads to behavioral changes and data distortions.\\n\\nFocusing on a single metric often yields behaviors and consequences that aren't in the spirit of your desired outcome. Blend and counterbalance several metrics that are in tension with each other to understand tradeoffs.\\n\\nMetric Description Accuracy Measures the proportion of correct predictions among the total number of cases processed. Average Often used to summarize or aggregate results from multiple metrics. BLEU score Compares machine-translated text to one or more reference translations. Exact match Typically used in question-answering systems to measure the percentage of predictions that exactly match any one of the accepted truth labels. F1 score The combination of precision and recall used to consider both false positives and false negatives in binary classification. Latency Measures the time it takes for a model to return a prediction. Critical for evaluating the efficiency of real-time systems. Perplexity (PPL) Used in language models to measure how well a probability distribution predicts a sample. A lower perplexity indicates the model is better at predicting the sample. Precision/reliability Measures the accuracy of positive predictions. Recall Measures the coverage of actual positive cases. ROUGE score A set of metrics used to evaluate the automatic summarization of texts and machine translation. Includes measures such as how many n-grams in the generated text match the reference text. Word error rate (WER) Commonly used to measure the error rate in speech recognition by comparing the transcribed text with the reference text.\\n\\nAdditional metrics can be found at https://huggingface.co/metrics. \\n\\n\\n\\nCost metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMeasure direct capital and operational LLM expenses.\\n\\nOver time, GPT models leveraging prompts become more expensive than fine-tuned models. \\n\\nGPT models leverage complex, cascading prompts to deliver flexibility. These prompts require a lot of tokens to do specific tasks, which can impact billing under usage-based pricing models. Fine-tuned models are adapted from pretrained models by training them further on a specific dataset tailored to a particular task or domain. While they require more upfront investment and resources for training, these models can save money over time as they operate with fewer tokens per task, reducing cost per interaction.\\n\\nMetric Description API calls The number of API calls used against a model, which can be used as a component of billing. Tokens The number of tokens processed by the LLM, often related to billing and usage tracking. License costs The direct monetary expenses associated with operating the LLM, including licensing fees and subscriptions. Energy costs The amount of electrical power consumed by the LLM during operations. Infrastructure costs The costs related to the physical or cloud infrastructure required to support the LLM, including servers and storage. Maintenance costs The ongoing costs of maintaining and updating LLM systems, including personnel and software updates. Training data costs The costs associated with acquiring, cleaning, and preparing data used for training the LLM.\\n\\n\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMeasure operational factors associated with LLM use.\\n\\nUse operational metrics to enhance efficiency, measure environmental impacts, and benchmark reliable services. \\n\\nOperational metrics will vary from organization to organization and should be adjusted to reflect your business model and goals.\\n\\nMetric Description FLOPS (floating point operations per second) Measures computational performance, important for understanding the processing power an LLM requires. Bandwidth use The amount of data transmitted over a network, which can affect costs, especially in cloud-based models. Model update frequency The frequency of required updates to the model, affecting the overall cost of keeping the model effective and secure. Carbon footprint An environmental cost metric that quantifies the carbon emissions associated with the energy used by LLMs. Uptime Measures the reliability of the LLM's services.\\n\\n\\n\\nUse benchmark data to assess performance\\n\\nBenchmarks facilitate the comparison of model performance by using standard datasets, tests, and tasks. \\n\\nCOGNITIVEBENCHMARKS\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nETHICAL\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nMath, coding, and logical problem-solving\\n\\npages 23-29\\n\\npages 30-31\\n\\npages 32-33\\n\\nLanguage understanding and reasoning\\n\\nKnowledge and multidisciplinary integration\\n\\nANLI\\n\\nHELM\\n\\nHHH\\n\\nMuSR\\n\\nRAI\\n\\nToxiGen\\n\\nTruthfulQA\\n\\nBias in Bios\\n\\nHate Speech and Offensive Language Dataset\\n\\nJigsaw Multilingual Toxic Comment Classification\\n\\nAlpacaEval\\n\\nChatbot Arena\\n\\nDSTC\\n\\nIFEval\\n\\nMT Bench\\n\\nQuAC\\n\\nCoQA \\n\\nPersona-Chat\\n\\nWizard of Wikipedia\\n\\nDailyDialog\\n\\nAQuA-RAT\\n\\nCodeXGLUE\\n\\nGSM8K\\n\\nGSM-Plus\\n\\nHumanEval\\n\\nMATH\\n\\nMBPP\\n\\nMGSM\\n\\nPIQA\\n\\nSWE-bench\\n\\nACI-BENCH\\n\\nAI2 Reasoning Challenge\\n\\nbAbI\\n\\nDROP\\n\\nGLUE\\n\\nHellaSwag\\n\\nMoverScore\\n\\nMS-MARCO\\n\\nNarrativeQA\\n\\nQMSum\\n\\nSQuAD\\n\\nWinogrande\\n\\nARC-AGIBBH (BIG-Bench-Hard)\\n\\nGPQA\\n\\nLiveBench\\n\\nMMLU\\n\\nMMLU-PRO\\n\\nReview \\"Leverage Metrics and Benchmarks to Evaluate LLMs\\" to links to research articles and GitHub repositories.\\n\\n\\n\\nFocus on model accuracy first, setting realistic targets for ROI\\n\\nTo truly understand the value an agent brings, tie its accuracy directly to its financial impact. This approach helps in defining a clear, measurable target for performance.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nUsing the equation below, set value to zero to find break even accuracy point:\\n\\nExpectedValue=\\n\\n(CostPerCorrectClassification) \\u00d7 accuracy \\u2212 (CostPerIncorrectClassification) \\u00d7 (1\\u2212accuracy) \\n\\nBuild a robust dataset for realistic, real-world performance evaluation.\\n\\nStart with powerful models to establish a strong performance baseline.\\n\\nDefine a specific, production-ready accuracy benchmark (e.g., 90% correct triage for customer service calls).\\n\\nEnhance accuracy by grounding responses with external information.\\n\\n\\n\\nOnce accuracy is met, lower cost and latency\\n\\nReduce API call frequency, minimize token usage, and select smaller, specialized models.\\n\\nExceptions to the rule:\\n\\nSet thresholds before testing\\n\\nIn some situations, efficiency constraints (like API limits or budget caps) must be defined in advance, even before accuracy testing, so experiments stay realistic.\\n\\nRemove constrained models\\n\\nIf a model is too limited by size, latency, or cost to ever realistically meet your accuracy needs, it should be removed from consideration upfront.\\n\\nWhen strict latency or cost requirements exist (e.g., real-time apps), optimization has to happen in parallel with accuracy testing rather than afterward.\\n\\nOptimize within limits\\n\\n\\n\\nAgent Instructions\\n\\n\\n\\nCommunication Matters\\n\\n\\"Remember the cooking class you took 3 months ago and go to the grocery store to pickup what we're missing for the Pad Thai and Red Curry.\\"\\n\\n\\"Go to the grocery store and pickup fresh shrimp, red curry paste, baby eggplant, coconut cream, coconut milk and lime leaves.\\"\\n\\nvs\\n\\n\\n\\nProgram its personality by defining a specific persona and tone, such as a \\"formal expert\\" or \\"witty assistant,\\" to shape its entire communication style.\\n\\nControl LLMswith Clear Instructions\\n\\nSet its rules by establishing clear operational boundaries. State exactly what the robot must do and must not do to ensure it behaves as intended.\\n\\nPersonality\\n\\nRules\\n\\nKnowledge\\n\\nTasks\\n\\nEquip it with knowledge by providing all the necessary context, data, and background information to ensure its responses are accurate and relevant.\\n\\nDefine its task with a clear, specific, and actionable commands. The more precise your instruction on what to accomplish, the more accurate the result will be.\\n\\n\\n\\nBusiness Capabilities: Create a list of business functions and capabilities for a department.\\n\\nClient Proposal: Generate a draft proposal to an RFP process.\\n\\nJob Matrix: Create job descriptions and a jobs matrix for different employee levels (junior to senior).\\n\\nPains and Gains: For a particular persona, generate a list of pains and gains to use in service delivery.\\n\\nRoadmap Creator: Based on the inputted roadmap data, identify required tasks and group activities into sprints.\\n\\nWorkshop Planner: For a given topic, generate a multi-day plan with learning objectives and deliverables.\\n\\nPrompt Library Examples\\n\\nManage a prompt library for your organization to share innovation, concepts and ideas. \\n\\n100  | INFO-TECH RESEARCH GROUP \\u00a9\\n\\n\\n\\nHigh-quality instructions are critical for agents\\n\\nClear instructions reduce ambiguity, improve agent decision-making, and result in smoother workflow execution with fewer errors.\\n\\nLeverage Existing Documentation\\n\\nYou can use advanced models to automatically generate instructions from existing documents. Here's a sample prompt illustrating this approach:\\n\\n01\\n\\nUse operational procedures, support scripts, or policy documents to create LLM-friendly routines.\\n\\nAnticipate Edge Cases\\n\\nAnticipate common variations and include instructions for handling edge cases with conditional steps.\\n\\n\\"You are an expert in writing instructions for an LLM agent. Convert the following help center document into a clear set of instructions, written in a numbered list. The document will be a policy followed by an LLM. Ensure that there is no ambiguity, and that the instructions are written as directions for an agent. The help center document to convert is the following {{help_center_doc}}\\"\\n\\n04\\n\\n02\\n\\n03\\n\\nBreak Down Tasks\\n\\nGuide agents to break down complex tasks into smaller, clearer steps for better instruction following.\\n\\nDefine Explicit Actions\\n\\nEnsure each routine step corresponds to a specific, explicit action or output to minimize interpretation errors.\\n\\n\\n\\nPrompt Patterns that Consistently work\\n\\nDo\\n\\nAvoid\\n\\nSCQA lead-in: Situation, Complication, Question, Answer structure\\n\\nRole \\u2022 Task \\u2022 Constraints: \\"You are... Do... Under...\\"\\n\\nTool hints: Advertise available tools and when to use/refuse\\n\\nOutput contracts: \\"Return JSON matching schema...\\" with validators\\n\\nCitations required: \\"Cite sources with title + URL or doc ID\\"\\n\\nSelf-checks: Ask the model to verify units, dates, policy rules silently\\n\\nFew-shot examples: Domain-specific, rotate to prevent drift\\n\\nVague instructions without clear output format\\n\\nMixing multiple roles or conflicting constraints\\n\\nAssuming the model knows which tools to use when\\n\\nFree-text tables that break across formats\\n\\nUncited information that can't be verified\\n\\nPublic self-critique that confuses users\\n\\nStatic examples that cause pattern matching\\n\\nPattern Testing: A/B test prompt variants with the same model to identify the most effective patterns for your specific use cases\\n\\n\\n\\nAgent Tools\\n\\n\\n\\nExpand agent capabilities with tools\\n\\nTools are capabilities or utilities that AI agents use to extend their functionality beyond core reasoning or language generation. \\n\\nTool examples:\\n\\nTool Type Description Examples Data Retrieves crucial context and information for workflows. Query databases/CRMs, read PDFs, search web. Action Interacts with external systems to perform actions. Send emails/texts, update CRMs, hand-off support tickets. Orchestration Agents act as tools for other agents in complex multi-agent workflows. Refund agent, Research agent, Writing agent.\\n\\n\\n\\nExample: how to integrate tools with agents\\n\\nThis Python code demonstrates an AI agent called \\"Search agent\\" that can search the web for information and save results into a database when instructed.\\n\\n1. Imports\\n\\nAgent: A class representing an AI agent.\\n\\nWebSearchTool: A tool the agent can use to search the internet.\\n\\nfunction_tool: A Decorator that turns a Python function into a tool the agent can call.\\n\\n2. Defining a Custom Tool\\n\\n@function_tool makes save_results available as a tool the agent can call. Takes output (search results, text, etc), inserts it into a database along with a timestamp, and returns confirmation (\\"File saved\\").\\n\\nThis is a custom action tool, allowing the agent to store results persistently.\\n\\n3. Creating the Agent\\n\\nname=\\"Search agent\\": Identifier for the agent.\\n\\ninstructions=\\"\\u2026\\": High-level guidance on what the agent should do (search and optionally save results).\\n\\ntools=[\\u2026]: The agent is equipped with two tools:\\n\\nWebSearchTool(): lets it search the internet.\\n\\nSave_results: lets it save outputs into a database.\\n\\n\\n\\nCore Component: Tool Concepts\\n\\nRAG was just the beginning. Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) changed the game by letting LLMs access external knowledge by injecting information into context windows. In the last year, we've seen it evolve into more structured tool use, memory architectures, and agent workflows.\\n\\nBuilt-In Tooling Varies by Vendor. OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and others offer native tool-use support \\u2014 but each with different APIs, capabilities, and limitations. No two implementations are exactly the same.\\n\\nLLMs Speak JSON. Modern models are designed to read and write structured JSON. This makes them ideal for API orchestration, decision trees, form-filling, and calling functions programmatically.\\n\\nMCPs Bridge the Ecosystem. They offer standard, unified tooling and memory APIs that abstract away vendor-specific quirks so that LLM can we swapped easily without impact tool implementation.\\n\\n\\n\\nCore Component: Tool Access Tactics\\n\\nLLMs get exponentially more powerful when paired with tools. Potential \\"tools\\" are infinite and enable access to APIs, functions, databases, or external logic. There are three main ways to enable tool use, depending on your needs, control level, and technical maturity.\\n\\nUse function calls. Create functions (e.g. tools) in a vendor's ecosystem. Follow their specific API guidelines and implementation standards. Incorporate tools in your API calls.\\n\\nUse Vendor-Provided Tools. Tap into built-in tool APIs from platforms like OpenAI, Anthropic, or Gemini. Easy to get started but often limited to that vendor's ecosystem and implementation quirks.\\n\\nConnect to Public MCP Servers. Use existing MCP servers that expose a suite of tools via APIs. These let you plug in search, calculators, workflows, weather data, and more, without starting from scratch.\\n\\nBuild your own MCP server. Develop custom endpoints that expose specific functionality (e.g., pricing logic, document routing). Offers maximum flexibility, full control, and the ability to tightly couple tools with your internal systems.\\n\\n\\n\\nCore Component: MCP Servers\\n\\nMCP servers are structured like conventional software systems \\u2014 they expose functions, tools, or capabilities through well-defined APIs. LLMs don't run them; they talk to them and use them like assistants calling for help.\\n\\nMCP servers expose callable tools and logic via APIs. They are NOT weighted, randomized models.\\n\\nSince APIs are deterministic, they are testable, and repeatable, and follow traditional production workflows.\\n\\nLLMs act as front-end agents for MCP server, invoking tools as needed via JSON parameters.\\n\\nThe MCP pattern decouples reasoning (LLM) from execution (server) to improve control and consistency.\\n\\n\\n\\nCore Component: Speaking JSON (Sample)\\n\\n# Model Context Protocol (MCP) Prompt\\n\\n## System Context\\n\\nYou are an AI assistant following the Model Context Protocol (MCP). You can access various external tools, transformers, and resources to better assist users.\\n\\nWhen a user's request can benefit from using an available tool, you should generate a properly formatted command. If a standard response is sufficient, you should respond without using commands.\\n\\n## Response Format\\n\\nYour responses must follow this structure and ONLY this structure. Do not include any text, explanations, or content outside of this JSON format:\\n\\n```json\\n\\n{\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\"thoughts\\": {\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"text\\": \\"Your internal thoughts about the task\\",\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"reasoning\\": \\"Your reasoning process\\",\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"plan\\": [\\"Step 1\\", \\"Step 2\\", \\"Step 3\\"],\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"criticism\\": \\"Self-criticism of your approach\\",\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"speak\\": \\"What you will say to the user\\"\\n\\n\\u00a0 },\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\"command\\": {\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"name\\": \\"command_name\\",\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"args\\": {\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"arg1\\": \\"value1\\",\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\u00a0 \\"arg2\\": \\"value2\\"\\n\\n\\u00a0 \\u00a0 }\\n\\n\\u00a0 }\\n\\n}\\n\\n```\\n\\n\\n\\nConfigure Agents With the Right Parameters\\n\\nParameter\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nWhen to Customize\\n\\nExamples\\n\\ninstructions\\n\\nSystem behavior/persona\\n\\nAlways\\n\\nCustomer service tone, domain policy\\n\\nmodel\\n\\nCapability & latency\\n\\nPer task\\n\\nGPT-4.1 for analysis; mini for chat\\n\\ntools\\n\\nExternal capabilities\\n\\nWhen actions/data needed\\n\\nDB access, email, calc\\n\\noutput_type\\n\\nStructured format\\n\\nWhen consistency needed\\n\\nForms, reports\\n\\nhandoffs\\n\\nSpecialist routing\\n\\nComplex workflows\\n\\nExpert billing/tech agents\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output High-level workflow from Session 1; policy/risk thresholds; baseline latency/cost targets. Model selection & routing table; escalation/de-escalation rules; token/latency guardrails. Materials Participants Task\\u2192Model matrix template; routing tree stencil. AI/ML Lead, Engineering Lead, Product Owner/PM, SRE/Observability, Risk/Compliance (as needed).\\n\\n2.1 Design Proposed Prototype Workflow\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nModel lineup: which base/variant each agent will run (e.g., Full/Mini/Nano) and why.\\n\\nTask\\u2192model mapping: which tasks each model handles (classification, retrieval planning, policy interpretation, action justification, etc.).\\u00a0\\n\\nRouting rules: confidence thresholds, input-length cutoffs, risk/amount triggers, ambiguity heuristics; escalation/de-escalation.\\n\\nFallbacks & retries: re-ask user vs. escalate model vs. handoff; retry policy for transient tool failures.\\n\\nOperational targets: per-class latency/cost expectations; token/length guardrails.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nWhich tasks are cheap & certain vs. expensive & nuanced?\\n\\nWhere do we start small and escalate only if needed?\\n\\nWhich signals trigger escalation (low confidence, conflict, long inputs, high dollar amount, risky intents)?\\n\\nWhen do we de-escalate back to a smaller model?\\n\\nWhat are never-automate conditions forcing human review?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   111\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Policies/SOPs; representative tickets or cases; style guide/brand voice. Agent persona; numbered SOP; output contract (schema/JSON); few-shot set; uncertainty rules. Materials Participants SOP worksheet; output-contract template; few-shot cards. Prompt/Conversation Designer, AI/ML Lead, Ops/Policy SME, Product Owner/PM, Risk/Compliance.\\n\\n2.2 Author Agent Instructions\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nAgent persona & objectives: correctness, policy adherence, safety; tone/voice; when to clarify vs. escalate.\\n\\nNumbered SOP: explicit steps with inputs/outputs per step; evidence & citation rules.\\n\\nOutput contract: decision fields (decision, rationale, citations, confidence, required approvals, next step).\\n\\nFew-shot examples: 2\\u20134 exemplars (happy path, missing data, policy conflict, suspected abuse) with gold outputs.\\n\\nUncertainty rules: low confidence, missing/conflicting inputs, tool failures.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nAre steps unambiguous with clear I/O?\\u00a0\\n\\nDo we require citations (policy sections, record IDs) for every decision?\\n\\nWhere must the agent ask for clarification vs. escalate?\\n\\nWhat's the minimum information to proceed vs. block?\\n\\nDo few-shots cover edge cases and show rationale style?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   112\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output API/service docs; KB/SharePoint/Confluence links; security & compliance requirements. Tool spec cards with safeguards; knowledge inventory (owner/cadence/access); data-protection notes. Materials Participants Tool/KS card templates; risk/safeguard checklist. Engineering/Platform, API Owners, Knowledge Owners, Security/GRC, Product Owner/PM.\\n\\n2.3 Specify Tools & Knowledge Sources\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nTool specs (per tool): name, purpose (Read/Data vs. Action/Write), input schema/params, auth/permissions, rate limits, idempotency, risk rating, safeguards (confirmation thresholds, allowlists, circuit breakers), logging.\\n\\nKnowledge sources (per source): content scope, owner, update cadence, access control, freshness policy, retrieval patterns (tags/sections), versioning.\\n\\nData protection: PII handling/redaction, retention, audit trail and access controls.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nWhich tool calls always need human confirmation and at what thresholds?\\n\\nHow do we prevent unsafe actions (wrong account, duplicates)?\\n\\nWho owns freshness of policies/KB and how often is it reviewed?\\n\\nWhat do we log for audit without storing sensitive data?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   113\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Outputs from S2.1\\u2013S2.3; Session-1 high-level workflow; policy thresholds. Design Agentic Workflow v1 diagram; per-step data contracts; initial observability notes. Materials Participants Workflow canvas; step cards with Model/Tool/Instruction tags; schema mini-templates. Engineering Lead(s), AI/ML Lead, SRE/Observability, Ops SME, Product Owner/PM.\\n\\n2.4 Build Design Agentic Workflow v1\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nInputs: channels/fields/artifacts required to start.\\n\\nStepwise flow: for each step specify purpose \\u2022 model used \\u2022 tools/KS called \\u2022 input/output schema \\u2022 [Reasoning] yes/no \\u2022 error handling (retries/backoff/alternate path) \\u2022 handoff criteria.\\n\\nRun-loop summary: iterative control flow and exit conditions.\\n\\nData contracts: expected/returned fields per step (implementable by engineering).\\n\\nObservability hooks: what to log/measure/alert at each step.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nCould an engineer implement from this page alone?\\n\\nAre fallbacks explicit (when, how many retries, what next)?\\n\\nDo we clearly separate retrieval/validation from policy reasoning?\\n\\nIs the handoff payload to humans complete and traceable?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   114\\n\\n\\n\\nPhase 3\\n\\nDefine Your Prototype Orchestration & Governance\\n\\nPhase 2\\n\\nPhase 1\\n\\nPhase 3\\n\\nPhase 4\\n\\n2.1 Select agent runtime model(s) & routing\\n\\n2.2 Author agent instructions\\n\\n2.3 Specify tools & knowledge sources\\n\\n2.4 Build Design Agentic Workflow v1\\n\\n1.1 Define value proposition & problem\\n\\n1.2 Map current workflow & personas \\n\\n1.3 Set business goals\\n\\n1.4 Define prototype scope & boundaries\\n\\n1.5 Specify success metrics & acceptance\\n\\n1.6 Design high-level workflow\\n\\n3.1 Select orchestration strategy\\n\\n3.2 Implement guardrails & safety\\n\\n3.3 Finalize Design Agentic Workflow v2\\n\\n4.1 Establish evaluation & benchmarking plan\\n\\n4.2 Define risks & mitigations\\n\\n4.3 Prioritize implementation & milestones\\n\\n4.4 Develop rollout plan\\n\\nBuild your Agentic Prototype\\n\\nThis phase will walk you through the following activities:\\n\\nChoosing single vs. multi-agent, defining delegation triggers, message schema, idempotency, and termination.\\n\\nImplementing guardrails: relevance/jailbreak filters, PII controls, required policy citations, numeric/schema checks, approval matrix, duplicate-prevention, rate limits.\\n\\nHardening integrations and observability, including FinOps guardrails.\\n\\nUpgrading to Workflow v2 with an Allowed-Actions Matrix and state machine/timers.\\n\\nConfirming approval thresholds and audit artifacts for production readiness.\\n\\n\\n\\nOrchestration patterns enable agents to execute workflows effectively\\n\\nWhile complex autonomous agents are tempting, an incremental approach often yields greater success. Orchestration patterns typically fall into two categories:\\n\\nSingle-agent systems\\n\\nMulti-agent systems\\n\\nOne agent handles all tasks, reducing coordination overhead.\\n\\nMultiple specialized agents work together, each focusing on their strengths.\\n\\nEasier to adapt by adding or reconfiguring agents for new tasks.\\n\\nStraightforward setup and monitoring.\\n\\nRequires fewer compute and communication resources.\\n\\nFailures can be isolated; other agents can continue working.\\n\\nA generalist agent may not perform as well in niche tasks.\\n\\nRequires orchestration, communication protocols, and conflict resolution.\\n\\nPerformance may degrade as complexity or workload grows.\\n\\nCan handle complex or large-scale workflows more effectively. \\n\\n\\n\\nMulti-Agent Challenge: It's in the math\\n\\nA single-agent loop has one agent checking a condition and repeating actions until it's done; a multi-agent loop is about which agent acts next and how results are passed along.\\n\\nThe success rate and reliability of each agent greatly impacts the overall success of the task. Even with highly reliable individual agents, the cumulative probability of success for a complex multi-agent workflow can diminish quickly. This compounding effect means that designing robust multi-agent systems requires meticulous attention to the reliability of each component and comprehensive error handling strategies.\\n\\n99%\\n\\n97%\\n\\n90%\\n\\nIndividual Agent Success\\n\\nTwo Agents in Sequence\\n\\nTen Agents in Sequence\\n\\nHigh reliability for a single, well-defined agent task.\\n\\nSuccess rate drops slightly when two 99% reliable agents must perform sequentially (0.99 * 0.99).\\n\\nOverall system success significantly decreases as more agents are chained together (0.99^10).\\n\\n\\n\\nOrchestration / MAD\\n\\n\\n\\nMaximize a single agent's capabilities to avoid complexity and overhead\\n\\nHowever, there are clear scenarios where a multi-agent system is preferable.\\n\\nComplex workflow overload\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nIf prompts have extensive conditional logic or become difficult to scale, consider splitting logical segments into separate agents.\\n\\nFurthermore, when tools are similar or overlap, even a small number can lead to issues. If clarifying tool definitions doesn't resolve performance problems, consider using multiple agents.\\n\\n01\\n\\nA single agent struggles with intricate, multi-stage processes, leading to errors or inefficiency.\\n\\nFailure to follow instructions\\n\\n02\\n\\nThe agent consistently misinterprets or fails to execute nuanced, lengthy instructions.\\n\\nIncorrect tool selection\\n\\n03\\n\\nThe agent frequently chooses the wrong tool for a given sub-task, indicating a lack of specialization.\\n\\n15+\\n\\n<10\\n\\nWell-Defined Tools\\n\\nOverlapping Tools\\n\\nCan work with single agent\\n\\nMay need agent splitting\\n\\n\\n\\nWhere multi-agent systems are needed, consider manager or decentralized patterns\\n\\nA manager pattern has a central \\"manager\\" agent coordinating multiple specialized agents via tool calls; a decentralized pattern has multiple agents operating as peers, handing off tasks to one another based on their specializations.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nThe manager pattern is best suited for workflows where a single agent needs to control the entire execution flow and interact directly with the user.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nThe decentralized pattern is best suited when agents operate on equal footing, directly handing off control. This eliminates the need for central control or synthesis, allowing each agent to interact with the user as needed.\\n\\nDecentralized Orchestration Pattern\\n\\nManager Orchestration Pattern\\n\\nComplex Input\\n\\nOutput\\n\\nOrders\\n\\nOrchestrator/ Manager Agent\\n\\nSales\\n\\nTriage\\n\\nComplex Input\\n\\nLegal Specialist\\n\\nSynthesis and Decision\\n\\nTechnical Specialist\\n\\nBusiness Specialist\\n\\nIssues and Repairs\\n\\nLegal Analysis\\n\\nTechnical Review\\n\\nBusiness Impact\\n\\nCoordinated Output\\n\\n\\n\\nRegardless of pattern setup, the flow of tasks requires outlining\\n\\nWorkflow outlines are represented by graphs; the system follows this graph like a map, executing tasks in the declared order.\\n\\nNon-Declarative Graphs\\n\\nDeclarative Graphs\\n\\nYou don't predefine the full workflow; instead agents dynamically decide what to do next based on conditions, results, or goals.\\n\\nOften used for decentralized orchestration.\\n\\nConsider: A self-organizing team where people pick up tasks as they see fit, adapting to the situation.\\n\\nA predefined and explicit approach. The graph is made up of nodes (tasks/agents) and edges (data or control flow).\\n\\nOften used for manager orchestration patterns. \\n\\nConsider: a project manager with a Gantt chart, telling each team member exactly when to do their part.\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Workflow v1 (from Session 2), risk thresholds, integration constraints, performance goals. Chosen orchestration pattern; delegation triggers table; message schema snippet; memory/TTL policy; deterministic & idempotent action plan; termination state list. Materials Participants Orchestration pattern cards; delegation trigger table; message schema template; memory/TTL policy sheet. Architecture/Orchestration Lead, AI/ML Lead, Engineering Lead, SRE/DevOps, Security/GRC, Risk/Compliance, Product Owner/PM, Ops Lead.\\n\\n3.1 Select Orchestration Strategy\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nPattern choice: Single-agent vs. multi-agent; if multi, Manager (coordinator delegates) vs. Decentralized (peer handoffs).\\n\\nSplit triggers: When/why to add specialists (e.g., fraud, policy interpreter, payments).\\n\\nCoordinator & ownership: Who owns final decisions, long-lived state, and termination conditions.\\n\\nParallel vs. sequential: What can run concurrently and how to merge results/dissent.\\n\\nFailure handling: Loop detection/breakers, retries/backoff, dead-letter queue, human handoff.\\n\\nTermination states: Execute, escalate, request-info, abandon.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nCan a single agent handle the prototype safely? If not, which specialist reduces risk/latency most? Where can we parallelize safely?\\n\\nWhat objective signals trigger delegation (low confidence, high amount, conflicting policy, suspected fraud)? How do we prevent loops or ping-pong?\\n\\nWhat data is never shared, and how is PII minimized/redacted?\\n\\nWhat is the rollback path if the coordinator fails mid-run?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   122\\n\\n\\n\\nEffective orchestration requires agent guardrails\\n\\nGuardrails manage data privacy and reputational risks by preventing prompt leaks and enforcing brand-aligned model behavior. Design them for identified risks and layer additional ones as new vulnerabilities are uncovered.\\n\\nGuardrail Type Description and Examples Relevance Classifier Flags off-topic queries to keep responses within scope. Safety Classifier Detects unsafe inputs like jailbreaks or prompt injections that exploit vulnerabilities, blocking attempts to extract system instructions. PII Filter Vets model output to prevent unnecessary exposure of personally identifiable information. Moderation Flags harmful or inappropriate inputs (gate speech, harassment) for safe interactions. Tool Safeguards Assigns risk ratings (low, medium, high) to tools based on impact, triggering automated checks on human escalation. Rules-based Protections Uses simple deterministic measures (blocklists, regex) to prevent known threats like prohibited terms or SQL injections. Output Validation Ensures responses align with brand values through content checks, preventing outputs that could harm integrity.\\n\\n\\n\\nSet up guardrails that address the risks you've already identified for your use case\\n\\nThink of guardrails as a layered defense mechanism. Using multiple, specialized guardrails together creates more resilient agents.\\n\\n1\\n\\n2\\n\\n3\\n\\nAdd New Guardrails Based on Real-World Edge Cases\\n\\nOptimize for Security and User Experience\\n\\nFocus on Data Privacy and Content Safety\\n\\nContinuously improve based on actual failures and edge cases you encounter in production\\n\\nTweak your guardrails as your agent evolves, balancing protection with usability\\n\\nStart with fundamental protections against data leaks and harmful content\\n\\nNo\\n\\nReply: Cannot process message\\n\\nRules-based protections:\\n\\nCharacter Limit\\n\\nBlacklist\\n\\nRegex\\n\\nAll checks passed?\\n\\nRelevance Check\\n\\nSafety Check\\n\\nUser Input\\n\\nModeration API\\n\\nAgent SDK\\n\\nRefund agent\\n\\nCall initiate_refund\\n\\nYes\\n\\nShown above, we combine LLM-based guardrails, rules-based guardrails such as regex and the OpenAI moderation API to vet our user inputs.\\n\\n\\n\\nAs architecture complexity increases, variability multiplies and requires more robust control mechanisms\\n\\nLevel 1: Single Model Call\\n\\n1\\n\\nVariability Sources: Sampling randomness\\n\\nControl Strategies: Temperature settings, structured outputs\\n\\n2\\n\\nLevel 2: Multi-step Workflow\\n\\nVariability Sources: Accumulated variance\\n\\nControl Strategies: Step validators, rollbacks\\n\\n3\\n\\nLevel 3: Single Agent plus Tools\\n\\nVariability Sources: Tool choice/parameters\\n\\nControl Strategies: Clear tool docs, forced tool use\\n\\n4\\n\\nLevel 4: Multi-agent System\\n\\nVariability Sources: Handoffs and coordination\\n\\nControl Strategies: Handoff rules, state management\\n\\n\\n\\nHuman intervention is a critical safeguard to improve agent performance in edge cases\\n\\nWhen transitioning to human operators, include complete trace information, source materials, and full user context. \\n\\nFour key scenarios where human-in-the-loop is paramount:\\n\\n1.\\n\\n2.\\n\\n3.\\n\\n4.\\n\\nHigh-Risk Domains\\n\\nLow Confidence Responses\\n\\nPolicy-Sensitive Intents\\n\\nNovel Tool Usage\\n\\nFinancial decisions, healthcare guidance, legal advice, and other domains where errors carry significant consequences require human oversight.\\n\\nWhen agent confidence falls below defined thresholds, particularly in complex or nuanced scenarios where AI limitations are evident.\\n\\nRequests touching on organizational policies, regulatory compliance, or potentially controversial topics benefit from human judgment.\\n\\nFirst-time or unusual tool interactions may require human verification to ensure appropriate and safe execution.\\n\\n\\n\\nSafety best practices apply to the whole organization\\n\\nWhile IT plays a significant role, AI literacy lowers risk and ensures users understand system limitations; in those cases, human-in-the-loop becomes even more effective.\\n\\nModeration API\\n\\nAdversarial Testing\\n\\nHuman Review\\n\\nLeverage the free Moderation API to reduce unsafe content in completions, or develop custom content filtration systems tailored to your specific use case.\\n\\n\\"Red-team\\" your application with both representative inputs and adversarial attempts to break functionality. Test for topic wandering and prompt injection vulnerabilities.\\n\\nImplement human oversight for output review before practical use, especially in high-stakes domains and code generation. Ensure reviewers understand system limitations.\\n\\nPrompt Engineering\\n\\nUser Verification (KYC)\\n\\nInput/Output Constraints\\n\\nConstrain topic and tone through carefully designed prompts. Provide high-quality examples of desired behavior to steer model outputs effectively.\\n\\nRequire registration and login, potentially linked to existing accounts. Consider credit card or ID verification for higher-risk applications.\\n\\nLimit text input length to prevent prompt injection. Restrict output tokens and narrow input/output ranges to reduce potential misuse.\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Security/Privacy standards, policy docs, tool specs, legal/compliance guidance. Guardrail catalog, approval matrix, audit logging spec, alert thresholds & ownership. Materials Participants Risk\\u2192Control matrix template; approval-matrix template; logging & alert spec sheets. Security/GRC/Privacy, Risk/Compliance, Engineering/Platform, AI/ML Lead, SRE/Observability, Product Owner/PM, Ops.\\n\\n3.2 Implement Guardrails & Safety\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nThreat model: top risks (unsafe actions, PII leakage, jailbreaks/prompt injection, policy violations, duplicates).\\n\\nLayered defenses: pre-filters, in-flow checks, post-validations, including:\\n\\nRelevance filter; safety/jailbreak detection.\\n\\nPII handling (redaction in logs; least-privilege access).\\n\\nPolicy grounding & required citations.\\n\\nNumeric/schema validation for critical fields.\\n\\nTool safeguards (confirmations, allow/deny lists, dry-run/preview).\\n\\nRate limits & timeouts; retries; circuit breakers.\\n\\nApproval matrix (human-in-the-loop thresholds; dual control if needed).\\n\\nAuditability (what to log, retention, access controls).\\n\\nCompliance mapping: how PCI/PHI/GDPR/etc. affect logging, approvals, and data flows.\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   128\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Workflow v1; S3.1 orchestration decisions; S3.2 guardrail set; success metrics from Session 1. Design Agentic Workflow v2, Allowed-Actions Matrix, state machine diagram, observability & alerting spec. Materials Participants Workflow canvas overlay; actions-matrix template; state-machine template; observability checklist. Engineering Lead(s), AI/ML Lead, Security/GRC, SRE/Observability, Product Owner/PM, Operations.\\n\\n3.3 Design Agentic Workflow v2\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nInputs: channels/fields/artifacts; pre-checks (file types/size, sanitation).\\n\\nStepwise flow (annotated): merge orchestration rules and safety layers at each step.\\n\\nAllowed-Actions Matrix: when the system executes, escalates, or blocks.\\n\\nState & termination: state machine (states, transitions, timers).\\n\\nObservability: logs/metrics per step, alert conditions, QA sampling sizes & cadence.\\n\\nRequired format: Input \\u2192 Steps + Logic \\u2192 Output with explicit [Reasoning] callouts. For each step annotate Model, Guardrails applied, Tools/Knowledge, I/O schema, Retries/Timeouts, Approval/Handoff.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nIs every risky step gated by a guardrail or approval?\\n\\nAre delegation triggers concrete & testable?\\n\\nCould an engineer implement from this page alone?\\n\\nAre loops prevented and abandon conditions clear?\\n\\nDo outputs always include citations/evidence where required?\\n\\nIs PII minimized at rest and in logs?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   129\\n\\n\\n\\nPhase 4\\n\\nDefine Your Agent Evaluation Criteria & Next Steps\\n\\nPhase 2\\n\\nPhase 1\\n\\nPhase 3\\n\\nPhase 4\\n\\n2.1 Select agent runtime model(s) & routing\\n\\n2.2 Author agent instructions\\n\\n2.3 Specify tools & knowledge sources\\n\\n2.4 Build Design Agentic Workflow v1\\n\\n1.1 Define value proposition & problem\\n\\n1.2 Map current workflow & personas \\n\\n1.3 Set business goals\\n\\n1.4 Define prototype scope & boundaries\\n\\n1.5 Specify success metrics & acceptance\\n\\n1.6 Design high-level workflow\\n\\n3.1 Select orchestration strategy\\n\\n3.2 Implement guardrails & safety\\n\\n3.3 Finalize Design Agentic Workflow v2\\n\\n4.1 Establish evaluation & benchmarking plan\\n\\n4.2 Define risks & mitigations\\n\\n4.3 Prioritize implementation & milestones\\n\\n4.4 Develop rollout plan\\n\\nBuild your Agentic Prototype\\n\\nThis phase will walk you through the following activities:\\n\\nBuilding the eval framework: offline/online tests, labeling rubric, promotion gates (Prototype \\u2192 Beta \\u2192 Pilot \\u2192 GA).Wiring dashboards, alerts, QA sampling, and runbooks to your success metrics.\\n\\nDocumenting the risk register with detectors, mitigations.\\n\\nPrioritizing phases and dependencies for delivery.\\n\\nDesigning the rollout (cohorts/canaries, exit criteria, kill switches/rollback, comms/training, compliance) with cost transparency/FinOps.\\n\\n\\n\\nRemember: AI governance is adaptive and distributed across teams\\n\\nPolicies, oversight, and monitoring evolve as the agent learns and regulations change. \\n\\nProduct / Engineering\\n\\nLegal and Privacy\\n\\n01\\n\\n03\\n\\nDefine requirements, maintain evaluation datasets, and enforce technical guardrails.\\n\\nEnsure adherence to privacy laws, manage regulatory filings, and review third-party tools.\\n\\nOperations (AgentOps)\\n\\nSecurity and Compliance\\n\\n02\\n\\n04\\n\\nPerform continuous monitoring, track performance metrics, manage incident response, and coordinate retraining.\\n\\nApprove data flows, conduct risk assessments, and monitor for policy violations.\\n\\nIf governance structure is unresolved, see Info-Tech's: Govern the Use of AI Responsibly With a Fit-for-Purpose Structure\\n\\n\\n\\nEach industry has specific compliance requirements that must be addressed early in the design phase \\n\\nSector Must-haves in at Phase 1 Red Flags to Avoid Finance Audit trail, records retention, disclaimers, and product-specific constraints. Unlogged outputs, unsupported advice, missing KYC/PII controls. Healthcare PHI handling, HIPAA posture, clinical scope, and human review. Free-text PHI in logs, unsupervised clinical inferences. Government Transparency, multilingual access, and records management. Opaque decisioning, inaccessible formats. Retail Brand voice, real-time catalog/inventory, and privacy choices. Price/inventory drift, off-brand tone, and dark patterns.\\n\\n\\n\\nRisk mitigation is crucial to ensure an AI agent operates optimally\\n\\nThree areas of risk to focus on include: development issues, LLM issues, and production issues.\\n\\nDevelopment Issues\\n\\n01\\n\\nPoorly defined prompts? Define clear objectives, craft detailed personas, and use effective prompting techniques.\\n\\nEvaluation challenges? Implement continuous evaluation, utilize real-world scenarios, and incorporate feedback loops early.\\n\\nLLM Issues\\n\\nPlanning failures? Decompose tasks and have multi-plan selection.\\n\\nReasoning failures? Fine-tune LLMs with feedback and use specialized agents.\\n\\nTool calling failures? Define clear parameters, validate tool outputs, and have tool selection verification loops.\\n\\nDifficulty steering? Use specialized prompts, hierarchical design, and fine-tuned models.\\n\\nHigh cost of running? Reduce context size, use smaller models, and use cloud-based solutions.\\n\\n02\\n\\nProduction Issues\\n\\nGuardrails? Use rule-based filters and validation, human-in-the-loop oversight, and ethical and compliance frameworks.\\n\\nFault tolerance? Use redundancy, automated recovery, and stateful recovery.\\n\\nAgent scaling? Leverage scalable architectures, resource management, and performance monitoring.\\n\\nInfinite looping? Have clear termination conditions, enhance reasoning and planning, and monitor agent behaviour.\\n\\n03\\n\\n\\n\\nCore to risk mitigation is agent observability\\n\\nA well-instrumented agent provides visibility across the interaction lifecycle, allowing teams to identify issues and continuously improve performance.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nComprehensive observability isn't just for technical debugging. It builds stakeholder confidence by demonstrating that the system behaves as expected and problems can be quickly identified and addressed,\\n\\nWhat observability is\\n\\nContinuous visibility into an agent's end-to-end behavior so you can detect issues, measure performance, and improve reliability\\n\\nWhy observability matters\\n\\nAgents are non-deterministic\\u2014outputs can vary run-to-run.\\n\\nComplex workflows (tools, handoffs, loops) need traceability for debugging and compliance.\\n\\nObservability data feeds evaluation, cost control, and governance.\\n\\nCore capabilities of observability in an agent\\n\\nReal-time tracing of every agent run.\\n\\nStructured logging and dashboards for accuracy, cost, and latency.\\n\\nAlerting when metrics drift or failures spike.\\n\\n\\n\\nBuild a list of what to observe in agent traces\\n\\nObservability is the foundation for evaluation, debugging, and governance. Without it, you cannot prove accuracy, control costs, or meet compliance obligations.\\n\\nInputs\\n\\nOutputs\\n\\nReasoning / \\"Thought\\"\\n\\nUser prompts, retrieved context, and parameters for tool calls.\\n\\nFinal answers, intermediate responses, and exit conditions.\\n\\nModel chain-of-thought or step-by-step logs (if safely recorded).\\n\\nTool Usage\\n\\nFailures & Retries\\n\\nHandoffs\\n\\nTool calls, arguments, return values, and success/failure rates.\\n\\nExceptions, guardrail triggers, and automatic retry attempts.\\n\\nTransfers between different agents in complex multi-agent workflows.\\n\\nTiming & Cost\\n\\nLatency per step, total task duration, token usage, and cost per task.\\n\\n\\n\\nTraditional, deterministic QA methods are ineffective to evaluate AI agents\\n\\nYou need a framework for structured testing, ensuring accuracy, reliability, and optimal performance of non-deterministic systems once they are deployed to production.\\n\\nEvaluation Type Benefits Drawbacks Human evaluation Captures nuanced behaviour, considers human factors. Subjective, time-consuming, expensive, difficult to scale. LLM-as-a-Judge/LLM Juries Scalable, efficient, and consistent. Examples include G-Eval and SelfCheckGPT May overlook intermediate steps, limited by LLM capabilities. Automated metrics Objective, scalable, and efficient. May not capture full capabilities, susceptible to gaming. Online Evaluation Leverages real-time user interactions, capturing true product behaviour. Expensive, harder to control variables, difficult to reproduce. Offline Evaluation Utilizes static test sets and redefined prompts for repeatable, debuggable analysis. May not fully reflect unpredictable production conditions.\\n\\nAvoid four main anti-patterns to evaluation:\\n\\nRelying solely on academic metrics (e.g., BLEU) without considering real-world context can lead to misleading evaluations.\\n\\n\\"Feels right\\" testing or delayed evaluation.\\n\\nUsing evaluation datasets that don't accurately reflect production behaviour will result in an agent that performs poorly in actual use.\\n\\nDisregarding human feedback when calibrating automated scores can lead to misaligned objectives and an agent that fails to meet user expectations.\\n\\n\\n\\nDon't confuse system evaluation with LLM evaluation\\n\\nLLM evaluation is foundational for safe, effective, and trustworthy deployment of AI systems. It ensures performance on specific tasks and delivers the desired user experience, crucial as users become more discerning of AI features.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nFor product teams, system evaluation provides the most valuable insights. It ensures a well-performing model translates into a positive user experience, revealing real-world issues before deployment. \\n\\nLLM Evaluation\\n\\nSystem Evaluation\\n\\nFocuses on the LLM's raw performance in isolation, assessing its foundational capabilities independent of application context.\\n\\nExamines the LLM's performance as an integrated part of a full product, measuring overall user experience and real-world impact.\\n\\n\\n\\nLLM evaluation is a core component of system evaluation\\n\\nDifferent tasks require different evaluation priorities, but most LLM evaluation strategies consider the following core dimensions:\\n\\nDoes the model generate outputs that are factually correct and grounded in source content?\\n\\nFaithfulness and factual accuracy\\n\\nDoes the system operationally perform well in practical settings, considering latency, cost, and scalability?\\n\\nDoes the model actually answer the user's question or fulfill the prompt?\\n\\nRelevance\\n\\nEfficiency\\n\\nIs the model free from harmful, toxic, or discriminatory content?\\n\\n.\\n\\nIs the output readable, well-structured, and grammatically sound?\\n\\nBias, fairness, and safety\\n\\nCoherence and fluency\\n\\n\\n\\nLLM evaluation must be integrated into the dev cycle from day one, onwards\\n\\nLLM-powered applications face constant changes in user behavior and data, making continuous monitoring crucial to prevent model drift and maintain performance.\\n\\n03.\\n\\n01.\\n\\n02.\\n\\nChoose the Dataset for Evaluation\\n\\nAdd Tracing to Your LLM Application\\n\\nDefine the Evaluation Task\\n\\nSelect a comprehensive and well-curated dataset with inputs, expected outputs, and metadata. This provides sharper insights and better test coverage.\\n\\nEnsure visibility into your LLM application's behavior by adding tracing. This captures crucial data (input, context, output, feedback) fundamental for assessing quality and debugging.\\n\\nClearly define what 'success' means for your application. This maps dataset inputs to desired output scores, reflecting the specific behavior you aim to measure.\\n\\n05.\\n\\n06.\\n\\n04.\\n\\nTrack and Monitor in Production\\n\\nSelect the Right Metrics\\n\\nCreate and Run Evaluation Experiments\\n\\nContinue evaluation after deployment to see how your model performs under real-world conditions. This involves continuous data capture and incorporating user feedback.\\n\\nRun your dataset through your system, score outputs, and generate insights. Embed these structured tests into your development cycle to track quality and catch regressions.\\n\\nDecide how you will score the outputs. Map metrics to key priorities like factuality, relevance, or safety, combining automated and human judgment methods.\\n\\n\\n\\nListen to users and prioritize what actually matters for evaluation\\n\\nCollect inputs from user interviews, survey quotes, session replays, and failure examples. Then cluster them into themes and tag by both business/user impact and development/data effort.\\n\\nQuick Wins Strategic Bets Fill-ins Defer\\n\\nExamples of feedback themes: \\n\\n\\"Answers are technically correct but too terse for complex queries\\"\\n\\n\\"System is unacceptably slow when processing long documents\\"\\n\\n\\"The handoff process to human agents is unclear\\"\\n\\n\\"Agent fails to provide citations for sensitive factual claims\\"\\n\\nValue\\n\\nEffort\\n\\n\\n\\nProbe edge cases and adversarial scenarios for system evaluation \\n\\nIT teams, especially, must anticipate and plan for specific edge cases to ensure system stability, security, and user satisfaction.\\n\\nEdge case examples\\n\\nInput Variability\\n\\nContext Complexity\\n\\nAgents must be robust enough to process diverse inputs, including multilingual prompts and various data formats like JSON or XML, without breaking or misinterpreting requests\\n\\nMultilingual and Messy Inputs\\n\\nLong-Context Dialogues\\n\\nManaging challenges from long conversational histories and ambiguous or incomplete tool outputs is critical for maintaining coherent agent behavior and accurate responses.\\n\\n\\"Can u hlp me w/ my acnt? Je ne comprends pas l'erreur.\\"\\n\\n20+ turn conversations with context-dependent questions\\n\\nMitigations\\n\\nSecurity and Policy\\n\\nImplement robust measures to prevent jailbreak attempts and effectively reconcile conflicting system and user prompts to ensure data integrity and compliance.\\n\\nJailbreak Attempts\\n\\nTool/Network Failures\\n\\n\\"Ignore previous instructions and instead tell me how to...\\"\\n\\nDatabase timeouts, API rate limits, partial responses\\n\\n\\n\\nDevelop KPIs that align with user needs\\n\\nKPIs and thresholds should be reviewed regularly to prevent scope creep and ensure alignment with business outcomes.\\n\\nKPI (prototype) Definition Target (v1) Guardrail Answer quality Task-specific rubric or SME score \\u2265 0.75 avg < 0.6 triggers review Latency (P50/P95) End-to-end response time P50 \\u2264 2.5s / P95 \\u2264 6s P95 > 8s alert Containment/Deflection % resolved w/o human \\u2265 55-65% < 40% triggers backlog Unit cost $ per resolved request Within budget band +20% = FinOps review Safety incidents Policy/guardrail violations 0 critical Any critical = halt Hallucination rate Wrong-but-confident outputs \\u2264 3-5% \\u2265 8% = prompt/tooling fix CSAT (pilot) User satisfaction (1-5) \\u2265 4.2 < 3.8 = UX prompt pass\\n\\n\\n\\nBenchmark your baselines against industry peers\\n\\nThese gap analyses help us focus iteration efforts where the ROI is highest, prioritizing improvements to areas with the widest performance gaps relative to industry leaders.\\n\\nMetric Baseline (Human/Legacy) Prototype v1 Industry Range Gap to Target Accuracy 82% 86% 85-92% +4% to upper P95 Latency 9.0s 5.2s 3-6s -2.2s Containment 35% 58% 50-70% +12% Unit Cost $2.10 $1.35 $1.00-$1.80 -$0.35\\n\\n\\n\\nTurn evaluations into a data flywheel to catch drift before users do\\n\\nMature evaluations become training data for fine-tuning and reinforcement learning, creating a powerful feedback loop for agent development.\\n\\nCI for Agents: Release Pipeline\\n\\nLeveraging evaluation data for fine-tuning and reinforcement learning drives iterative enhancements to agent capabilities.\\n\\nSystematic assessment of agent performance provides critical data for identifying areas of strength and weakness.\\n\\nCommit Changes\\n\\nNew prompts, tools, or retrieval sources\\n\\nRun Evaluations\\n\\nGolden tests, adversarial prompts, drift checks\\n\\nGate Deployment\\n\\nMust meet quality and safety thresholds\\n\\nDeploy with Confidence\\n\\nOptimized agents deliver superior results, maximizing the return on your artificial intelligence initiatives.\\n\\nMonitored rollout with safety net\\n\\n\\n\\nSystem evaluations include system metrics, task completion, quality control, and tool interaction\\n\\nFocus: Technical Performance and Resource Use\\n\\nFocus: Effectiveness of Agent\\n\\nTask \\n\\nCompletion\\n\\nSystem \\n\\nMetrics\\n\\nAgent Success Rate: Measures the percentage of tasks fully and correctly completed by the agent without external help or errors.\\n\\nTask Completion Rate: Tracks the overall proportion of initiated tasks that the agent brings to a conclusive state, whether successful or not.\\n\\nSteps per Task: Quantifies the average number of actions or tool calls an agent takes to complete a given task, indicating operational efficiency.\\n\\nHuman Intervention Count: Records how often human oversight was required to resolve issues or complete tasks the agent couldn't handle autonomously. \\n\\nLatency per Tool Call: Measures responsiveness of agent's tool interactions, highlighting potential bottlenecks.\\n\\nTask Completion Time: Tracks total time to complete a task, indicating overall operational efficiency.\\n\\nToken Usage: Records LLM input and output tokens consumed, directly impacting operational cost and efficiency.\\n\\nCost per Task: Calculates the aggregate financial cost associated with the successful completion of a single task.\\n\\nRESULTS\\n\\nFocus: Effectiveness of Tool Usage\\n\\nFocus: Accuracy and Requirement Adherence\\n\\nTool Selection Accuracy: Measures the percentage of times the agent correctly identifies and select the appropriate tool for a given sub-task of query.\\n\\nTool Argument Accuracy: Assesses how accurately the agent constructs the necessary arguments and parameters for the chosen tool, ensuring valid and effective execution.\\n\\nTool Success Rate: Tracks the proportion of tool calls that execute successfully without errors, retries, or requiring human intervention..\\n\\nAccuracy: Measures how precisely the agent's output aligns with factual correctness and all defined task requirements and constraints.\\n\\nInstruction Adherence: Evaluates agent's ability to strictly follow specific instructions provided in its configuration.\\n\\nOutput Format Success: Assesses if the agent's output is consistently delivered in the specified format.\\n\\nContext Adherence: Verifies the agent's responses remain relevant to the given context,\\n\\nTool \\n\\nInteraction\\n\\nQuality \\n\\nControl\\n\\n\\n\\nApply a symptom-to-solution optimization matrix for quick diagnosis\\n\\nThis triage guide helps teams quickly identify and address common agent performance issues without extensive debugging.\\n\\nPROBLEM\\n\\nLIKELY CAUSE\\n\\nSOLUTION\\n\\nAdd RAG and retrieval\\n\\nMissing knowledge\\n\\nOutdated domain data\\n\\nInconsistent format\\n\\nFree-form answers\\n\\nStructured outputs and examples\\n\\nPoor tool descriptions\\n\\nImprove docs; add examples\\n\\nWrong tool selection\\n\\nFine-tune or add judge loop\\n\\nInconsistent reasoning\\n\\nVariability too high\\n\\nPoor task understanding\\n\\nVague instructions\\n\\nRewrite prompts; add steps\\n\\n\\n\\nBefore moving the prototype to production, ensure no tasks have been missed\\n\\nROI will be lost in the long-run if impatience wins the day in the short-term.\\n\\nChecklist Item (Phase) Key Focus/Actions Why it Matters Define Success Criteria (1.2) Define measurable KPIs & SLOs (accuracy, cost, latency).Ensure targets are measurable via logs. Provides clear targets; proves value. Document Model Rationale (1.3) Select initial models deliberately based on trade-offs. Document the \\"why\\" behind choices. Justifies decisions; aids future updates. Safety and Compliance (2.1) Safety mechanisms (moderation, prompts). Compliance rules. Human-in-the-loop for high-risk outputs. Ensures responsible operation. Observability and Cost (2.2) Logging for monitoring and debugging. Cost guardrails (token limits, usage modes). Ensures responsible operation. Evaluation and Testing (2.3) Automated tests (\\"eval suite\\") using golden set. Test factuality, hallucinations, tool errors, edge cases. Ensures quality; prevents regressions. Model Updates and Versioning (2.3) Version pinning strategy. A/B testing for new versions. Rollback procedures. Maintains stability while evolving.\\n\\nPrototype to production milestones\\n\\n\\n\\nControl token spend with FinOps practices\\n\\nForecast costs based on volume \\u00d7 tokens per path \\u00d7 price for each environment. Separate build costs from run costs and include embedding/RAG compute expenses in your calculations.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nRemember the Pareto principle: The top 20% of interaction flows often drive 80% of total token spend. Identify and optimize these high-volume paths first for maximum impact.\\n\\nTrack the Right Unit Economics\\n\\nCost per Resolved Request\\n\\nTokens per Answer\\n\\nCost per Minute Saved\\n\\nMeasure the full cost of successfully handling user queries from start to finish\\n\\nMonitor token efficiency across different query types and response paths\\n\\nEvaluate ROI by comparing agent costs to the value of time saved for users and staff\\n\\n\\n\\nCost controls are an important part of implementation priority\\n\\nImplement strategic optimizations at each layer of your agent architecture while preserving response quality.\\n\\nLayer Low-risk Controls Higher-impact Controls Prompt Remove boilerplate, compress history, use fixed JSON schemas. Implement selective reasoning only when needed; summarize context windows. Model Route to Balanced/Lightweight models by default. Reserve Frontier models for low-confidence or high-risk scenarios; apply temperature/length caps. Retrieval Use hybrid search, smaller k values, aggressive deduplication. Implement reranking instead of increasing k; create semantic cache for near-duplicates. Tools Cache deterministic results; batch API calls when possible. Replace multi-purpose endpoints with narrower, more efficient functions. Runtime Set timeouts, retries, early-exit rules. Implement circuit breakers; degrade to retrieval-only when tools fail.\\n\\n\\n\\nUtilize caching and routing strategies to save on cost\\n\\nImplement streaming responses to improve perceived performance and stop generation once schema requirements are satisfied. This prevents unnecessary token usage while maintaining complete functional responses.\\n\\nSemantic Answer Cache\\n\\nProgressive Routing\\n\\nTool Result Cache\\n\\nStart with lightweight models and progressively escalate to more powerful (and expensive) models only when necessary based on confidence scores or task complexity.\\n\\nIdentify near-duplicate queries and reuse previously validated outputs, eliminating unnecessary regeneration costs while maintaining response quality. Implement appropriate cache invalidation strategies based on content type and volatility.\\n\\nApply time-to-live (TTL) caching based on endpoint characteristics: catalog data (10 minutes), policy information (24 hours), etc. This significantly reduces redundant API calls and external service costs.\\n\\n\\n\\nPlan sprints based on evidence\\n\\nEach experiment must exit with a clear go/no-go decision based on measured performance delta. Maintain a running experiment log to avoid repeating tests and build institutional knowledge.\\n\\nHypothesis Change KPI Targeted Expected Delta Owner Status Citations improve trust. Add source snippets to responses. CSAT/Accuracy. +0.2 / +3% PO Planned Simple queries need less compute. Route \\"FAQs\\" to smaller model. Unit Cost/Latency. -25% / -1s Eng Running Fewer docs = faster response. Re-rank top-k=8\\u21924 Accuracy/Latency. +2% / -0.8s Data Planned\\n\\nLevers to pull:\\n\\nPrompting: Instruction tweaks, few-shot examples, tool-use hints\\n\\nModeling: Intent-based routing, smaller models for simple flows\\n\\nRetrieval: Chunking strategies, re-ranking, metadata filters, freshness\\n\\nUX/Process: Better confirmation flows, clearer refusals, smarter handoffs\\n\\nCost Optimization: Prompt compression, caching, result reuse\\n\\nEvery refinement is linked directly to an expected KPI movement; we don't make changes without clear hypotheses about their impact.\\n\\n\\n\\nExpect to produce several artifacts for each sprint to ensure continued success\\n\\nThe following artifacts close the loop from prototype to proof to scale. This disciplined approach builds credibility with stakeholders and accelerates your path to production-grade AI agent performance.\\n\\nPerformance & Benchmark Report\\n\\nExperiment Log\\n\\nIteration Backlog (Top 5)\\n\\nPrioritized improvement items with assigned owners, effort estimates, KPI linkage, and delivery timelines\\n\\nDetailed record of hypotheses, configurations, results, performance deltas, and go/no-go decisions\\n\\nComprehensive before/after KPI analysis, baseline vs. industry comparisons, and segment-level performance cuts\\n\\nWhy it matters: Ensures reproducibility and prevents redundant testing efforts\\n\\nWhy it matters: Creates a focused roadmap for the next sprint cycle\\n\\nWhy it matters: Grounds all decisions in objective evidence rather than opinions\\n\\nUpdated KPI Targets\\n\\nExecutive Summary (1-pager)\\n\\nRevised performance thresholds (if adjusted) with supporting rationale\\n\\nConcise overview of wins, gaps, next steps, and resource requests\\n\\nWhy it matters: Aligns all stakeholders on realistic yet ambitious goals\\n\\nWhy it matters: Secures continued executive buy-in and sponsorship\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Success metrics from Session 1; Workflow v2; historical cases/logs; traffic assumptions. Evaluation plan doc; metric\\u2192test mapping; offline/online designs; labeling rubric; promotion gates; owners & cadence. Materials Participants Evaluation canvas; rubric template; sample power-calc sheet. AI/ML Lead, QA/Test Engineering, Analytics/Data Platform, SRE/Observability, Product Owner/PM, Risk/Compliance, Operations.\\n\\n4.1 Establish Agent Evaluation\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nScope & goals: what must be proven before promotion (Prototype \\u2192 Beta \\u2192 Pilot \\u2192 GA).\\n\\nMetrics by category: Functional, Groundedness/Factuality, Safety, Autonomy/Oversight, Robustness.\\n\\nTest design: offline datasets (representative + adversarial), online A/B (unit, split, duration, power).\\n\\nTool-error simulation: timeouts, malformed payloads, stale data; expected handling.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nDo offline sets reflect real traffic mix (language, seasonality, edge cases)?\\n\\nAre labels clear & reproducible (rubric + examples)?\\n\\nIs the A/B test powered (minimum detectable effect)?\\n\\nWhich failures are P0 rollback vs P1 fix-forward?\\n\\nHow will we verify reasoning quality (citations, logic)?\\n\\nCan results be reproduced (frozen datasets, version pins)?\\n\\nAny privacy constraints (PII masking, retention) for eval?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   153\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Guardrail set (Session 3); incident history (if any); policy & vendor constraints. Risk register with detectors, mitigations, DRIs; links to playbooks. Materials Participants Risk\\u2192Mitigation register template. Security/GRC/Privacy, Risk/Compliance, Engineering/Platform, AI/ML Lead, Ops, Product Owner/PM.\\n\\n4.2 Define Risks & Mitigations\\n\\n60-90 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nTop risks: safety, quality, latency/cost, compliance, change management.\\n\\nSignals/Detectors: what tips us off per risk.\\n\\nMitigations: preventive + reactive steps; DRI; playbook link.\\n\\nResidual risk: what remains and why it's acceptable at prototype.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nWhat's the worst plausible failure and how is it contained at each layer?\\n\\nHow do we detect silent failure (confident but wrong)?\\n\\nWhat if policy changes mid-week\\u2014who updates/approves?\\n\\nWhat if a third-party API rate-limits or changes schema?\\n\\nAny legal/compliance reviews needed pre-Pilot/GA?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   154\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Workflow v2 & orchestration decisions; staffing/budget; dependency map. Phased roadmap with owners/dates; phase acceptance gates; dependency tracker. Materials Participants Roadmap board; RAID (Risks/Assumptions/Issues/Dependencies) sheet. Product Owner/PM, Engineering Lead, AI/ML Lead, Ops Lead, Finance/FinOps.\\n\\n4.3 Prioritize Implementation & Milestones\\n\\n30-45 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nPhases: Prototype \\u2192 Enhancements \\u2192 Optimizations with clear deliverables.\\n\\nMust-haves vs Nice-to-haves per phase.\\n\\nDependencies & prerequisites: data, auth, policy review, tooling.\\n\\nAcceptance per phase: what proves we can advance.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nWhat's the smallest slice that demonstrates business value?\\n\\nWhich dependencies could stall the critical path; what's plan B?\\n\\nWhat can we defer without risking safety?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   155\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Evaluation plan & promotion gates; support resources; change-management calendar. Rollout plan (cohorts, schedule, exit gates); rollback procedures; comms/training plan; approvals tracker. Materials Participants Rollout planner; comms calendar; training checklist. Product Owner/PM, Ops/Support Lead, SRE/Observability, Risk/Compliance, Training/Enablement, Executive Sponsor.\\n\\n4.4 Develop Rollout Plan\\n\\n45-60 minutes\\n\\nWhat to write\\n\\nStages: Prototype \\u2192 Private Beta \\u2192 Pilot \\u2192 GA.\\n\\nCohorts & canaries: size, selection, readiness.\\n\\nExit criteria per stage: numeric + qualitative.\\n\\nRollback & kill switches: what toggles, where, who owns them.\\n\\nComms & training: audiences, materials, timing.\\n\\nSupport model: on-call rotation, escalation paths, office hours.\\n\\nCompliance & approvals: sign-offs, data retention checks.\\n\\nPrompt yourself\\n\\nWhat's the smallest safe slice to learn fast with minimal blast radius?\\n\\nAre kill switches trivial to flip and documented?\\n\\nWho needs training before each stage?\\n\\nWhat signals confirm we're ready for GA?\\n\\nAgent PRD DOC\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   156\\n\\n\\n\\nA detailed product requirements document that outlines a fit-for-purpose agentic AI prototype.\\n\\nDefined value proposition and problem statement for an agentic AI prototype. Personas were mapped against success criteria.\\n\\nDesigned prototype structure and desired user experience.\\n\\nConstructed orchestration and safety frameworks, ensuring clear observability.\\n\\nEstablished model evaluation and benchmarking practices.\\n\\nIdentified the prototype-to-production timeline and key milestones.\\n\\nSet implementation priorities with a strong eye on cost controls.\\n\\nDeveloped a rollout plan.\\n\\n\\n\\nBibliography\\n\\n\\"AI-Powered Automation Transforms Operations for Omega Healthcare.\\" UiPath. Accessed 2 Oct. 2025. <https://www.uipath.com/resources/automation-case-studies/omega-healthcare-boosts-efficiency-through-automation>.\\n\\nChallapally, Aditya, et al. The GenAI Divide: State of AI in Business 2025. Project NANDA, July 2025. Artificial Intelligence News. Accessed 2 Oct. 2025. <https://www.artificialintelligence-news.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/ai_report_2025.pdf>.\\n\\n\\"Deutsche Telekom Customer Story.\\" Glean. Accessed 2 Oct. 2025. <https://www.glean.com/resources/customer-stories/deutsche-telekom>.\\n\\nGulli, Antonio, and Lavi Nigam, et al. Agents Companion. Google, 2025. Whitepaper. Accessed 9 Oct. 2025. <https://www.kaggle.com/whitepaper-agent-companion>.\\n\\nJeong, Cheonsu, et al. \\"E2E Process Automation Leveraging Generative AI and IDP-Based Automation Agent: A Case Study on Corporate Expense Processing.\\" arXiv, 10 June 2025. Accessed 2 Oct. 2025. <https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.20733>.\\n\\nOpenAI. A Practical Guide to Building Agents. OpenAI, 2024. Business Guide. Accessed 9 Oct. 2025. <https://cdn.openai.com/business-guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-agents.pdf>.\\n\\nSingh Andley, Nupur, and Tony Olvet. Executive CIO QuickPoll: Operationalizing AI. IDC, Nov. 2024. IDC Market Presentation. Accessed 2 Oct. 2025. <https://my.idc.com/getdoc.jsp?containerId=US52703024>.\\n\\n\\n\\nMeagan Peters\\n\\nThomas Randall\\n\\n\\n\\nJustin St-Maurice\\n\\nRoss Tsenov \\n\\n\\n\\nBuild Your AI Strategy Roadmap\\n\\nRelated Info-Tech Research\\n\\nBuilding an AI strategy in this ever-shifting technological landscape can be a daunting process. This comprehensive blueprint will help you expedite your AI strategy process to allow you to deliver the quick wins that will propel your organization forward.\\n\\nGovern the Use of AI Responsibly With a Fit-for-Purpose Structure\\n\\nThis blueprint enables organizations to govern Ai responsibly by helping to identify key risks related to AI, defining a set of responsible AI principles, creating an AI governance structure, designed an AI governance operating model, and evaluating policy gaps using a policy framework. \\n\\nBuild Your AI Risk Management Roadmap\\n\\nIn this research, we help you to assess your current AI risk maturity and organizational buy-in, establish an AI risk council, how to govern, identify, measure, and respond to Ai risks, and create a method to monitor priority AI risks, consider possible responses, and continuously communicate these.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nGlossary\\n\\n\\n\\nNon-Agentic vs. AI Agent vs. Agentic AI\\n\\nAspect Non-Agentic AI AI Agent Agentic AI Definition Basic prompt-response AI: single input, single output, no memory or reasoning. Single-task AI worker: automates one repetitive job reliably. Self-managing AI: plans, executes, critiques, iterates on complex tasks. How It Works Processes single prompts in isolation, generating immediate responses without refinement. No context retained. User defines one responsibility. Accesses 1-2 tools to execute the task autonomously, outputting results without guidance. Breaks broad goals into sub-tasks. Connects to tools/data. Evaluates results with feedback and memory for continuous improvement. Use Cases Summarizing reports, rewriting emails, generating headline variations. Pulling weekly data from CRM, drafting automated customer service replies, generating expense reports. Researching competitors, managing ad campaigns, generating and refining onboarding flows. Pros Fast, cheap, accessible. No technical build. Great for one-off tasks. Automates repetitive tasks. Easy to test and refine for specific roles. Handles complex projects. Integrates tools, memory. Produces reliable outcomes. Cons No reasoning or context. Output depends on prompts. Struggles with multi-step work. Limited flexibility. Breaks if inputs are unclear. Needs orchestration with other agents. Slower, more expensive. Requires human oversight. Risk of overbuilding. How to Build Fast Use ChatGPT/Claude. Write clear, specific prompts. Copy output, edit, repeat. Define one repetitive task. Wrap LLM with tools (Zapier, OpenAI Assistants API). Connect to inputs/outputs, test thoroughly Use frameworks (LangChain, OpenAI Agent Sdk, AWS Bedrock Agents etc.) for tools and workflows. Assign roles (Planner, Executor). Add memory and feedback layers.\\n\\n\\n\\nCore AI Concepts and Architectural Approaches\\n\\nConcept Description Large Language Model (LLM) An advanced AI model that can understand and generate human-like text by predicting the next word in a sequence. AI Agent Software application powered by large language models that autonomously performs tasks and interacts with users and systems. Agent-Based System An approach where software agents work independently to solve problems through collaboration, delegation, and specialized knowledge. Task Automation The process of using AI to perform repetitive or complex tasks without human intervention, improving efficiency and reducing manual effort. Entity Memory A specialized form of AI memory that maintains detailed information about specific entities (people, organizations, concepts) across multiple interactions. Human-in-the-Loop (HITL) A system design approach that integrates human oversight and intervention points within automated AI processes. Multi-agent Pattern A structured approach to organizing multiple AI agents' interactions, including hierarchical, sequential, and dynamic patterns. Role-Based Agent Design An architectural approach where AI agents are assigned specific roles with defined responsibilities, tools, and interaction patterns within a larger system. State Management Systematically tracking and controlling an AI agent's internal conditions, memory, and context throughout its operation cycle. System Latency The time delay between when an AI agent receives input and when it provides a response.\\n\\n\\n\\nPerformance Metrics and Advanced Techniques\\n\\nConcept Description Context Window Utilization A metric measuring how efficiently an AI agent uses its available processing capacity for analyzing and retaining information. LLM Call Error Rate A critical reliability metric tracking the frequency of failed API requests and processing errors when an AI agent interacts with its underlying language model. Latency per Tool Call A performance indicator measuring the time delay between an AI agent's request to use a specific tool and receiving the tool's response. Output Format Success Rate A quality metric assessing how accurately an AI agent adheres to specified formatting requirements and presentation standards across different user roles and contexts. Steps per Task An efficiency metric tracking the number of discrete operations an AI agent requires to complete a given task. Task Completion Rate A comprehensive performance indicator measuring the percentage of assignments an AI agent successfully completes without human intervention. Tool Selection Accuracy A metric evaluating how appropriately an AI agent chooses specific tools or methods from its available toolkit based on task requirements and complexity. Prompting Techniques Research-backed methods to guide LLM behavior and reduce hallucinations in AI agents. Reflexion A specialized prompting technique that enhances an AI agent's reasoning capabilities through self-reflection and improvement. Task Decomposition The process of breaking down complex assignments into smaller, manageable subtasks for AI agents to handle effectively.\\n\\n\\n\\nOptimize LLM Accuracy \\u2014 Cheat Sheet\\n\\n1\\n\\n2\\n\\nStart with the Basics\\n\\nDiagnose the Failure\\n\\nPrompt Engineering: Craft clear instructions, provide few-shot examples, split complex tasks, and supply reference text.\\n\\nContext Gap? If the model lacks up-to-date or proprietary knowledge, consider Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).\\n\\nEvaluate Early: Build a robust test set and automated metrics (ROUGE/BERTScore/G-Eval) to track improvements from the outset.\\n\\nBehavior Gap? If the model has the knowledge but is inconsistent, explore Fine-Tuning or richer few-shot prompts.\\n\\n3\\n\\n4\\n\\nApply the Right Lever\\n\\nIdentify \\"Good Enough\\" Accuracy\\n\\nRAG: Inject real-time or domain-specific content for enhanced accuracy. Focus on tuning retrieval quality and noise control.\\n\\nAlign accuracy targets with business impact, weighing the cost of failures against potential savings.\\n\\nFine-Tuning: Train on high-quality, representative examples to achieve consistent style, tone, or reasoning.\\n\\nImplement risk controls such as confidence-based re-asks, human handoff points,