f2adc271-6177-44a2-a173-ade8713b2323	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx	{"name": "background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document", "size": 4820015, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768337907	437b1676e9a7323cf386390cc4e48440642c5eb19e52ec1c1a012072575f0c24	{"status": "completed", "content": "Modeling Patient Treatment in Primary Care: An Abstraction Hierarchy Incorporating Shared Decision Making to Understand User Competencies and Needs\\n\\nOriginal Paper\\n\\nJustin St-Maurice1 2 * and Catherine Burns1\\n\\n1System Design Engineering\\nUniversity of Waterloo\\n200 University Ave W, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1\\n\\n2Applied Health Information Science\\nConestoga College Institute of Technology and Advanced Learning\\n299 Doon Valley Drive, Kitchener, ON N2G 4M4\\n\\n*Corresponding Author: justin.st-maurice@uwaterloo.ca\\n\\nAbstract\\n\\nBackground:\\u00a0Primary care is a changing socio-technical system that needs to incorporate the use of technology and adopt new care paradigms, such as shared decision making. Work Domain models and Cognitive Work Analysis are effective tools for understanding these types of complex ecologies. The Ecological Interface Design approach consumes the results of work domain analysis to design improved systems. Due to their scope of work, some WDA characterize patients as biomedical machines, while others describe patient actors involved in their own care. An abstraction hierarchy that incorporates the Shared Decision Making paradigm and characterizes patients as beings with complex social values and priorities during treatment is needed to better understand treatment in primary care. \\nObjective: The purpose of this study was to perform a work domain analysis and generate an abstraction hierarchy to represent the treatment of patients in primary care. The model needs to be reflective of shared decision making approaches to patient care, and incorporate the realities of modern workflows associated with electronic medical records.\\nMethods:\\u00a0The methods to develop this model included the analysis of written texts and collaboration with subject matter experts. Our abstraction hierarchy represents the ecology through its functional purposes, abstraction functions, generalized functions, physical functions and physical forms.\\nResults:\\u00a0Compared to other abstraction hierarchies, the model is able to articulate the nuanced balance between medical treatment, patient education and limited healthcare resources. Concepts in the analysis were similar to the modeling choices of other work domain analyses but combined them in as a comprehensive, systematic and contextual overview. Our model also reflected concepts from the Shared Decision Making paradigm. The use of Shared Decision Making concepts helped created a better work domain model. The model is helpful to understand user competencies and needs.\\nConclusions: Our abstraction hierarchy links treatment goals, decision making constraints and task workflows. This model can be used by system developers who would like to use Ecological Interface Design to improve systems in primary care. Our hierarchy is the first in a future set that is needed to fully articulate Shared Decision Making. Future hierarchies could model the patient as a controller and could be useful for mobile application development. Incorporating Shared Decision Making concepts in team Cognitive Work Analysis could also prove valuable in trying to understand interdisciplinary teams. \\n\\nKeywords: Clinical decision-making, knowledge support systems, and theory; health services research; modelling; patient decision aids; qualitative research; shared decision making\\n\\nIntroduction\\n\\nHealthcare is considered a complex socio-technical system [1]. In an increasingly digitized world, primary care is no exception and has become technologically complex with the increased use of Electronic Medical Record (EMR) systems [2]. As well, there is a movement in primary care to move away from paternalistic healthcare approaches [3,4] and engage patients in their own care through Shared Decision Making (SDM) [5]. In this evolving environment, primary care clinicians have unique needs and require a rich set of competencies to practice medicine. \\n\\nThe field of human factors and environmental ergonomics has a variety of tools to help understand complex system ecologies, develop strategies to support users, and incorporate technology into user-centered workflows [6]. Various approaches have been used to develop models describing patient health and clinical decision making [7\\u201316]. Specifically, Cognitive Work Analysis (CWA) and Work Domain Analysis (WDA) [17] can help describe user decision making and competency requirements within complex socio-technical systems. A detailed CWA can help design more effective systems through the use of Ecological Interface Design (EID). For example, a model of anaesthesia [13] was used to support the development of auditory alarms [18], and a model of the cardiovascular system [16] was used in the design of clinical displays [19]. \\n\\nOne of the challenges of SDM is incorporating patient's values and preferences into decision making [20]. Future EMRs could better support clinicians in this challenging undertaking if treatment in this context was better understood. Thus, there is an opportunity to develop patient-centered WDA models to better understand primary care, its users and their changing ecology. Whereas WDA and EID could be helpful to further understand user competencies in primary care, the concepts underlying SDM could reciprocally help create more meaningful WDA models. Creating a comprehensive, systematic and contextual overview of the patient treatment in the primary care ecology could help designers and engineers improve systems design and support the integration of SDM paradigms. \\n\\nShared Decision Making\\n\\nPaternalistic approaches to healthcare are flawed by a failure to accept patients as equal partners [3]. Whereas physicians are experts in disease, patients are experts in their own experience of disease and in their preferences [4]. SDM refers to a form of healthcare decision-making where the patient and their practitioners make choices together that are informed by both the available evidence and the patient's values and preferences. There is a shift in health care towards SDM in Canada [21], which has been described as the crux of patient-centered care [4]. Engaging with patients through SDM also generates an opportunity to discuss \\"preference diagnosis\\", which is a crucial step in recommending appropriate treatments to patients [22]. Increasingly there is a need to understand how interdisciplinary teams of family physicians, nurse practitioners, pharmacists, medical specialists, caregivers and patients can work together to make informed and shared decisions about healthcare and treatment [23,24]. \\n\\nThough there are many definitions for SDM, the general qualities of treatment with SDM include deliberation with patients, an individualized approach, information exchange, involvement of multiple parties, finding middle ground, espousing mutual respect, developing patient education, encouraging patient participation, and following a process with stages [25]. Adopting SDM is important because inadequate patient involvement in decision-making can result in poor health outcomes\\u00a0[26].\\n\\nCognitive Work Analysis\\n\\nCWA is a conceptual framework that facilitates the analysis of complex systems at various levels of detail. It can help assess how the environment impacts and shapes human-information interactions [17]. Work Domain Analysis (WDA) is the first step of CWA that focuses on ecology. It can provide valuable information about the structure of work, articulate abstract concepts such as professional values and culture, and describe the constraints that operate in the work domain. WDA can describe how structures, abstract values and constraints affect the normal functions of a system [27]. CWA has previously been used in healthcare [12,14,15,18,28\\u201331].\\n\\nThe abstraction hierarchy is a modelling tool that describes the results of a WDA [17]. The abstraction hierarchy is intended to be a full depiction of the necessary constraints that need to be taken into consideration in order for the system to achieve its purpose, while describing the system's underlining ecology and limitations [32]. Using abstraction hierarchies can help bridge the psychology-culture-medicine gap in healthcare. These hierarchies can be used to develop representations of patient care that are align with biomedical knowledge, support medical problem solving and act as a frame of reference [8]. As a structured approach to WDA, the abstraction hierarchy includes a layer to describe the system's functional purposes, abstract functions, generalized functions, physical functions and physical forms. Lines are shown between each layer to show means-end or how-why relationships [32]. \\n\\nWork Domains, Patients and Patient Care\\n\\nThere have been many uses of abstraction hierarchies to describe patient health. Some of these abstractions treat patients as biomedical machines with physiological processes  [8,13,16,33,34]. For example, some models represent the human body in its resting state during anaesthesia [13], decompose the human body into systems and organs [12] or describe the cardiovascular system as an independent system [16]. The scope of these analyses are more biomedical in nature because they describe treatments and procedures, and occur after the implied or direct patient consultation. Within the confines of emergency or surgical care to unconscious patients, there are few opportunities to engage in SDM during the scope of treatment. In these contexts, 'aberrations in physiological and biological regulatory processes' are the 'domain upon which clinicians work' [33].\\n\\nIn other cases, patients are conscious and therefore capable participants in their own healthcare. Ashoori and Burns [14] modelled the patient-as-an-actor approach effectively during a study of a birthing unit. The CWA showed rich coordinative points, shared artefacts and adjusting structures, and described the patient as active partner that engaged in her own health. In another example, Rezai and Burns [15] modelled patient values, skills, support systems and abilities in a home healthcare scenario. Though this approach started to incorporate some of the ideas of SDM, the scope was focused on the patient's home environment after the patient had left primary care practice. Regardless, both examples demonstrate that CWA is capable of characterizing patients as emotionally complex, social creatures and that CWA can successfully describe the patient as a decision maker with rich sets of values and capabilities to support their own healthcare.\\n\\nNo existing abstraction hierarchies describe how treatment in primary care takes place with clinician-controllers and modern patient-partners that have a rich set of values and capabilities. A comprehensive and systematic overview of a system can be used to generate system improvement recommendations that take into account contextual information. For example, a macro-level view of medication administration in home care facilitated an in-depth understanding of medication safety problems and analyzed medication errors [31]. \\n\\nStudy Purpose\\n\\nThe purpose of this study was to create an abstraction hierarchy that represents patient care by clinicians in primary care. The scope of this model needed to be compatible with SDM. The model must characterize patients as beings with complex social values and priorities, and incorporate complex socio-technical workflows associated with EMR records. \\n\\nMethods\\n\\nStudy Context\\n\\nThe study was conducted through collaborations in Ontario. The concepts that were included in the model are reflections of a single-payer system in Canada, reflect a Canadian perspective on social determinants of health [35], and reflect a Canadian approach to the use of SDM [21]. The scope of the study included the development of a model to represent all types of primary care clinicians including, but not limited to, physicians, physiotherapists, nurse practitioners, dietitians, mental health workers and pharmacists.\\n\\nInformation Gathering\\n\\nThe development of the abstraction hierarchy took place over the span of 12 months. This included collaborating with 8 SMEs, iterating through various model concepts, gathering feedback and reworking the model. There were 10 iterations and versions of the abstraction hierarchy before the development of the final version.  In addition to working with SMEs, information for the WDA was collected by reviewing textbooks (such as pathophysiology textbooks [36] and health system textbooks [37]), best practice guidelines, professional standards [38,39] and literature [1,2,5,6,40\\u201345]. Insightful information and anecdotes were also gathered during previous research [46]. \\n\\nAbstraction Hierarchy Development\\n\\nThe development of abstraction hierarchies is challenging because there are many ways to model abstract concepts and ideas. Practitioners need to engage and observe users and articulate thoughts and suggestions into the abstraction hierarchy. Abstraction hierarchies are intended to be helpful, but not perfect, and managing scope and level of detail can be very challenging. \\n\\nThe first phase of a WDA is to determine the system boundary. There is a balance to achieve in the analysis: a domain boundary that is too narrow will leave out connections and interactions that exist outside the boundary whereas a broad boundary can distract the modelling effort as time is spent developing concepts that are not germane to the modelling objective [12].\\n\\nThe operator of the system domain was the primary care clinician and the boundary was restricted to activities that were within the clinician's control during a patient's use of services in a primary care clinic, even if they were indirect. The patient and their attributes were included in the scope of the analysis. Patient flows and activities outside of an encounter with a clinician were excluded from the scope (e.g. patient opting not to take medicines, performing exercises, adjusting diet, etc.). \\n\\nWorkflows representing patient flows (Figure 1) and information workflows (Figure 2) were developed with SMEs to describe the generalized activities of the clinic and its clinicians. As generalized workflows, not all components of the workflow were necessarily 'activated' during each patient encounter but represented possible workflows during a visit. In the case of patient flows, most use-cases within the clinic (involving a combination of triage, assessment, treatment, care transfer and scheduling) were captured. In the case of information flows, most use-cases involving the EMR (involving a combination of summarization, sharing, updating and interpretation) were also captured. These workflows were later translated into the 'Generalized Function' layer of the abstraction hierarchy. \\n\\nFigure 1 - Patient Flow Generalized Functions\\n\\n\\n\\nFigure 2 - Information Flow Generalized Functions\\n\\n\\n\\nUsing the boundary definition, previous work regarding medical records [46] and discussions with SMEs, five goals were developed to describe the purpose of treatment in the primary care ecology. These formed the 'Functional Purpose' layer of the abstraction hierarchy. Whereas a purely biomedical treatment goal would be to 'improve health', concepts such as patient education and public safety were included in the scope of patient treatment. \\n\\nAfter developing the system goals and the clinic workflows, a list of concepts that linked the generalized functions in the clinic and the system goals was developed. This included articulating abstract concepts such as values and balances and showing how system goals were mediated to perform functions. These concepts were translated into the 'Abstract Function' layer of the abstraction hierarchy. \\n\\nThe physical functions layer of the abstraction hierarchy represented concepts, objects and actors that were needed to perform the workflows. The physical form represented details and attributes of the objects and actors that were relevant to the system processes. For example, the social status and severity of symptoms were relevant attributes of the patient. \\n\\nModel Validation\\n\\nAfter developing each layer of the hierarchy, concepts were linked based on comments from SMEs and literature. We consulted with a family physician who volunteered to provide feedback after seeing drafts. While practicing over the course of a week, the physician took notes about the abstraction hierarchy and verified that all important concepts, workflows and decision making tasks, from a normal day of clinical practice were generally included in the model.\\n\\nResults\\n\\nThe patient flows and information flows were each placed into separate views of the same abstraction hierarchy (see Figure 3 and Figure 4). Showing two views increased the readability of the hierarchy and allowed each type of workflow to be displayed separately. Other than the generalized functions and specifically noted omissions, all elements of the model is shown in each view.  \\n\\n\\n\\n\\nFigure 3 - Abstraction Hierarchy 1.A \\u2013 Patient Functions\\n\\n\\n\\nFigure 4 - Abstraction Hierarchy 1.B \\u2013 Information Functions\\n\\n\\n\\nFunctional Purpose and Treatment Goals\\n\\nFive functional purposes were identified in the abstraction hierarchy. The treatment purposes (e.g. goals) included concepts of patient education, financial compensation, health improvement, sustainable care and public safety. These goals are linked to abstract functions which represent constraints to be respected in achieving each goal. In some situations, each goal is met during treatment. In other situations, one goal may take priority over the other. These concepts were created in consultation with SMEs.\\n\\nEducate Patient\\n\\nAs part of treating patients, clinicians aim to educate patients. This includes providing information about health conditions, treatments and lifestyle. Educating patients is an important goal in their treatment since poor education or incorrect information can interfere with treatment and must be taken into consideration as a goal. For example, some patients may not wish to be vaccinated based on individual patient beliefs about vaccination benefits and personal values. In this context, the overall goal of treating a patient is a combination of education, improving their health and ensuring public safety from communicable diseases. \\n\\nAs shown in the abstraction hierarchy, during treatment patient education is mediated by patient means and abilities (e.g. financially patients who cannot afford physio therapy might be educated about exercises instead of receiving a referral) and patient values (e.g. not believing in the value of a particular treatment). \\n\\nReceive Financial Compensation\\n\\nFor physicians in Ontario, there are fee-for-service payments issued by the Government, an insurance provider or by the patients themselves. In other situations, clinicians are salaried and employed by the Government to provide healthcare services and treat patients (such as clinicians who are part of a Family Health Team in Ontario) [37]. \\n\\nWhen physicians treat patients and receive financial compensation as a result, this is an important element to include in the model of treatment. While treatment could be modelled altruistically, payment to clinicians would impact the treatment approach. As mentioned by SMEs, some doctors adopt a 'one visit, one problem' approach to treatment to maximize potential remuneration. Since this decision is influenced by financial remuneration and not driven by best practice or health outcomes, this concept is important to capture in the abstraction hierarchy.\\n\\nAs shown in the abstraction hierarchy, compensation is mediated by a patient's resources (e.g. ability to pay uncovered costs and fees), best practice guidelines (e.g. Government bonuses for specific additional interventions, which are based on best practice guidelines), patient flow (e.g. volume and theoretical maximum billable time), system resources (e.g. the Government purse), professional values and training (e.g. what services can be performed and opting to select strategies favouring maximum remuneration), balancing risks versus benefits (e.g. determining if receiving compensation for the treatment is worth any potential risks or benefits to the patient), and professional standards (e.g. what actions are permitted, ethical and appropriate). \\n\\nImprove Patient Health and Wellness\\n\\nThe most obvious goal of patient treatment is to improve their health and wellbeing. Patients who are not looking to improve their health or wellbeing (directly or indirectly) will not seek treatment. Improving patient health is mediated by patient resources (e.g. financial ability to pay clinicians when required, and afford drugs, or social supports to support care), the ability to actually see the patient (e.g. patient flow), patient values and beliefs (e.g. willingness to accept recommendations), best practice guidelines, health system constraints (e.g. scheduling constraints for referrals), physiology and psychology principles, professional values and training (e.g. what treatment can be performed) and balancing the costs and benefits of a treatment plan.\\n\\nProvide Sustainable Care\\n\\nIn Ontario, clinicians need to select appropriate tests and treatments that support a sustainable healthcare system. Clinicians need to avoid unnecessary procedures that are of limited clinical value. For example, patients may request 'fad' bloodwork (e.g. vitamin test without clinical reasons). Unlike fully privatized healthcare systems, clinicians need to make treatment choices that respect the public purse and support a sustainable healthcare system by ensuring diagnostics are medically necessary. This type of conflict resolution is challenging [4] and is important to include as a constraint in treatment.\\n\\nSustainable care is moderated by best practice guidelines, patient flow (e.g. volume and capacity), system constraints (e.g. budgetary limits), professional values (e.g. caring about the public purse), and professional standards of care (e.g. guidelines). \\n\\nEnsure Public Safety\\n\\nClinicians need to place individual patient treatment into the context of public safety. Patients who are a danger to others, who have communicable diseases or whom could endanger their community in other ways (e.g. poor eyesight in a senior citizen who drives) may require treatment that is not related to the patient's personal wellness, education or the sustainability of care. Ensuring public safety is moderated by professional values and training, the balancing of risks versus outcomes, and professional standards. This also has an impact on many information flows (e.g. mandatory reporting requirements).\\n\\nAbstract Functions and Treatment Constraints\\n\\nAbstract functions represent constraints that need to be respected during workflows (e.g. generalized functions) in order to achieve the system goals. These concepts were created in consultation with SMEs.\\n\\nBalance Patient Means & Abilities \\n\\nPatient means (e.g. financial, social) and abilities (e.g. mental competency, self-care) need to be balanced and considered in their treatment. For example, a physician will need to take a patient's ability to pay for drugs when issuing a prescription or recommending physiotherapy. Likewise, an elderly patient's access to peer groups and family would impact their ability to live at home or require homecare. This constraint influences treatment functions and plays a role in how medical records are processed and summarized for sharing. \\n\\nPatient Values & Beliefs\\n\\nPatients have varying worldviews and values that need to be understood and balanced during treatment. For example, some religions would prevent blood transfusions, some cultures will not tolerate birth control, some peer groups adhere to false information about vaccines and some patients will not be comfortable with the genders of their clinician for specific procedures. This abstract concept plays a role in patient assessment and treatment workflows. It may also play a role in how information is shared with the patient and distributed, such as a patient making decisions about their privacy rights [47]. These constraints are represented by this abstract function.\\n\\nBest Practice Guidelines\\n\\nBest Practice Guidelines suggest health screenings, preventative tests and appropriate actions for patients with specific characteristics (e.g. age, diagnosis, etc.). Guidelines are used in prescribing treatment functions (e.g. recommending a test), care transfer functions (e.g. sending a patient to a stroke unit) and are important when reviewing medical history. To manage the scope of the analysis, specific guidelines and guideline documents were not included in the Physical Function of the abstraction hierarchy. The constraints on treatment that are associated with best practice guidelines are represented through this abstract function.\\n\\nPatient Flow Patient\\n\\nFlow is a representation of patients entering, moving through, and exiting the system. Patient flow also represents limits related to patient volume and throughput. Patient volume is an important constraint on the system as the flow of the patient through the clinic and the healthcare system must be taken into consideration, and is important for all generalized functions. \\n\\nBalance System Resources and Constraints\\n\\nAs a single payer, publicly-funded healthcare system, healthcare dollars and resources in Ontario must be taken into consideration during treatment. Not all drugs or treatments are available, and some procedures have significant waiting lists due to insufficient system resources (e.g. number of beds, number of surgeons, etc.). This abstract function describes a constraint in selecting treatment options for patients while achieving treatment goals. \\n\\nPhysiology and Psychology Principles\\n\\nHuman anatomy, physiology and pathophysiology principles are important constraints to be taken into consideration during treatment. When patients are suffering from situations that are not strictly biomedical in nature (e.g. social distress, isolation, stress, etc.) psychological principles need to be taken into account. This abstract function describes constraints during triage, patient assessment, treatment and transfer of care. From an information perspective, these principles are important when clinicians interpret results and data.\\n\\nProfessional Values and Training\\n\\nClinicians are not uniform in their decisions. Like patients, clinicians have worldviews, professional values and priorities. For example, physicians may choose to see more patients in a day (e.g. volume) and provide care to a large number of patients, or may choose to see fewer patients for full assessments to provide higher quality care. Worldviews may also impact ethical decisions, such as valuing the public purse. A professional's scope of practice, practice style and set of priorities is based on training and personality characteristics. This abstract value system plays a role in assessing patients, performing treatments and deciding when it is appropriate to transfer care. It also plays a role in a clinician's interest in creating high quality documentation that is above minimum standards. Patient and documentation workflows are constrained by professional values and training.\\n\\nBalance Risks, Costs and Outcomes\\n\\nWhenever a treatment is provided to a patient, there are risks, possible outcomes and costs. If a clinician determines there is a very high risk and a very low probability of a positive outcome, another treatment option may be selected. Similarly, a clinician may balance the healthcare costs of surgery for an arthritic patient versus a prescription, and make a treatment determination that is based on total costs, recovery periods and quality of life. Risk balancing takes place in consultation with patients who describe their preferences and capabilities. In situations where patients pose a risk to public safety, a clinician must make an appropriate determination between risks and potential negative outcomes to the patient and public.\\n\\nThis abstract concept plays a role in assessments and treatments. Risks are also evaluated when choosing to transfer care. Information functions assist in determining risk.\\n\\nProfessional Standards\\n\\nAll clinicians are governed by professional bodies. For example, physicians in Ontario are governed by the College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario (CPSO). The CPSO establishes specific conditions and training requirements for all physicians in Ontario. They have policies on medical records [38] and permissive reporting of information [39]. This concept constrains patient assessment, prescription and treatment, transfer of care, and maintaining, reviewing, updating and sharing medical records. To manage the scope of the domain analysis, the standards documents were not included in the scope of the model and are not included in the Physical Function of the abstraction hierarchy.\\n\\nInformation Flow\\n\\nInformation Flow is a representation of information that enters the system, is used and is stored in an EMR. Information flow is important in managing care and impacts decision making and timing. If information is not available when needed, it will impact many aspects of treatment. As an abstract concept, information flow is important through all information functions in the Generalized Function layer of the model. Information flow impacts financial compensation (e.g. ability to bill and document encounters), patient health (e.g. improved care quality through information) and public safety (e.g. reporting mandatory situations).\\n\\nGeneralized Treatment Workflows\\n\\nThe generalized functions represented the general workflow functions in primary care, as described in Figure 1 and Figure 2. Each generalized function was linked to abstract function constraints that needed to be respected in order to achieve the system goals.\\n\\nPhysical Treatment Elements and Attributes\\n\\nThe physical functions layer of the abstraction hierarchy represents concepts, objects and actors that were needed to perform the workflows in the generalized functions. The physical form represent details and attributes of the objects and actors that were relevant to the system processes. Keeping in mind that the clinician is the system controller (and not represented in the physical form), the relevant actors and objects in the abstraction hierarchy include the patient, the type of assessment, clinic staff, the level of care, forms and medical records. \\n\\nPatient\\n\\nThe patient is obviously an important actor associated with all generalized functions. The patient attributes that are relevant in treatment include patient family and friends (e.g. presence of social supports to facilitate treatment), the patient's biopsychosocial status (e.g. social circumstances such as employment, stressors, etc.), the severity of the patient's symptoms or problems, and the complexity of the clinical case. The patient and their most important attributes are included in the model as they impact the entire treatment ecosystem.\\n\\nAssessment Type\\n\\nThere are different types of assessments. A physical exam would be detailed, whereas a 10 minute assessment would be problem-oriented. Other assessments may play the role of triage and refer a patient directly to the hospital. Severity and complexity play a role in the type of assessment that will be used with the patient. \\n\\nClinic Staff\\n\\nThe clinical staff support many processes. Depending on the specializations and location of the primary care clinic, there may be more or less resources. Larger clinics with multiple clinicians will have a larger support staff with specific roles and responsibilities. Smaller clinics with an individual doctor may only have a single support resource who plays a generalist role. The type of staff and their abilities varies according to location of the practice.\\n\\nLevel of Care\\n\\nThe level of care (e.g. primary care) varies according to location of the practice and impacts the scope of treatment for the patient. \\n\\nForms\\n\\nThere are many forms that support the information processes during treatment. The location of the forms and their type (paper or electronic) are relevant attributes.\\n\\nMedical Record\\n\\nMedical records support all the information flow processes. The location of the status (e.g. availability), record type (e.g. paper or electronic) and the location of the system are relevant attributes.\\n\\nDiscussion\\n\\nThrough this study we created an abstraction hierarchy to represent the findings of a primary care WDA. The abstraction hierarchy was developed through collaborations with Subject Matter Experts (SMEs) and represents the rich primary care ecology during treatment decision making. The model needed to incorporate SDM concepts during patient flows (e.g. assessment, treatment, etc.) and information flows (e.g. reviewing patient history, updating records, etc.)\\n\\nShared Decision Making and Cognitive Work Analysis\\n\\nThe concept of SDM was incorporated at several points of the abstraction hierarchy. In the functional purpose of the hierarchy, patient education is shown as an objective for the clinician, as well as aiming to negotiate towards sustainable care. Sustainable care ties into examples provided to describe decisional conflict [4,26] and articulates the source and remediation of potential conflict between the clinician and the patient. The tensions around decisional conflict are described by the constraints of the abstraction hierarchy. \\n\\nSDM was also reflected in the abstract functions of the hierarchy. The hierarchy describes the incorporation of patient values, beliefs and abilities into the treatment and assessment processes. Balancing risks based on individual patients is another reflection of SDM thinking. From a treatment perspective, our model articulates the additional constraints that clinicians must respect and shows that the incorporation of SDM complicates the decision making ecology. \\n\\nThough the development of our model, we noted a synergy and compatibility between SDM and CWA. We found that SDM can support CWA by contributing to the thought process of model development and could be used to make stronger CWA models. Reciprocally, we have created an abstraction hierarchy that is compatible and friendly with the SDM paradigm.\\n\\nIt is important to note that SDM is not always easy for clinicians to implement and there are barriers to its use in patient care: in addition to requiring more time, it might also not apply to the patient's characteristics or their clinical situation [23]. Our abstraction hierarchy does not assume that all elements are 'activated' in each patient encounter. Thus, our model is able to accommodate the concepts of SDM but is also able to represent situations where SDM is not feasible or applied. \\n\\nDesign Implications\\n\\nPrimary care users have many responsibilities with the introduction of EMRs and SDM. Users need to balance antithetical data requirements. On one hand they must capture sometimes vague and generalized information to support a nuanced biopsychosocial medical model [40]. On the other hand, they must act as an aggregator of highly structured data regarding each patient's longitudinal story on behalf of the healthcare system [43]. Though this dichotomy may appear technical in nature, the challenges are also rooted in several cultural aspects of primary care [41]. Given the broad potential uses of primary care data [42,43], there are interesting opportunities and challenges for vendors looking to create effective solutions. As primary care data is used in creative new ways [44,45], understanding primary care users, their capabilities and their workflows is important in order to ensure systems are effectively designed to support their tasks. \\n\\nWDAs and abstraction hierarchies are consumed during design by using the EID approach [29,48]. Our abstraction hierarchy will support system designers by properly articulating the ecosystem and clinician decision-making in context. The model supports system thinking and can help articulate how changes may impact the ecosystem through linear and ripple effects. [49]. Based on our analysis, the decision support requirements for primary care system are actually quite complex. The challenge for system engineers will be to determine how electronic systems could be support, and not hinder, the treatment process in primary care and to support SDM in its designs.\\n\\nLimitations\\n\\nOur abstraction hierarchy is intended to be helpful, but not perfect. The model is limited to a clinician's perspective and aims to provide a high level overview of treatment. There are obvious opportunities for a deeper analysis of the work domain in special areas. For example, there are complex nuances to medication prescription and administration that have been abstracted in our model as 'Prescribe / Perform Treatment' and it would be possible to do a more detailed WDA on this specific issue. For example, Lim, Anderson and Buckle developed a detailed analysis of medication administration in home care [31] and this could be performed in primary care. In this sense, our work is incomplete. In this same sense, the amount of modelling to be performed is infinite and our hierarchy is a contextual overview that could serve as a blueprint for additional work in primary care abstraction hierarchies.\\n\\nFuture Work\\n\\nOur model is novel in its marriage of SDM, WDA and future design. Future hierarchies could further develop the idea of the patient as a controller [15] and use a stricter SDM paradigm. This would be useful for mobile application development and could articulate decision making constraints from a patient perspective. The combination of a provider model and patient model to understand decision making could prove very helpful.\\n\\nAnother interesting area of work regards interdisciplinary team decision making: building on the demonstrated compatibility of SDM and CWA, team-based CWA [50] could be helpful to  understand how teams of family physicians, nurse practitioners, pharmacists, medical specialists, care givers and patients work together to make informed and shared decisions about care [23,24]. \\n\\nConclusions\\n\\nOur abstraction hierarchy links primary care treatment goals, decision making constraints and task workflows. Our model articulates the immense task complexity and nuanced approach to decision making in primary care. The model can help identify user needs in future system designs. Our model can be used by system developers to improve systems in primary care by better supporting complex decision making in context. Our hierarchy is a contextual overview of the primary care treatment domain from a clinician's perspective and additional models could further articulate depth and details in sub-domains of the system. Our model could support the development of EMRs that incorporate the cognitive processes associated with patient treatment in primary care. \\n\\n\\n\\nAcknowledgements\\n\\nWe'd like to thank our team's Engineering and Science Librarian for her assistance in identifying relevant work regarding shared decision making. We'd also like to thank our SMEs for providing insight and feedback regarding our work domain analysis. \\n\\nConflicts of Interest\\n\\nNone declared.\\n\\nAbbreviations\\n\\nCWA: Cognitive Work Analysis\\nCPSO: College of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario\\nEID: Ecological Interface Design\\nEMR: Electronic Medical Record\\nSDM: Shared Decision Making\\nSME: Subject Matter Expert\\nWDA: Work Domain Analysis\\n\\nReferences\\n\\n1. \\tJiancaro T, Jamieson GA, Mihailidis A. Twenty Years of Cognitive Work Analysis in Health Care: A Scoping Review. J Cogn Eng Decis Mak. 2013;8(1):3\\u201322. doi:10.1177/1555343413488391\\n\\n2. \\tGagnon M-P, Desmartis M, Labrecque M, L\\u00e9gar\\u00e9 F, Lamothe L, Fortin J-P, et al. Implementation of an electronic medical record in family practice: a case study. Inform Prim Care. 2010;18(1):31\\u201340. PMID:20429976\\n\\n3. \\tCharles C, Gafni A, Whelan T. Decision-making in the physician-patient encounter: Revisiting the shared treatment decision-making model. Soc Sci Med. 1999;49(5):651\\u2013661. PMID:10452420\\n\\n4. \\tWeston WW. Informed and shared decision-making: the crux of patient-centered care. CMAJ. Can Med Assoc; 2001;165(4):438\\u20139. PMID:11531054\\n\\n5. \\tElwyn G, Frosch D, Thomson R, Joseph-Williams N, Lloyd A, Kinnersley P, et al. Shared Decision Making: A Model for Clinical Practice. J Gen Intern Med. Springer; 2012;27(10):1361\\u20131367. doi:10.1007/s11606-012-2077-6\\n\\n6. \\tSaleem JJ, Russ AL, Sanderson P, Johnson TR, Zhang J, Sittig DF. Current challenges and opportunities for better integration of human factors research with development of clinical information systems. Yearb Med Inform. 2009;48\\u201358. PMID:19855872\\n\\n7. \\tCarayon P, Wetterneck TB, Rivera-Rodr