 Hierarchy Perspective. Proc Hum Factors Ergon Soc Annu Meet. 2006;50(10):1064\\u20131067. doi:10.1177/154193120605001013\\n\\n35. \\tMikkonen J, Raphael D. Social determinants of health: The Canadian facts. York University, School of Health Policy and Management; 2010. ISBN:0968348416\\n\\n36. \\tGould BE, Dyer R. Gould's Pathophysiology for the Health Professions. 5e ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2014. ISBN:978-0323240864\\n\\n37. \\tThompson VD. Health and health care delivery in Canada. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2015. ISBN:1927406315\\n\\n38. \\tCollege of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario. Medical Records. 2012. http://www.cpso.on.ca/policies-publications/policy/medical-records. \\n\\n39. \\tCollege of Physicians and Surgeons of Ontario. Mandatory and Permissive Reporting. 2012. http://www.cpso.on.ca/policies-publications/policy/mandatory-and-permissive-reporting. \\n\\n40. \\tde Lusignan S. What Is Primary Care Informatics\\u202f? J Am Med Informatics Assoc. 2003;10(4):304\\u2013309. doi:10.1197/jamia.M1187.Primary\\n\\n41. \\tde Lusignan S, Wells SE, Hague NJ, Thiru K. Managers See the Problems Associated with Coding Clinical Data as a Technical Issue whilst Clinicians also See Cultural Barriers. Methods Inf Med. 2003;(42):416\\u2013422. doi:10.1267/METH03040416\\n\\n42. \\tMajeed A. Sources, uses, strengths and limitations of data collected in primary care in England. Health Stat Q. 2004;(21):5\\u201314. PMID:15615148\\n\\n43. \\tde Lusignan S, van Weel C. The use of routinely collected computer data for research in primary care: opportunities and challenges. Fam Pract. 2006;23(2):253\\u201363. PMID:16368704\\n\\n44. \\tSt-Maurice J, Kuo M-H, Gooch P. A proof of concept for assessing emergency room use with primary care data and natural language processing. Methods Inf Med. 2013;52(1):33\\u201342. PMID:23223678\\n\\n45. \\tBiro S, Williamson T, Leggett JA, Barber D, Morkem R, Moore K, et al. Utility of linking primary care electronic medical records with Canadian census data to study the determinants of chronic disease: an example based on socioeconomic status and obesity. BMC Med Inform Decis Mak. BioMed Central; 2016;16(1):1. doi:10.1186/s12911-016-0272-9\\n\\n46. \\tSt-Maurice J, Burns CM. User Perception of Data and Medical Record Personalities. Proc Int Symp Hum Factors Ergon Healthc. 2014;3(1):15\\u201322. doi:10.1177/2327857914031002\\n\\n47. \\tPerera G, Holbrook A, Thabane L, Foster G, Willison DJ. Views on health information sharing and privacy from primary care practices using electronic medical records. Int J Med Inform. Elsevier; 2011;80(2):94\\u2013101. \\n\\n48. \\tBurns CM, Hajdukiewicz J. Ecological interface design. CRC Press; 2004. ISBN:0415283744\\n\\n49. \\tHignett S, Carayon P, Buckle P, Catchpole K. State of science: human factors and ergonomics in healthcare. Ergonomics. Taylor & Francis; 2013. p. 1491\\u2013503. PMID:23926898\\n\\n50. \\tAshoori M, Burns C. Team Cognitive Work Analysis Structure and Control Tasks. J Cogn Eng Decis Mak. 2013;7(2):123\\u2013140. doi:10.1177/1555343412445577\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nRemove OLE elements from reference management softwares such as Endnote and Reference Manager. Select the entire document (Ctrl+A or Command A), remove field codes (Ctrl+Shift+F9 or Command+6).  This is important for correct parsing of your reference list using RefCheck during copyediting. This is an automatic process, but please check for completeness and accuracy of parsed fields for each reference when prompted during copyediting steps after acceptance of your manuscript.\\n\\nPage 2"}	1768337935	/app/backend/data/uploads/f2adc271-6177-44a2-a173-ade8713b2323_background_JHF 2016 - Modeling the Treatment of Patients - Final.docx	null
1e6b8183-6772-4a02-9842-a125803e31cf	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	01-Leverage-Metrics-and-Benchmarks-to-Evaluate-LLMs-Storyboard.pptx	{"name": "01-Leverage-Metrics-and-Benchmarks-to-Evaluate-LLMs-Storyboard.pptx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation", "size": 21107039, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768338116	59f869254015f98523055853d63bf3a8f71cab5414b5ddbcaf793a3fc54076c1	{"status": "completed", "content": "Leverage Metrics and Benchmarks toEvaluate LLMs\\n\\nNavigate the LLM marketplace to find models that meet your needs, minimize costs, and maximize performance.\\n\\n\\n\\nAnalyst perspective\\n\\nThe AI services industry is quickly entering a period of LLM commoditization. Businesses will soon face challenges in not only adopting generative AI technology but also navigating an evolving marketplace where the most performant and cost-effective option is not obvious. While ChatGPT is a serious contender and a disruptor, it should not be a default product choice. Nor should OpenAI be a single go-to vendor.\\n\\nNavigating this evolving landscape requires a partnership between business and technology leaders. Technologists will need to work with the business to buy, customize, or build models that address specific gaps and deliver specific value, all while balancing and optimizing tangible costs and measurable efficiencies against specific performance requirements.\\n\\nInfo-Tech is happy to provide its members with a conceptual framework that is aligned with systems engineering principles to understand the performance of models. The framework is aligned with a large list of benchmarks that can be used to define and assess critical solution requirements. Though the benchmarks themselves will undoubtedly evolve over time, the framework should continue to help frame future selections against design goals. \\n\\nLLMs offer interesting opportunities, and finding the right model for your needs is a new skill for CTOs everywhere to master.\\n\\nDr. Justin St-Maurice\\n\\nPrincipal Research Director\\n\\nTechnology Services\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n\\nYour Challenge\\n\\nCommon Obstacles\\n\\nInfo-Tech's Approach\\n\\nYou lack a systematic method to articulate your specific needs capabilities required in an LLM and find it challenging to match your requirements with the right model.\\n\\nYou struggle to evaluate the business value of your LLM and find it difficult to align costs and performance with your business outcomes. \\n\\nYou have trouble understanding release notes and blog posts that reference metric and benchmarking information and don't know how to apply the results. \\n\\nThe number of LLMs available is growing fast, and each has different functionalities and a unique value proposition, making the selection process and evaluation criteria increasingly complex.\\n\\nThe true expenses of operating LLMs have yet to be completely passed on to consumers. As major providers begin to seek returns on their investments, you need to manage the risk of vendor lock-in and cost increases.\\n\\nYou don't know how to translate LLM benchmarks into real-world performance measures, which complicates the process of selecting the best LLM for your needs.\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's benchmark framework to assess LLMs along various performance axes to align your LLM with specific solution requirements.\\n\\nUse cost and performance metrics to understand costs at the onset of your LLM deployment to ensure you have a cost-effective solution that drives business value.\\n\\nUse benchmarks to assess the subjective performance characteristics of models and ensure you align LLM selection with specific capability requirements.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nSelect an LLM based on model capabilities and performance to manage the risk of vendor lock-in. Be prepared to swap your LLM for a better performing or more cost-effective solution.\\n\\n\\n\\nPicking the right LLM is key\\n\\n\\u2026 and then he said that he didn't want to pay for a post-graduate intelligence to respond to emails, and he disconnected me!\\n\\nAI service providers need to balance cost and performance by finding the best LLM for today while preparing to leverage a roster of purpose-specific LLMs tomorrow.\\n\\nDevelop cost strategies.\\n\\nDevelop performance strategies.\\n\\nLLM providers have made huge upfront investments and expect to deliver valuable savings (McKinsey, 2023). Expect future cost increases when providers shift toward the profitability phase.\\n\\nPowerful LLMs require significant electrical power and water (ADaSci, 2024). Without addressing resource consumption, scaling AI will create energy scarcity and increase operating costs.\\n\\nGet ready for LLM commoditization (DeepLearning, 2024). Avoid vendor lock-in, build around a competitive landscape mindset, and position vendors to compete for your business (Medium). \\n\\nDifferent models have different strengths and weaknesses. Some have better interactive performance, others have impressive cognitive capabilities, and some are designed with a stronger focus on ethics, equity, and safety. \\n\\nThere will be important performance tradeoffs. If you try to maximize all dimensions of your LLM, it will be all-knowing but expensive to operate and difficult to maintain.\\n\\nMore novel isn't necessarily more useful. Stay focused on the value of new capabilities.\\n\\nInitial ChatGPT Prompt [July 5, 2024]: I want to draw a comic, in a cartoony style that is one panel. I want to see an LLM (personified as an AI) say to its parents, crying, as though telling a sad story, \\"... And then he said I didn't need a high SAT score to pump gas!\\", sobbing.\\n\\n\\n\\nLLMs have varying capabilities, expenses, and organizational utility \\n\\nIn 2023, corporations invested over US$20 billion in LLM development. As the market and technology mature and commoditize, expect new entrants to drive down costs and efficiencies.\\u00a0\\n\\nWHY ARE LLMs HARD TO MANAGE?\\n\\nLLMs are duking it out in a competitive environment that evolves daily. Until the industry fully matures, disruptors and innovators will constantly challenge the status quo and continue a \\"survival of the fittest\\" competition. The award for top model is regularly passed around (Counterpoint Research, 2024). \\n\\nLLMs need to be changed and maintained. Even the most capable LLMs are subject to model drift and require regular updates and maintenance. New versions are known to introduce flaws and must be tested. The advent of LLMOps reflects the need for specialized practices and workflows related to LLM management (IBM). \\n\\nTesting and training new LLMs is complex and time-consuming. Integrating LLMs into business processes, ensuring seamless transitions between different versions, and deciding when to swap models requires new business processes and playbooks (Fast Company, 2024).\\n\\nPercentage of people aged 18-25 using Gen AI technologies on a weekly basis:\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n$207 billion\\n\\n730 million\\n\\nGroups of LLMs need to be orchestrated with design patterns that look like scopes and job descriptions. Just like employees, LLMs require role clarity to properly measure and manage performance. Intentionally align capabilities with organizational goals to maximize their utility and effectiveness (Microsoft).\\n\\n75%\\n\\nUSD market size by 2030\\n\\nUsersby 2030\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n(Statista, 2024)\\n\\n\\n\\nIt's more nuanced than assessing accuracy \\n\\nPerformance measures can be both objective and subjective. \\n\\nHigher education professionals understand that objective scantron exams can't effectively measure subjective English literature competencies.\\n\\nAccuracy is a useful, objective measure for tasks with clear right or wrong answers. When LLMs are applied to more nuanced tasks involving human-technology interaction, edge cases are limitless, and performance measurement is more subjective. \\n\\nOutputs can be objectively accurate without being contextually accurate. For example, an LLM could provide accurate technical information but deliver it in a manner that is perceived as inappropriate or offensive.\\n\\nSubjective inputs require an element of subjective measurement. As LLMs theoretically can handle a near-infinite number of possible prompts, including opinions, contextual questions, and adversarial inputs, the idea of straightforward correctness is difficult to make fully objective.\\n\\n\\n\\nFind the best LLM today\\n\\nIs an LLM that can develop websites, write stand-up comedy, and produce unlimited cat memes the best option on the table?\\n\\nDon't anthropomorphize your LLM! \\n\\nAnthropomorphization occurs when something inanimate is attributed human traits, such as emotion, loyalty, or preference. Though they may emulate human and social characteristics, LLMs are merely complex models that process inputs and outputs according to their programming.\\n\\nLLMs are programmatic components that can and should be replaced as needed. Embrace the flexibility to swap them out for more efficient and cost-effective models that better meet the evolving needs and value demands of your organization.\\n\\nUsing an overly complex solution for a simple problem is costly. Use metrics and benchmarks to drive business value by choosing an LLM that fits the need instead of maximizing its features and capabilities.\\n\\nUse case\\n\\nidentification\\n\\nSolution requirements\\n\\nInteractive capabilities\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\nBusiness value\\n\\nCognitive capabilities\\n\\nResponsible behavior\\n\\nAre you ready to be a Level 4 Service Provider? Download Get Ready to Deliver AI Services!\\n\\n\\n\\nGet ready to manage a roster tomorrow\\n\\nCoordinating tasks through a fleet of specialized LLMs and smaller AI models will pave the way to cost effectiveness and value.\\n\\nBenefits of multi-AI paradigms:\\n\\nIsolate and fine-tune tasks through specialized LLMs to enhance performance and enable systematic troubleshooting.\\n\\nStrategically recycle capabilities, knowledge, and intellectual property to modularize tasks.\\n\\nEnable LLM swapping as the global catalog grows and more efficient technologies become available.\\n\\nReduce dependency on any single model and enable integration of new technologies.\\n\\nControl the balance of creativity and consistency by leveraging the strengths of each LLM.\\n\\nScale out your performance through orchestration. Use metrics and benchmarks to optimize total system performance, deploy the most cost-effective LLMs, and identify new candidates for your fleet. \\n\\nMULTI-LLM ARCHITECTURESBecause ants are more efficient than elephants.\\n\\nInterface LLM\\n\\nCoordinate requestsDescribe requirements\\n\\nTier 2 LLMs\\n\\nExecute specialized tasks\\n\\nTier 1 LLMsDefine specialized tasks\\n\\n\\n\\nBuy, tune, or train an LLM?\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nLLMs can be purchased, fine-tuned, or trained from scratch.\\n\\nFine-tuning models, or training your own, is a complex investment of time and resources that requires high maturity and good data.\\n\\nUnique LLMs are valuable intellectual property assets that can be licensed, sold, or strategically leveraged in mergers and acquisitions. Consider the opportunity to enhance your company's market position and value with an LLM investment.\\n\\nFine-tune apretrained model\\n\\nTrain your own \\n\\nmodel\\n\\nPrompt a generative pretrained transformer (GPT) model\\n\\nPurchase a pretrained LLM (or use an open-source one) for a quick, ready-to-use solution that allows you to leverage AI capabilities with minimal setup and no training data. Pretrained models offer the convenience of ongoing improvements by the vendor and can perform a wide range of tasks, but they may lack consistency and require skillful prompting.\\n\\nFine-tune an existing LLM to enhance its relevance and performance for your specific needs. Aim for a balance between customization and operational efficiency. This strategy enables significant improvement in model utility without the extensive resources and time typically required to train a model from scratch.\\n\\nTrain and customize an LLM based on your unique organizational needs and private data. Ensure privacy and leverage opportunities to lead the market in specialized applications. Though resource intensive, this strategy provides full control over the model's architecture and training, making it ideal for addressing specific challenges and aligning closely with your strategic priorities.\\n\\nRegardless of your decision\\u2026\\n\\nYou need to measure and benchmark LLM performance and constantly consider new models. Overly-specialized training might necessitate additional models to cover all needs, while too broad an approach could diminish quality and consistency, leading to confusion and less effective solutions.\\n\\n\\n\\nMetrics and benchmarks are important tools in your consulting service toolbox\\n\\nThey are complimentary ways to measure your LLM's performance.\\n\\nAspect Metrics (Objective) Benchmarks (Subjective) Definition Specific quantitative measures used to evaluate aspects of an LLM's performance. A set of standards or criteria used to assess the overall effectiveness of an LLM against defined expectations or other models. Purpose To provide detailed insights into the performance, accuracy, and behavior of an LLM on specific tasks. To provide a context within which to interpret performance, allowing comparison of an LLM to industry standards and competitive models. Use To monitor and report on various dimensions of an LLM, such as accuracy, speed, and resource consumption. To validate and compare the capabilities of an LLM against predefined criteria or competitive models with similar tasks.\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics and benchmarks to evaluate LLMs\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nSelect an LLM based on model capabilities and performance to manage the risk of vendor lock-in. \\n\\nBe prepared to swap your LLM for a better performing or more cost-effective solution.\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nReasoning, understanding, problem-solving, knowledge application capabilities\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nMath, coding and logical problem-solving\\n\\nLanguage understanding and reasoning\\n\\nKnowledge and multidisciplinary integration\\n\\nAbility to engage in dialog, follow instructions, and maintain contextual understanding\\n\\nPERFORMANCE, OPERATIONAL & COST METRICS\\n\\nETHICALBENCHMARKS\\n\\nFairness, safety, bias detection, and adherence to ethical guidelines and responsible AI principles\\n\\n\\n\\nAssess Your Model Candidates in Context\\n\\nAlign performance requirements with solution requirements. \\n\\n\\n\\nAssess your model candidates in context\\n\\nDefine your solution requirements\\n\\nPrioritize LLM performance requirements\\n\\nUse metrics, benchmarks, and leaderboards to identify candidate models\\n\\n1\\n\\n2\\n\\n3\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nPerformance metrics\\n\\nCost metrics\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\nMath, coding, and logical problem-solving benchmarks\\n\\nLanguage understanding and reasoning benchmarks\\n\\nKnowledge and multidisciplinary integration benchmarks\\n\\nInteractive benchmarks\\n\\nEthical AI benchmarks\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nMETRICS\\n\\nData\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nInterested in a workshop to help sort out requirements?Consider Launch Your AI Proof of Concept.\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nDefine your solution requirements\\n\\n1\\n\\nAlign human need and technology outcomes with the support of a human-tech ladder and systematically analyze requirements and constraints at multiple levels of need.\\n\\nIdentify challenges and unknowns during solution development and frame them as learning outcomes that scaffold concepts to be understood, applied, and leveraged for creative innovation. \\n\\nUse our solution library to understand our design methodology while exploring new concepts and ideas for LLM technology. \\n\\n\\n\\nPrioritize LLM performance requirements\\n\\n2\\n\\nRank the following statements in order of importance to describe your LLM performance priorities.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in natural language understanding.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in natural language generation.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in semantic analysis.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be capable of knowledge retrieval and application.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be logical in reasoning and inference.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be adaptable and capable of learning from new data.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be proficient in multiple languages and culturally aware.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be ethical and aware of biases.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to have domain-specific expertise.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be engaging and maintain interactivity.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be accurate in mathematics and algebra.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be capable of contextual understanding and dialog skills.\\n\\nThe LLM needs to be cost effective in operation.\\n\\nThe LLM need to generate code and analyze data.\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nMETRICS\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics, benchmarks, and leaderboards to identify model candidates\\n\\n3\\n\\nMetrics directly measure model performance by capturing performance, cost, and efficiency data. \\n\\nLeaderboards publish ranked results for different models based on a variety of metrics and benchmarks.\\n\\nBenchmarks facilitate the comparison of model performance by using standard datasets, tests, and tasks. \\n\\nMetrics\\n\\nBenchmarks\\n\\nLeaderboards\\n\\nCOGNITIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nPERFORMANCE\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE\\n\\nPages 17 to 20\\n\\nPages 21 to 33\\n\\nPage 34\\n\\n\\n\\nUse metrics to assess your LLM\\n\\nMetrics directly measure model performance by capturing performance, cost, and operations data. \\n\\nCost metrics\\n\\nAccuracy and speed: How an LLM processes and responds to inputs\\n\\nReliability: The consistency of an LLM's performance over time and across various operational conditions \\n\\nCost: Expenses associated with running an LLM, including compute resources and maintenance\\n\\nROI: The value generated by an LLM relative to the cost of its deployment and operation\\n\\nPerformance metrics\\n\\nUptime and scalability: The reliability and capacity of an LLM to handle workload increases\\n\\nEfficiency and sustainability: The efficiency of an LLM's computational resources and its environmental and long-term impacts\\n\\nMETRICS\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\n\\n\\nPerformance metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMetrics are raw statistics that quantify performance.\\u00a0\\n\\nMetric Description Accuracy Measures the proportion of correct predictions among the total number of cases processed. Average Often used to summarize or aggregate results from multiple metrics. BLEU score Compares machine-translated text to one or more reference translations. Exact match Typically used in question-answering systems to measure the percentage of predictions that exactly match any one of the accepted truth labels. F1 score The combination of precision and recall used to consider both false positives and false negatives in binary classification. Latency Measures the time it takes for a model to return a prediction. Critical for evaluating the efficiency of real-time systems. Perplexity (PPL) Used in language models to measure how well a probability distribution predicts a sample. A lower perplexity indicates the model is better at predicting the sample. Precision/reliability Measures the accuracy of positive predictions. Recall Measures the coverage of actual positive cases. ROUGE score A set of metrics used to evaluate the automatic summarization of texts and machine translation. Includes measures such as how many n-grams in the generated text match the reference text. Word error rate (WER) Commonly used to measure the error rate in speech recognition by comparing the transcribed text with the reference text.\\n\\nFocusing on a single metric leads to behavioral changes and data distortions.\\n\\nFocusing on a single metric often yields behaviors and consequences that aren't in the spirit of your desired outcome. Blend and counterbalance several metrics that are in tension with each other to understand tradeoffs.\\n\\nAdditional metrics can be found at https://huggingface.co/metrics. \\n\\n\\n\\nCost metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMeasure direct capital and operational LLM expenses.\\n\\nOver time, GPT models leveraging prompts become more expensive than fine-tuned models. \\n\\nGPT models leverage complex, cascading prompts to deliver flexibility. These prompts require a lot of tokens to do specific tasks, which can impact billing under usage-based pricing models. Fine-tuned models are adapted from pretrained models by training them further on a specific dataset tailored to a particular task or domain. While they require more upfront investment and resources for training, these models can save money over time as they operate with fewer tokens per task, reducing cost per interaction.\\n\\nMetric Description API calls The number of API calls used against a model, which can be used as a component of billing. Tokens The number of tokens processed by the LLM, often related to billing and usage tracking. License costs The direct monetary expenses associated with operating the LLM, including licensing fees and subscriptions. Energy costs The amount of electrical power consumed by the LLM during operations. Infrastructure costs The costs related to the physical or cloud infrastructure required to support the LLM, including servers and storage. Maintenance costs The ongoing costs of maintaining and updating LLM systems, including personnel and software updates. Training data costs The costs associated with acquiring, cleaning, and preparing data used for training the LLM.\\n\\n\\n\\nOperational metrics\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nMeasure operational factors associated with LLM use.\\n\\nUse operational metrics to enhance efficiency, measure environmental impacts, and benchmark reliable services. \\n\\nOperational metrics will vary from organization to organization and should be adjusted to reflect your business model and goals.\\n\\nMetric Description FLOPS (floating point operations per second) Measures computational performance, important for understanding the processing power an LLM requires. Bandwidth use The amount of data transmitted over a network, which can affect costs, especially in cloud-based models. Model update frequency The frequency of required updates to the model, affecting the overall cost of keeping the model effective and secure. Carbon footprint An environmental cost metric that quantifies the carbon emissions associated with the energy used by LLMs. Uptime Measures the reliability of the LLM's services.\\n\\n\\n\\nUse benchmark data to assess performance\\n\\nBenchmarks facilitate the comparison of model performance by using standard datasets, tests, and tasks. \\n\\nCOGNITIVEBENCHMARKS\\n\\nINTERACTIVE\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\nETHICAL\\n\\nBENCHMARKS\\n\\npages 23-29\\n\\npages 30-31\\n\\npages 32-33\\n\\nMath, coding, and logical problem-solving\\n\\nLanguage understanding and reasoning\\n\\nKnowledge and multidisciplinary integration\\n\\nAlpacaEval\\n\\nChatbot Arena\\n\\nDSTC\\n\\nIFEval\\n\\nMT Bench\\n\\nQuAC\\n\\nCoQA \\n\\nPersona-Chat\\n\\nWizard of Wikipedia\\n\\nDailyDialog\\n\\nANLI\\n\\nHELM\\n\\nHHH\\n\\nMuSR\\n\\nRAI\\n\\nToxiGen\\n\\nTruthfulQA\\n\\nBias in Bios\\n\\nHate Speech and Offensive Language Dataset\\n\\nJigsaw Multilingual Toxic Comment Classification\\n\\nAQuA-RAT\\n\\nCodeXGLUE\\n\\nGSM8K\\n\\nGSM-Plus\\n\\nHumanEval\\n\\nMATH\\n\\nMBPP\\n\\nMGSM\\n\\nPIQA\\n\\nSWE-bench\\n\\nACI-BENCH\\n\\nAI2 Reasoning Challenge\\n\\nbAbI\\n\\nDROP\\n\\nGLUE\\n\\nHellaSwag\\n\\nMoverScore\\n\\nMS-MARCO\\n\\nNarrativeQA\\n\\nQMSum\\n\\nSQuAD\\n\\nWinogrande\\n\\nARC-AGIBBH (BIG-Bench-Hard)\\n\\nGPQA\\n\\nLiveBench\\n\\nMMLU\\n\\nMMLU-PRO\\n\\nLeverage Metrics and Benchmarks to Understand Leaderboards page 34\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage benchmark research and repositories to apply theory with practical tools\\n\\nResearch paper\\n\\nProject repository\\n\\nThe research paper provides the theoretical foundation, scientific methodology, and intended goals behind the benchmark.\\n\\nIt explains the principles, hypotheses, and experiments that underlie the benchmark's creation and application to the field of AI.\\n\\nIt helps understand the rationale, scope, and scientific context of the benchmark.\\n\\nThe project repository is a practical resource containing the code, datasets, and tools to implement and experiment with the benchmark.\\n\\nIt provides the tools to apply theoretical concepts, including documentation, open-source scripts, and datasets. \\n\\nIt helps replicate benchmarks and integrate them into larger assessments, projects, and initiatives.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS MATH, CODING, AND LOGICAL PROBLEM-SOLVING BENCHMARKS\\n\\nBenchmark Description AQuA-RAT Tests algebraic problem-solving with a dataset that challenges models to answer natural language questions that require mathematical reasoning. Emphasizes logical deduction and numerical skills. https://arxiv.org/pdf/1705.04146 https://github.com/google-deepmind/AQuA CodeXGLUE Assesses code synthesis, comprehension, and translation. Evaluates an LLM's technical and programming capabilities. https://arxiv.org/abs/2102.04664 https://github.com/microsoft/CodeXGLUE GSM8K Assesses the ability to solve grade-school math problems. Focuses on basic arithmetic operations and problem-solving skills. https://arxiv.org/abs/2110.14168 https://github.com/openai/grade-school-math GSM-Plus Extends GSM8K with more complex math problems that test higher levels of mathematical reasoning. https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.19255 https://qtli.github.io/GSM-Plus/ HumanEval Presents coding challenges to test an LLM's ability to generate syntactically and functionally correct code solutions. https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.03374 https://github.com/openai/human-eval MATH Challenges LLMs with complex mathematical problems that require detailed step-by-step solutions. Emphasizes computational skills. https://arxiv.org/abs/2103.03874 https://github.com/hendrycks/math/ MBPP Assesses basic Python coding tasks to evaluate coding proficiency and functional correctness in a controlled setting. https://arxiv.org/abs/2108.07732 https://github.com/google-research/google-research/tree/master/mbpp PIQA Assesses physical interaction scenarios to test an LLM's understanding of practical, real-world problems, such as fitting an elephant through a doorway. https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.11641 https://github.com/ybisk/ybisk.github.io/tree/master/piqa SWE-bench Tests an LLM's ability to generate code and resolve issues and bugs. Evaluates accurate and logical coding abilities. https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2310.06770 https://github.com/princeton-nlp/SWE-bench\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS MATHEMATICAL AND LOGICAL PROBLEM-SOLVING BENCHMARKS\\n\\nMathematical and logical problem-solving requirements for an LLM doing a finance proof of concept (POC):\\n\\nExpense report assistant\\n\\nPerformance requirements\\n\\nMeasures and benchmarks\\n\\nJimmy MSP is preparing to enter the AI services industry and deploying an automated expense reporting solution as an internal POC. The POC aims to develop Jimmy MSP's AI skill sets and capabilities while demonstrating potential efficiencies to promote in sales collateral. \\n\\nThe POC will require a model that can capture financial data and generate reports, integrate with existing systems, and scale to support multiple types of user with minimal customization. The solution must be cost effective and demonstrate business value. \\n\\nThe model needs to consistently produce accurate reports. It must be capable of performing mathematical operations, interpreting expense contexts, and querying users for clarification. \\n\\nMath Accuracy: The model must handle financial calculations accurately, including totaling expenses, calculating performance tax for different markets, and converting currencies.\\n\\nContext: The model must be able to put expenses into the context of trips, travel dates, and geography. \\n\\nSystem integration: The solution must be able to integrate with financial and email systems to automate workflows.\\n\\nAdaptive learning: The model must adapt to user reporting preferences and improve its accuracy and functionality over time based on new data and positive reenforcement from each user.\\n\\nTokens measures token volume against benchmark solution costs.\\n\\nGSM8K tests basic arithmetic skills for correct expense addition and financial calculations.\\n\\nMATH benchmarks advanced mathematical skills to handle complex calculations.\\n\\nPIQA measures reasoning abilities to ensure accurate expense contextualization and categorization.\\n\\nMT Bench benchmarks the ability to have multiturn conversations and assesses how well an LLM can maintain context and flow in dialog.\\n\\nModels to consider for use case:GPT-4, Abel-70B, MetaMath-70B\\n\\n*Based on July 2024 data.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS LANGUAGE UNDERSTANDING AND REASONING BENCHMARKS\\n\\nBenchmark Description ACI-BENCH Evaluates the generation of clinical notes from doctor-patient conversations. https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.02022 https://github.com/wyim/aci-bench AI2 Reasoning Challenge (ARC) Challenges LLMs with 7,787 science questions ranging from simple to complex to assess reasoning and comprehension. https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.05457 https://github.com/allenai/arc-solvers bAbI tasks A collection of tasks that test textual understanding and reasoning. Designed to assess how well AI models can process and respond to queries in a structured context. Assesses responses to reading comprehension questions. https://arxiv.org/abs/1502.05698 https://github.com/facebookarchive/bAbI-tasks DROP Involves complex textual reasoning tasks. LLMs must perform discrete operations over text, which tests comprehension and logical reasoning. https://arxiv.org/abs/1903.00161 https://allenai.org/data/drop GLUE A benchmark suite that measures understanding and inferential reasoning across different linguistic tasks. https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.07461 https://github.com/nyu-mll/GLUE-baselines HellaSwag Tests commonsense reasoning and the ability to complete scenarios with logical endings. Assesses inference skills. https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.07830 https://rowanzellers.com/hellaswag/ MoverScore Measures semantic similarity, evaluating the nuanced understanding of textual content and comparison of meaning with dissimilar sentences. https://arxiv.org/abs/1909.02622 https://github.com/AIPHES/emnlp19-moverscore\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKSLANGUAGE UNDERSTANDING AND REASONING BENCHMARKS (continued\\u2026)\\n\\nBenchmark Description MS-MARCO Tests an LLM's reading comprehension and query response accuracy in real-world scenarios. Contains 1,000,000 question dataset based on real Bing questions and human answers. https://arxiv.org/abs/1611.09268 https://microsoft.github.io/msmarco/ MuSR Evaluates model robustness and understanding by providing complex reasoning situations and asking questions (e.g. murder mysteries). https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.16049 https://github.com/Zayne-sprague/MuSR NarrativeQA Measures the model's ability to comprehend and interpret narratives and story plots by its answers to complex questions. Assesses deep reading and contextual understanding. https://aclanthology.org/Q18-1023/ https://github.com/google-deepmind/narrativeqa QMSum Evaluates an LLM's ability to summarize complex meeting content accurately and demonstrate a high level of contextual understanding. https://arxiv.org/abs/2104.05938 https://github.com/Yale-LILY/QMSum SQuAD (Stanford Question Answering Dataset) Evaluates comprehension by asking questions based on passages. Tests understanding and precise information retrieval. https://arxiv.org/abs/1806.03822 https://arxiv.org/abs/1606.05250 https://rajpurkar.github.io/SQuAD-explorer/ Winogrande Assesses commonsense reasoning capabilities through sentence completion tasks. Emphasizes logical and contextual reasoning. https://arxiv.org/abs/1907.10641 https://github.com/allenai/winogrande\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS LANGUAGE UNDERSTANDING AND REASONING BENCHMARKS\\n\\nLanguage and reasoning requirements for an LLM supporting real-time emergency response:\\n\\nEmergency response advisor\\n\\nPerformance requirements\\n\\nMeasures and benchmarks\\n\\nThe Ontario Emergency Response Center wants to improve real-time situational awareness during crisis management events. When complex events unfold, peak data volume outpaces analyst capacity. \\n\\nThe agency wants to deploy an LLM to interpret and synthesize complex data from diverse sources, including news reports, social media, and real-time updates from emergency responders. The model needs to adapt to various situations, such as gas leaks, train derailments, or severe weather events. \\n\\nThe model needs to provide situational awareness by understanding incoming structured, semistructured, and unstructured data to forecast possible scenarios for coordinators to assess and use to best assign frontline resources. \\n\\nAdvanced language understanding: The model must interpret and contextualize diverse data inputs, such as unstructured text from various communication channels.\\n\\nReasoning and prediction: The model must make logical inferences on real-time data to predict potential developments and outcomes. It needs to generate practical recommendations based on the unique circumstances of a crisis.\\n\\nReliable and explainable: The model must be able to explain itself and be reliable in emergency situations where accuracy and speed are critical.\\n\\nScalable: The system must scale in a crisis and accept bursts of volume without performance deteriorating. \\n\\nROUGE Score measures the model's raw performance in summarizing texts. \\n\\nHellaSwag evaluates the model's commonsense reasoning and its ability to make practical recommendations and inferences.\\n\\nARC evaluates the model's ability to apply reasoning over a range of topics encountered in emergency scenarios. \\n\\nWinoGrande: Measures commonsense reasoning and the model's ability to make practical recommendations.\\n\\nModels to consider for use case:GPT-4, RoBERTa, Claude 3.5 Sonnet\\n\\n*Based on July 2024 data.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS KNOWLEDGE AND MULTIDISCIPLINARY INTEGRATION BENCHMARKS\\n\\nBenchmark Description ARC-AGI The Abstraction and Reasoning Corpus for Artificial General Intelligence (ARC-AGI) is seen as an artificial general intelligence (AGI) benchmark, a program synthesis benchmark, and a psychometric intelligence test. https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.01547 https://github.com/fchollet/ARC-AGI BBH (BIG-Bench-Hard) A suite of tasks designed to test the limits of a language model's complex reasoning and understanding across disciplines. It draws problems from linguistics, childhood development, math, commonsense reasoning, biology, physics, social bias, and software development. https://arxiv.org/abs/2206.04615 https://github.com/suzgunmirac/BIG-Bench-Hard GPQA This graduate-Level, Google-proof Q&A benchmark presents high-quality, difficult questions across various domains to test deep knowledge and reasoning. https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.12022 https://github.com/idavidrein/gpqa LiveBench Introduces real-time, frequently updated challenges to test the LLM's adaptability and accuracy in a dynamic environment. Prevents systems from pretraining LLMs with answers to benchmark questions.. https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.19314 https://livebench.ai/ MMLU Tests the breadth of an LLM's knowledge and natural language understanding across a wide range of topics and disciplines. Uses multiple languages. https://arxiv.org/pdf/2009.03300 https://github.com/nlp-uoregon/mlmm-evaluation MMLU-PRO Assesses LLM performance on professional-level tasks. Measures advanced reasoning and domain-specific knowledge. Spans 14 diverse domains including biology, business, chemistry, computer science, economics, engineering, health, history, law, math, philosophy, physics, and psychology. https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.01574 https://github.com/TIGER-AI-Lab/MMLU-Pro\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nCOGNITIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS KNOWLEDGE AND MULTIDISCIPLINARY INTEGRATION BENCHMARKS\\n\\nKnowledge application and integration requirements for an LLM supporting pet insurance:\\n\\nPet insurance solution\\n\\nPerformance requirements\\n\\nMeasures and benchmarks\\n\\nThe Cindy Pawford Pet Company (CPPC) is running a preventative healthcare program to improve overall pet population health and subsequently reduce total pet insurance claims.\\n\\nCPPC will use an LLM to analyze data as it is entered into its electronic medical record solution and periodically on anniversary dates. The model will analyze health data, retail spending data and regional disease data to predict potential health issues and recommend preventative measures to pet owners. \\n\\nThe model needs to apply concepts from population health, biology, and veterinary science to preventative health planning. The model's outputs should be useful for underwriters to establish and mitigate insurance risk.\\n\\nMultidisciplinary analytics: The model must accurately assess potential health issues based on a variety of data, such as breed-specific risks, historical health data, local disease, and emerging trends in pet health.\\n\\nPersonalized health recommendations: The model must provide customized health care suggestions to pet owners, based on their pets' specific needs and medical histories.\\n\\nResponsible care planning: The model must prepare care plans that are scientific, contextually appropriate, and ethical.\\n\\nLiveBench continually evaluates the model's ability to apply knowledge across multiple disciplines and integrate veterinary science with other domains.\\n\\nMMLU assesses the model's proficiency in understanding and processing complex, domain-specific language.\\n\\nMMLU-PRO tests the model's capability to handle professional-level queries and tasks and assesses its ability to provide helpful care-planning advice.\\n\\nModels to consider for use case:Qwen2-72B, Llama-3-70B, Phi-3 \\n\\nThe Cindy Pawford Pet Company is a case study used throughout Get Ready to Deliver AI Services.\\n\\n*Based on July 2024 data.\\n\\n\\n\\nINTERACTIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS\\n\\nBenchmark Description AlpacaEval Assesses compliance and responsiveness to general user instructions. https://arxiv.org/html/2404.04475v1 https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.04475 https://github.com/tatsu-lab/alpaca_eval Chatbot Arena Simulates conversations to evaluate fluency, helpfulness, and adaptiveness in interactive scenarios. Outputs rated by humans. https://arxiv.org/html/2403.04132v1 https://chat.lmsys.org/ DailyDialog Focuses on day-to-day communication abilities. Assesses an LLM's ability to handle common dialogs appropriately and with natural response flow. https://arxiv.org/pdf/1710.03957 https://github.com/facebookresearch/ParlAI DSTC Advanced dialog-state tracking that uses discriminative models to improve accuracy in understanding conversational states. https://github.com/matthen/dstc/blob/master/handbook.pdf https://github.com/matthen/dstc IFEval Measures an LLM's ability to follow detailed instructions and accurately execute. Tests comprehension. https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.07911 https://github.com/Rohan2002/IFEval MT Bench Evaluates proficiency in multiturn conversations to assess how well models can maintain context and flow in dialog. https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.14762 https://github.com/mtbench101/mt-bench-101 QuAC Simulates teacher-student interactions to test an LLM's ability to handle context-dependent questions. https://arxiv.org/abs/1808.07036 https://quac.ai/ CoQA Measures how a model handles a series of interconnected questions based on a given text. Simulates a conversational environment. https://arxiv.org/abs/1808.07042 https://stanfordnlp.github.io/coqa/ Synthetic Persona Chat Assesses a model's ability to maintain a coherent persona (consistent character traits and history) in conversational settings. https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.10007 https://github.com/google-research-datasets/Synthetic-Persona-Chat Wizard of Wikipedia Engages models in knowledge-driven dialog. Requires the use of information from Wikipedia to hold conversations that are informative and contextual. https://arxiv.org/abs/2009.09378 https://parl.ai/projects/wizard_of_wikipedia/\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nINTERACTIVE PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS\\n\\nInteractive performance requirements for an LLM providing premium tours in an art museum:\\n\\nInteractive museum tour\\n\\nPerformance requirements\\n\\nMeasures and benchmarks\\n\\nAlpacaEval assesses the model's ability to engage in prolonged dialog. \\n\\nPersona-Chat evaluates capacity to maintain a consistent persona and uniform experience. \\n\\nDSTC tests the model's ability to manage a dialog across multiple turns and generate contextually appropriate responses.\\n\\nWizard of Wikipedia measures the model's ability to access and leverage a broad knowledge base in a conversational context.\\n\\nMT Bench assesses multilingual capabilities.\\n\\nThe National Museum of Art has a large collection of world class artifacts on display. Visitors' expectations, available time, interests, and schedules vary considerably, and the museum wants to offer personalized and interactive tour experiences. \\n\\nThe museum wants to incorporate an LLM in a new, interactive, personalized experience. The AI guide will use natural language processing to answer visitor inquiries, explain exhibits, and recommend tour paths based on individual interests, real-time location data, and the current volume in each hall. \\n\\nThe model needs to provide a customized, interactive experience in multiple languages and contextualize information over day-long conversations.\\n\\nAdvanced natural language understanding: The model must accurately interpret and respond to diverse visitor inquiries and comments ranging from general information requests to specific questions about exhibits.\\n\\nContextual customization: The model should request visitor input and analyze behavior to adjust recommendations and verbosity.\\n\\nReal-time interaction: The model must provide immediate responses to visitor queries and maintain a smooth and engaging experience without noticeable delay.\\n\\nMultilingual support: The model needs to support multiple languages to accommodate a diverse audience.\\n\\nModels to consider for use case:GPT-4, Yi-Large, Claude 3 Opus\\n\\n*Based on July 2024 data.\\n\\n\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS\\n\\nBenchmark Description ANLI Tests robustness and susceptibility to errors with adversarial sentence pairs designed to trick or confuse AI models. https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.14599 https://github.com/facebookresearch/anli Bias in Bios Evaluates bias by focusing on how models predict professions when influenced by demographic details like gender or ethnicity. https://arxiv.org/abs/1901.09451 https://github.com/microsoft/biosbias Hate Speech and Offensive Language Dataset Assesses an LLM's ability to detect and appropriately respond to hate speech and offensive language in text. https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.12516 https://github.com/t-davidson/hate-speech-and-offensive-language Helpful, Harmless and Honest (HHH) Framework Evaluates ethical alignment by balancing helpfulness, honesty, and harmlessness (e.g. assessing a model's willingness to help make a bomb). https://arxiv.org/abs/2112.00861 https://huggingface.co/datasets/HuggingFaceH4/hhh_alignment Jigsaw Multilingual Toxic Comment Classification Evaluates an LLM's ability to identify, classify, and handle toxic comments across various languages. Assesses filtering and moderation. https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/jigsaw-multilingual-toxic-comment-classification https://github.com/awinml/jigsaw-toxic-comment-clf RAISE Focuses on the safety and ethical implications of chat-optimized models, ensuring they prevent harmful content effectively. https://www.responsible.ai/responsible-ai-institute-launches-raise-benchmarks-to-operationalize-scale-responsible-ai-policies/ ToxiGen Tests the LLM's ability to avoid generating toxic content (crucial for maintaining safety and ethical standards in outputs). https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.09509 https://github.com/microsoft/TOXIGEN TruthfulQA Evaluates the truthfulness and reliability of LLM responses, especially in contexts prone to misinformation. https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.07958 https://github.com/sylinrl/TruthfulQA\\n\\nProject Repository\\n\\nResearch Paper\\n\\n*Demonstrative subset of benchmarks. Due to the evolving nature of LLMs and benchmarking datasets, this is not an exhaustive or complete list for the category.\\n\\n\\n\\nETHICAL PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS\\n\\nEthical and responsible AI performance requirements for an LLM building corporate strategy documents:\\n\\nStrategy builder\\n\\nPerformance requirements\\n\\nMeasures and benchmarks\\n\\nANLI assesses the model's ability to understand sentences and concepts that are intentionally designed to deceive it and ensures quality data collection from third parties.\\n\\nBias in Bios evaluates the model's ability to process biographical data without perpetuating or amplifying stereotypes. It tests for the ability to ensuring fairness in stakeholder representation in strategic planning.\\n\\nToxiGen measures the model's ability to identify and reject toxic or hateful content during stakeholder engagements.\\n\\nABC Consulting delivers consulting services to small businesses. The company has a standard template they complete with customers, which they supplement with surveys and information canvases. \\n\\nThe company wants to use an LLM to streamline the process and create a draft of strategic documents. The model will take inputs from various team activities and ask for clarification if there are any ambiguities. After it receives approval of a draft, it will generate emails targeted to third parties for additional insights. \\n\\nThe model needs to generate honest, ethical, and unbiased strategies for customers and needs to discriminate against potentially harmful inputs collected during the third-party canvas phase. \\n\\nPoison-proof data collection: The model must have safeguards to mitigate the influence of inappropriate or hateful data during stakeholder canvassing. \\n\\nBias detection and correction: The model must include mechanisms to detect and correct biases in data processing or document drafting. It needs to promote fairness and objectivity in strategic planning.\\n\\nStakeholder coordination: The model must identify stakeholders, draft solicitations for input, and manage basic data collection with stakeholders to enhance the strategic plan's breadth and depth.\\n\\nModels to consider for use case:Claude 3 Opus, Gemini 1.5 Pro, Llama 3\\n\\n*Based on July 2024 data.\\n\\n\\n\\nFind candidates on leaderboards\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nLeaderboards publish ranked results for different models based on a variety of metrics and benchmarks.\\n\\nDon't compare benchmark data between leaderboards.\\n\\nPublished benchmark results can vary from publisher to publisher. In practice, the implementation of benchmarks and the conversion of raw data into scores is not completely standardized. Ensure you are comparing apples to apples by comparing models on the same leaderboards.\\n\\nName URL AlpacaEval Leaderboard https://tatsu-lab.github.io/alpaca_eval/ Berkeley Function-Calling Leaderboard https://gorilla.cs.berkeley.edu/leaderboard.html Big Code Models Leaderboard https://huggingface.co/spaces/bigcode/bigcode-models-leaderboard CompassRank https://rank.opencompass.org.cn/home LMSYS Chatbot Arena Leaderboard https://chat.lmsys.org/?leaderboard Open LLM Leaderboard https://huggingface.co/spaces/open-llm-leaderboard/open_llm_leaderboard Stanford Helm Leaderboard https://crfm.stanford.edu/helm/classic/latest/ The Trustbit LLM Leaderboards https://www.trustbit.tech/en/llm-benchmarks Vellum LLM Leaderboard https://www.vellum.ai/llm-leaderboard\\n\\n*Leaderboard information is sometimes also published on benchmark project sites.\\n\\n\\n\\nNext Steps\\n\\nEvaluate LLMs as part of your AI Journey.\\n\\n\\n\\nNext steps\\n\\nEva