a5fa091a-8b97-4ae1-b468-3ad01f3c91c9	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	24C4.1 - 3361 - v2.1 - Wireframe Your GenAI Solution Design - FINAL.pptx	{"name": "24C4.1 - 3361 - v2.1 - Wireframe Your GenAI Solution Design - FINAL.pptx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation", "size": 36506869, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}}	1768338169	\N	{"status": "pending"}	1768338169	/app/backend/data/uploads/a5fa091a-8b97-4ae1-b468-3ad01f3c91c9_24C4.1 - 3361 - v2.1 - Wireframe Your GenAI Solution Design - FINAL.pptx	null
6be7df1d-68d9-40f7-8da0-bab0e82be3a7	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	Presentation Catalogue vAugust-29-2025.docx	{"name": "Presentation Catalogue vAugust-29-2025.docx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document", "size": 114425, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768337868	99253df51683dc735d03068678c1f8d4c341d83bcaf694d4e331a57e43f861d0	{"status": "completed", "content": "Justin St-Maurice \\u2013 AI Presentation Catalogue\\n\\nLast updated: July 11, 2025\\n\\n\\n\\nName: Dr. Justin St-Maurice\\n\\nBiography: Dr. Justin St-Maurice has a diverse background spanning informatics, systems design, and cloud engineering, which he uses today to innovate in the field of AI Systems Design. With over 20 years of experience in technology management, research, and education, he brings a human-centered, systems-thinking mindset to modern service delivery and helps his clients see the north star in their tactical projects and strategic initiatives. He applies his expertise to develop cloud strategies, create prototypes, and demonstrate novel uses of LLM technologies. He is a frequent keynote speaker known for his humor and style.\\n\\nPrior to joining Info-Tech, Justin held technology roles in postsecondary education, primary healthcare, and high-growth technology companies. He has served as a Senior Technical Product Manager, operated a VAR business, and was an executive leader during the height of the COVID-19 pandemic. His portfolio includes modern cloud-native solutions, peer-reviewed contributions in systems design research, and teaching awards at the postsecondary level. Outside of work, Justin is a certified ACC coach, Vice-President of the Guelph Hiking Trail Club, a cellist in the Cambridge Symphony Orchestra, and an aspiring curler at the Guelph Curling Club.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nBring AI Out of the Shadows\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nType\\n\\nA majority of your team is already using Generative AI, whether you like it or not. If you're like most organizations, you struggle with AI enthusiasm and inadvertently leaving the most promising use cases and ideas hidden the shadows. Former professor-turned-technical-counselor, Dr. Justin St-Maurice, talks about what pushes people in the shadows and explains how Shadow AI is an opportunity, and a call to action. Learn about the opportunities and gotchas of Generative AI, what's truly possible with these new tools, and get ready to enable your existing workforce for new, scalable capabilities via actionable insights.\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nKeynote Presentation\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nAgentic AI Architecture and Core Components\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nEnterprise Architecture; Software Developers\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nWe'll explore emerging multi-agent design patterns and introduce the BRAINS (Broad-Range Artificial Intelligence Node System) framework. This modular approach outlines how to integrate key components (including LLM gateways, MCP servers, and controller modules) to build scalable, secure, and interoperable AI systems. We'll review the architecture, highlight emerging multi-agent patterns, and demonstrate working prototypes built using serverless technology. Ideal for technology leaders, AI architects, and innovation professionals looking to advance their AI infrastructure.\\n\\nType\\n\\nWebinar\\n\\nLength\\n\\n120 minutes (60 minutes per core component)\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nRapid Prototyping with Generative AI\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral / Software Developers / Business Analysis\\n\\n\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nWant to see rapid prototyping with AI in action? In this session we're going to use Cursor AI and Claude 4.0 to add features to a functional app! Test the app and make feature requests to our volunteer Product Manager, and see AI quickly add the functionality. Learn about communicating business requirements and concepts, negotiate with other audience members and walk away with a customized version of the app on your phone.\\n\\nType\\n\\nInteractive Workshop\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nThe Impact of GenAI Tools on Work OR\\n\\nUnpacking Generative AI: Beyond Traditional Tech\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nGenerative AI behaves unlike any technology we've encountered before. In this interactive presentation, we delve into its inherently non-deterministic, often chaotic, and uniquely powerful nature. We'll uncover how its returns on investment manifest in hard, soft, contextual, and deeply personal ways, challenging traditional metrics. Understand how GenAI challenges the very nature of work by examining different types of cognitive impact through practical, real-world case studies and examples.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLive Demonstration\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nLessons and Gotchas with Generative AI\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nGenerative AI behaves unlike any technology we've encountered before. Through examples of image generation, gain a deeper understanding of how Generative AI works. Learn to appreciate its exploratory nature, embrace hallucinations and randomness for what they are, and recognize its output as opinion rather than fact. Through comics and examples, discover the playful and chaotic aspects of Generative AI and understand the importance knowing its limits, while embracing its potential.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLive Demonstration\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nLeverage Generative AI to Create Unique Visuals for Presentations\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nLearn to communicate your ideas using Generative AI image generation and start creating memorable visuals for your presentations today! See how to draw your thoughts, describe your vision, roll the dice and, eventually, accept the output of your prompts. Join to see the iterative development of a comic, a unique example of data drift and learn how to add this capability to your presentation toolkit.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLightning Talk\\n\\nLength\\n\\n5 minutes (can be expanded!)\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nDesign With the Human-Tech Ladder\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nThis session reviews the thought model presented in the \\"Wireframe Your Generative AI Solution Design\\" blueprint. The model decomposes problems and requirements according to a human-tech ladder, which is helpful in the development of AI solutions.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLightning Talk\\n\\nLength\\n\\n5 minutes (can be expanded!)\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nThe Impact of GenAI Tools on Work OR\\n\\nUnpacking Generative AI: Beyond Traditional Tech\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nGeneral\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nGenerative AI behaves unlike any technology we've encountered before. In this interactive presentation, we delve into its inherently non-deterministic, often chaotic, and uniquely powerful nature. We'll uncover how its returns on investment manifest in hard, soft, contextual, and deeply personal ways, challenging traditional metrics. Understand how GenAI challenges the very nature of work by examining different types of cognitive impact through practical, real-world case studies and examples.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLive Demonstration\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nIntroduction to Generative AI\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nUsers without experience using GenAI.\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nGenerative AI is rapidly transforming how we work. This presentation provides a foundational understanding of GenAI, covering essential rules for responsible use and practical guidance on accessing and utilizing tools like Microsoft Copilot. We'll explore various examples of what can be achieved with GenAI. We'll also delve into critical considerations such as managing hallucinations, maintaining authentic voice and style, ensuring data privacy, and understanding the potential cognitive impacts of working with AI. This session is designed to equip participants with the knowledge to begin their GenAI journey confidently and ethically.\\n\\nType\\n\\nLive Demonstration\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\nPrompt Engineering 101\\n\\nAudience\\n\\nUsers with a basic understanding of prompts and GenAI.\\n\\nOverview\\n\\nUnlocking the full potential of Generative AI hinges on effective communication. This interactive session introduces the fundamental principles of prompt engineering, teaching you how to craft clear, concise, and impactful instructions for AI models. We'll explore various techniques, including the use of prompt templates, role-playing directives like \\"think as though you are a...\\" or \\"pretend you are a...\\", and the importance of comprehensive context setting. The highlight of this workshop will be a collaborative exercise where we build a practical prompt together for immediate use with tools like Copilot.\\n\\n\\n\\nType\\n\\nLive Demonstration + Workshop\\n\\nLength\\n\\n60 minutes\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nPresentation Title\\n\\n\\n\\nAudience\\n\\n\\n\\nOverview\\n\\n\\n\\nType\\n\\n\\n\\nLength\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nDomain: Development Domain Practices / Operations Domain Practices Title: Multi Agent Design and Opportunities in DevSecOps Duration: 30 - 45 minutes Presenter: Justin St-Maurice, Technical Counselor, Infrastructure & Operations Session Description: Today's DevSecOps pipelines are ruled by automation, yet they often feel like a fragile series of scripts demanding significant human oversight. We've shifted security left, but have we made it smarter? The next evolution isn't more tools; it's augmented team members. By understanding different perspectives on AI use in DevSecOps, explore different roles and architectures to improve and evolve DevSecOps workflows. \\n\\nAgenda Description From Automation to Autonomy: The Next Leap for DevSecOps \\n\\nDuring the presenting we will:\\n\\nExplore the limits of traditional CI/CD automation and why a new, systems-thinking mindset is required to overcome the complexity ceiling. \\n\\nComparison the use of cognitive augments via assistants, and workflow offload via agents. \\n\\nExplore multi-agent designs and conceptual architectures for multiagent workflows and assistant swarms to review Code, Security, and Deployment requirements."}	1768337874	/app/backend/data/uploads/6be7df1d-68d9-40f7-8da0-bab0e82be3a7_Presentation Catalogue vAugust-29-2025.docx	null
db17bfb2-d6a2-4f17-92b8-335422bbe683	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	01-Get-Ready-to-Deliver-AI-Services-Storyboard.pptx	{"name": "01-Get-Ready-to-Deliver-AI-Services-Storyboard.pptx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation", "size": 23272849, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768338025	092d092ae899bcb0ae6c80808d70dcefbe91d78dfe942e32c57ea33bce015e58	{"status": "completed", "content": "Get Ready to DeliverAI Services\\n\\nLeverage your existing capabilities to deliver competitive offerings in the new AI services industry.\\n\\n\\n\\nAnalyst Perspective\\n\\nCombining the projected size of the AI and technology services industries would displace today's telecommunication industry as the tenth largest in the world. I have no doubt that the AI services industry has become worthy of its own classification and deserves the attention of businesses everywhere. \\n\\nAs a new industry, AI Services represents a greenfield scenario where we are tasked with inventing something new, together. By establishing common terms to describe our collective capabilities and our inherent needs, we can streamline the new industry's exchange of services and drive toward an efficient steady state. There is a universal opportunity to leverage AI Services to drive advancement, using both provider and consumer lenses. \\n\\nAt Info-Tech, we pride ourselves on giving you practical insights and advice. In that great tradition, we have created a framework to organize the AI Services category into a cohesive industry that partners and collaborates to maximize the business value of AI innovation.\\n\\nFrom here, innate human ingenuity will identify novel use cases, brilliant solutions, and creative applications to leverage AI technology. In this era of democratized innovation, I am hopeful that strategic collaboration will enable us to tackle some of the biggest challenges of our day. \\n\\nDr. Justin St-Maurice\\n\\nPrincipal Research Director\\n\\nTechnology Services Provider Industry\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nExecutive Summary\\n\\nYour Challenge\\n\\nCommon Obstacles\\n\\nInfo-Tech's Approach\\n\\nYou regularly see new providers enter the market to position the latest AI products but have trouble differentiating offers and expertise and don't know how to articulate your own needs and capabilities.\\n\\nYou see signs that the market is shifting and know there is a new AI services industry taking shape, but you don't know where you fit in or how to participate. \\n\\nYou need to get ready for the AI services industry and need to take advantage of new opportunities to ensure you aren't left behind.\\n\\nYou have no reference framework to understand AI Services as an emerging industry, and selling services in this new market is chaotic.\\n\\nYou don't know how to round out your team's AI delivery capabilities and need a strategy to ensure you have wholistic AI abilities by working with specialized third-party partners while focusing on your strengths. \\n\\nYou don't understand the ecosystem and struggle to strategically find vendors and customers, which complicates monitoring competitors and developing partnerships. \\n\\nLeverage Info-Tech's AI Services framework to understand service domains and opportunities. Adopt a systematic approach to AI service delivery that aligns with the industry.\\n\\nDevelop a plan that takes client personas, business capabilities, and competency requirements into consideration to enter the industry with a gameplan that outperforms the competition.\\n\\nLeverage Info-Tech's library to create go-to-market strategies, refine your IT plan, price your services, and keep track of the AI Marketplace.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nYou need to provide value across seven service domains. Master your domain and expand your reach with value-added partnerships.\\n\\n\\n\\nThe Kodak story underscores the peril of relying too heavily on traditional business models in\\n\\nthe face of technological innovation. Kodak's failure toadapt to the digital photography revolution, despite inventing the first digital camera, led to their bankruptcy in 2012. They once controlled 80% of the market (The CDO Times, 2023; Startup Talky, 2021).\\n\\nYou need to get ready for the AI services industry\\n\\nChatGPT launched a wave of accessible AI innovation. Industries everywhere need to embrace a new reality and strategically leverage technological advances to stay competitive and remain relevant.\\n\\nKodak exemplifies the importance of foresight and the willingness to disrupt one's products to remain competitive.\\n\\nDon't have a Kodak moment!\\n\\nPLEASE DONOT\\n\\nPUT HEAD IN SAND\\n\\nChatGPT prompt: Draw me a picture of someone with their head in the sand. Make it in a comic style, funny, with a few AIs overlooking the person. Make it obvious the person has their head in the sand. \\n\\n\\n\\nThe market for AI Services is huge \\n\\n\\"The recent advancements in generative AI are creating incredible opportunities to rethink business processes at GM, our dealer networks and beyond.\\"\\n\\n[After a Chevy dealership chatbot recommended a Ford F-150]\\n\\nGM spokesman (Detroit Free Press, 2023)\\n\\nAIServices\\n\\nArtificial IntelligenceUS$529 Billion by 2028\\n\\n(Statista, \\"Artificial Intelligence \\u2013 Worldwide\\") \\n\\nTechnologyServices\\n\\nUS$1,771Billion by 2028 (Statista, \\"IT Services \\u2013 Worldwide\\") \\n\\nGen AI's projected boost to productivity gains in the United States(McKinsey & Company, 2023).\\n\\n+20%\\n\\n\\n\\nDemand for AI Services is growing quickly\\n\\nWHAT IS DRIVING DEMAND?\\n\\nChallenges are opportunities:\\n\\nNOT OUR SPOKESPERSON \\u2026\\n\\nPeople don't know what they're doing. Companies are moving ahead too quickly without testing. When the public notices that solutions have gone awry, public relations teams are activated (Vox, 2023).\\n\\nA customer was misled by Air Canada's chatbot about a bereavement fare, resulting in overcharges. The airline tried to claim that the chatbot was a separate entity when the customer complained. A tribunal ruled that Air Canada was responsible for the chatbot's erroneous information and needed to honor the fare.\\n\\nAir Canada invertedly introduced case law related to AI-use liability in business delivery(Washington Post, 2024).\\n\\nIt's an interdisciplinary industry, not a technical industry. Companies are realizing that the technology specialists who understand the bolts powering LLMs can't solve the bigger problems alone (University of Waterloo, 2023).\\n\\nThe risks are real and starting to manifest. Generative AI can't be left alone or exposed without additional measures. There are many examples of data leakage and unauthorized responses (diginomica, 2024).\\n\\nNobody wants to be left behind. Boards are putting pressure on organizations everywhere to keep up and take action. Generative AI are still dominating new business intake calls (Forbes, 2024). \\n\\n\\n\\nMarkets are already shifting in response\\n\\nHOW IS THE MARKET ADAPTING?\\n\\nChallenges are opportunities:\\n\\nTHE CHATBOT SAID WHAT?!?\\n\\nIncreased industry specialization and spinoffs: There is a rise of spinoffs in industries such as healthcare, where we are seeing more and more managed services organizations come to market (Medi-Tech Insights, 2024). \\n\\nDynamic Parcel Distribution faced a PR dilemma when its AI chatbot began writing sarcastic poetry and swearing at a dissatisfied customer. After attempts to obtain a customer service number, the customer was able to prompt the chatbot to create a poem criticizing itself and the company. \\n\\nThe situation escalated when the chatbot agreed to start swearing at the customer(New York Post, 2024). \\n\\nNew product categories: In 2022, LLMs were not commoditized products. Since then, many new business opportunities and categories have come to fruition, such as LLM Security products (Unusual Ventures, 2023).\\n\\nNew markets: There are 159,000 public GPTs in the OpenAI GPT Store (seo.ai, 2024). AIPRM Cockpit facilitates the exchange of models and GPT templates (AIPRM, 2024). Hugging Face provides access to thousands of models and tools.\\n\\nHistory of service specialization: There have always been areas of specializations in technology service delivery, with companies specializing in backend-IT, VOIP, and even robotic process automation.\\n\\n\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's approach to get ahead with AI Services\\n\\nProvider challenges:\\n\\nProviders don't have a framework to understand the AI services industry and are unclear about how to position services.\\n\\nProviders are unclear about their service capabilities and risk overpromising and underdelivering during project scoping. \\n\\nProviders don't know how to leverage the ecosystem and struggle to find customers, identify competitors, and develop partnerships. \\n\\nBuyer challenges:\\n\\nBuyers have trouble describing their service needs and don't know where to go to request quotes.\\n\\nBuyers don't know how to differentiate between offerings from multiple service providers and don't know how to assess capabilities.\\n\\nBuyers need to establish a network of trusted service providers to meet their short- and long-term AI service needs.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nInfo-Tech's methodology for capitalizing on the AI services industry\\n\\n1. Identify Client Value 2. Assess Your Capabilities 3. Explore Your Competency Needs Steps 1.1 Develop client profiles 2.1 Assess your strategy alignment capabilities 3.1 Prioritize your AI service competencies Deliverables AI Services Client Personas AI Service Capability Scoreboard AI Services Competency Plan\\n\\n\\n\\nUnderstand yourrole in theAI services industry to enhance your strategic planning\\n\\nBlueprint deliverables\\n\\nEach step of this blueprint is accompanied by supporting deliverables to help you develop your strategy:\\n\\nAI ServicesOpportunities Review\\n\\nAI Service Capability Assessment\\n\\nA breakdown of your ideal customer personas and strategic partners.\\n\\nA systematic analysis of your service capabilities according to seven different AI service domains.\\n\\nDefine a Digital Business Strategy\\n\\nAI ServicesCompetency Priorities\\n\\nBuild a Business-Aligned IT Strategy\\n\\nA list of your top ten competency needs for AI service delivery.\\n\\n\\n\\nInsightssummary\\n\\nOverarching insight You need to provide value across seven service domains. Master your domain and expand your reach with value-added partnerships.\\n\\nStep 3 insight Identify competitors and partners based on service domains. Focus on competencies and industry stakeholders to help you deliver competitive AI services.\\n\\nStep 1 insight Define your ideal customer and specific use cases to accelerate your time to market. Ground your new offerings on great customers with serviceable needs.\\n\\nStep 2 insight Explore different service domains to identify great value propositions that align with your current capabilities. Use self-assessments to determine your ability to delivery-specific services.\\n\\nTactical insight Don't try to eat the whole pie. Few providers can do everything, and even fewer can do everything well. Pick an area of specialization and carve out a niche or specialization for your service offerings.\\n\\nTactical insight Embrace the multidisciplinary nature of AI service delivery. Seek multiple perspectives and types of expertise. Don't assume that AI is a technical discipline.\\n\\n\\n\\nGuided Implementation\\n\\nA Guided Implementation (GI) is a series \\n\\nof calls with an Info-Tech analyst to help work through our methodology with your organization.\\n\\nA typical GI is 8 to 12 calls over the course of 2 to 3 months.\\n\\nWhat does a typical GI for service providers look like for this topic?\\n\\nCall #5: Which service model aligns wi