ementing, and controlling the full lifecycle management of digitally organized information and records. SFIA Competency Library\\n\\nNeed a deeper dive on AI competencies and skills?Download (Re)Calibrate Your IT Workforce for AI.\\n\\n\\n\\nDomain 5Cindy Pawford Pet Company (Part 5)\\n\\nCould you meet Cindy's service needs?\\n\\nClient Profile\\n\\nAI Service Needs\\n\\nCan you \\u2026\\n\\nThe Cindy Pawford Pet Company (CPPC) is an international veterinary clinic franchiser that offers veterinary services as a service (VaaS). Customers pay membership fees to access online veterinary consults and can be referred to a franchised clinic for follow-up without limit. Members get preferred rates from partners on food, toys, and spa services. CPPC also sells a mutual pet insurance product. \\n\\nCindy, the CTO, has learned that operationalizing a new preventative healthcare program is very sensitive to the quality and organization of the underlying data. She needs a strategy to systematically improve data quality and ensure it is reliable for the preventative healthcare use. \\n\\nCindy needs help organizing data into structures, while assuring its quality and fit for use. \\n\\nData Governance: Cindy needs to improve the maturity of her data. She wants to launch a data governance program to coordinate the use and quality of data, which she understands is a strategic asset. She needs the ability to transparently decompose insights into specific sources of truth. \\n\\nData Pipeline: Cindy needs to be able to reliably load data from multiple sources into a common data structure. She needs a pipeline with the capability to collect, ingest, store, and process data from streams and in batches. The process needs to be automated and flexible to accommodate information from other insurance and veterinary partners. \\n\\nCreate a data governance program to manage metadata and access controls? \\n\\nDevelop processes to assess and improve the quality of data?\\n\\nDesign and implement a data pipeline that can collect, inject, store, compute, and consume data from multiple sources? \\n\\nDeliver a data architecture that can efficiently provide easy access to data for analytics, reporting, and machine learning?\\n\\nStore data in optimal database engines to improve performance based on need?\\n\\nAnalyze existing data collection and processing procedures and identify sources of truth?\\n\\nDownload Create an Architecture for AI to build your target state architecture\\n\\n\\n\\nInput Output Client Profiles From Step 1 Service Capability Score Materials Participants Whiteboard/Flip Charts Chief Technology Officer\\n\\nActivity 2.5 Assess your data engineering service capabilities \\n\\n1-3 hours\\n\\nSelect Data Engineering as the AI service domain and enter your answers in the table.\\n\\n\\u200fTalent Assessment Questions: Rate your current teams' ability to successfully answer each question in an interview scenario, on a scale from 1 (unsatisfactory) to 5 (exemplary).\\n\\n\\u200fBusiness Model Assessment Questions: Rate the feasibility of the business model for your organization, from 1 (unfeasible) to 5 (very feasible).\\n\\n\\u200fKnowledge and Skill Assessment Questions: Rate your current capacity to leverage each knowledge category and skill set, from 1 (no capacity) to 5 (ready to productize).\\n\\n\\u200fOrganizational Self-Assessment Questions: Rate your organization's current maturity in executing the listed internal processes, from 1 (not performing) to 5 (mature, repeatable process).\\n\\n\\u200fCase Study Service Delivery Assessment Questions: Rate your organization's ability to deliver the listed service in the case study, from 1 (very difficult to deliver) to 5 (very simple to deliver).\\n\\n\\u200fReview the results summary in the scoreboard.\\n\\nIs your organization ready to deliver data engineering services? \\n\\nAre other service domains worth assessing to complement this domain's services?\\n\\n(Optional) Perform a SWO