c56951fe-fd18-4c72-9202-e05057d19038	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	microLLM Reference Architecture.docx	{"name": "microLLM Reference Architecture.docx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document", "size": 18188, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768337964	d42bb18cef4cb2a2329d15995db7060c10a1f9325850a7e552c97ffd12b2be3d	{"status": "completed", "content": "microLLM Design Pattern\\n\\n\\n\\nThe \\"microLLM Services Design Pattern\\" represents a forward-thinking approach to constructing modern AI solutions, particularly emphasizing the deployment and management of specialized Generative Pre-trained Transformer (GPT) models, termed microLLMs, within a scalable, flexible architecture. This design pattern integrates principles from microservices architecture, serverless computing, and event-driven communication to create a robust framework for AI applications.\\n\\nCore Components\\n\\nSpecialized AI Models (microLLMs)\\n\\nAt the heart of this design pattern are the microLLMs, which are GPT models optimized for specific tasks or domains. These models provide the specialized intelligence and functionality required by various components of the AI solution, from natural language processing to data analysis.\\n\\nMicroservices Architecture:\\n\\nThe architecture breaks down the AI solution into a collection of small, independently deployable services. Each microservice is focused on a specific function, such as data ingestion, model training, analytics, or user interface services, facilitating scalability and rapid development.\\n\\nData Management Layer\\n\\nUtilizes scalable and flexible data storage solutions like Amazon DynamoDB to manage the diverse datasets required by microLLMs. This layer ensures efficient data handling, supporting the dynamic needs of AI models for training and inference.\\n\\nAPI Gateway\\n\\nActs as the unified entry point for the system, directing incoming requests to the appropriate microservices or serverless functions. It simplifies access to the AI solution, providing essential functionalities such as authentication, rate limiting, and request routing.\\n\\nServerless Execution Environment\\n\\nEmploys platforms like AWS Lambda for executing code in response to events or triggers. This component allows for operational efficiency, enabling the system to automatically scale resources based on demand.\\n\\n \\n\\nOperational Dynamics\\n\\nEvent-Driven Communication\\n\\nThe pattern advocates for an event-driven approach to facilitate asynchronous communication between services, ensuring the system remains responsive and scalable. This setup allows microservices to react in real-time to changes or events within the ecosystem.\\n\\nContinuous Integration and Deployment (CI/CD):\\n\\nIntegrates CI/CD practices to automate the testing, building, and deployment processes of microservices and AI models. This promotes agility, allowing for frequent updates and maintaining high-quality standards.\\n\\nModel Registry and Cataloging\\n\\nIncorporates a centralized registry for documenting and managing microLLMs, including details about their capabilities, performance metrics, and application guidelines. This facilitates effective model management, selection, and deployment.\\n\\nDesign Principles\\n\\nSpecialization and Modularity\\n\\nCentral to the pattern is the development of specialized AI models (microLLMs) that can be easily integrated into modular microservices, enhancing the system's flexibility and capability to adapt to specific requirements.\\n\\nScalability \\n\\nDesigned to scale both the computational resources and the AI functionalities seamlessly, accommodating fluctuating demands and expanding data volumes.\\n\\nInteroperability\\n\\nEnsures seamless integration and interaction among microservices, microLLMs, and external systems through standardized interfaces and protocols.\\n\\nEfficiency\\n\\nLeverages serverless computing to minimize operational overhead and optimize cost-efficiency, focusing resources only when needed.\\n\\nAgility\\n\\nSupports rapid development, testing, and deployment cycles, facilitating innovation and the quick iteration of AI models and services.\\n\\nImplementing the Pattern\\n\\nImplementing the microLLM Services Design Pattern involves defining the specific domains or tasks where AI can add value, developing or selecting the appropriate microLLMs for those tasks, and architecting a system of microservices that leverages these models effectively. It requires careful planning of data management strategies, the establishment of a scalable infrastructure using serverless technologies, and the creation of an API Gateway to manage access and integration points.\\n\\nThis design pattern offers a comprehensive blueprint for developing sophisticated, scalable, and efficient AI solutions. It emphasizes the strategic use of specialized AI models within a flexible, service-oriented architecture, catering to the dynamic and diverse needs of modern applications and systems."}	1768337973	/app/backend/data/uploads/c56951fe-fd18-4c72-9202-e05057d19038_microLLM Reference Architecture.docx	null
cd27234b-4d4b-4653-87d6-981bf18e7703	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	background_Ergonomics Manuscript - Final - Sept 26.docx	{"name": "background_Ergonomics Manuscript - Final - Sept 26.docx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document", "size": 90135, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768337935	4e4bd03cde537872863480da351490326983bb274b14642a48fa2edeea210185	{"status": "completed", "content": "Title:\\n\\nComparing Multiple Cognitive Work Analysis Models to Characterize Complex System Differences and Similarities\\n\\n\\n\\nAuthors:\\n\\nJustin St-Maurice1 2 * and Catherine Burns1\\n\\n\\n\\n1System Design Engineering\\nUniversity of Waterloo\\n200 University Ave W, Waterloo, ON N2L 3G1\\n\\n\\n\\n2Applied Health Information Science\\nConestoga College Institute of Technology and Advanced Learning\\n299 Doon Valley Drive, Kitchener, ON N2G 4M4\\n\\n\\n\\n*Corresponding Author: justin.st-maurice@uwaterloo.ca  \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nWord count: 8,063\\n\\n\\n\\nSubmission as: Original Article\\n\\nAcknowledgements:\\n\\nThe authors would like to thank the local health care community for supporting this work through informal interviews, a practicum and user observations. This work was supported by the Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of Canada under Discovery Grant 132995.\\n\\nDisclosure statement: \\n\\nNo potential conflict of interest.\\n\\n\\n\\nOnline supplemental material:\\n\\n\\n\\nPosted at https://figshare.com/s/b1bb74ba19657c8df237 or http://bit.ly/2cFarGU  \\n\\n\\nAbstract\\n\\nThere are several reasons to compare socio-technical systems. Ongoing work with this paradigm includes transferring knowledge from aviation to healthcare. Conceptually, understanding system differences in complex environments could highlight the behaviours, processes, values and training that drive performance and ensure safety. Though various approaches exist, we show that an ecological framework, such as Cognitive Work Analysis, provides an ideal opportunity for rich comparisons. Our approach includes comparing models at each phase of the Cognitive Work Analysis framework and aims to extract useful insight by comparing models at each phase. As a demonstration of this approach, two similar healthcare systems that codify data are compared. Through a detailed description of our comparison in a healthcare setting, we demonstrate that unique and useful insights are possible. Though this approach is still preliminary, it has sufficient potential to merit further use and refinement in other applications. \\n\\nKeywords: health care ergonomics, ergonomics tools and methods, modelling and prototyping, system performance modelling, complex systems, cognitive work analysis, model comparison, data codification\\n\\nPractitioner Summary\\n\\nWe propose an approach that can be used to systematically compare complex systems. Our approach can extract important differences for analysis. We demonstrate this approach using an example from healthcare. This approach could be used in interesting ways, such as transferring knowledge from aviation to healthcare. \\n\\n\\nIntroduction and Motivation\\n\\nOccasionally in ergonomics there is a desire to transfer ideas from disparate domains. For example, despite very different ecologies there are regular attempts to take the lessons learned in aviation and leverage them to make healthcare safer. Recent examples of this paradigm include work by Kapur et al. (2016) and Clay-Williams and Colligan (2015).  As a concept, transferring knowledge between different complex domains is an interesting and challenging problem in the field of cognitive, organisational and environmental ergonomics. It has many potential uses. Likewise, there is value in exploring ways to compare similar domains in a systematic way.\\n\\nCognitive Work Analysis (CWA) is a conceptual framework that facilitates the analysis of the environment at various levels of detail. It is an approach used to dissect and analyse complex socio-technical systems. Using CWA for comparisons was first done after two groups independently analysed and assessed different (but very similar) command and control centres of naval combat vessels. More specifically, both groups used CWA's Work Domain Analyses (WDA) phase to better understand the purpose of each system (Burns, Bisantz, and Roth 2004). While this study drew interesting conclusions about modelling with CWA (specifically, that modellers sometimes vary in their modelling choices), it also indirectly asked another interesting question: should two North American command and control centres have similar work domains models? Is it reasonable to expect identical (or similar) abstractions? And most importantly, if two CWA analyses are different, what can we conclude about specific differences? Conceptually, two independent studies of two similar systems could generate useful information that could be combined and incorporated into a deeper understanding of both systems. In theory, incorporating data from similar environments, identifying commonalities and differences, learning lessons from related systems and adjusting an approach accordingly could be a very powerful approach towards solving the knowledge transfer challenge in ergonomics.\\n\\nIn the first part of this article, we review CWA, review several comparison techniques and describe our approach to comparing complex systems with CWA. The approach is generalizable and is compatible with existing theory. Our approach focuses primarily on developing and comparing Abstraction Hierarchies (AHs), Decision Ladders (DLs) and Information Flow Maps (IFMs), and creating comparison tables. \\n\\nIn the second part of this article we demonstrate an example of using CWA to compare two similar systems and show how our approach can offer unique insights into system differences and the systems themselves. In addition to demonstrating the use of CWA to compare systems, our analysis of data codification in two healthcare environments can be adopted by other practitioners who are working on data, data quality and health information problems. All models and summary tables for both systems are available as online resources to readers. \\n\\nBackground\\n\\nCWA is a conceptual framework that facilitates the analysis of the environment at various levels of detail and assesses how the environment impacts and shapes the human-information interaction. CWA is a systematic framework can be used to examine the work activities of participants in workflows and processes using environmental, organizational, and social lenses (Vicente 1999). CWA provides concepts and templates that facilitate the analysis of complex phenomena and supports better design in complex socio-technical systems (Fidel and Pejtersen 2004). \\n\\nCWA is a formative framework and describes how the system could behave, rather than how the system should or does perform (McIlroy and Stanton 2015). The approach is work-centred, rather than user-centred, and it analyses the constraints and goals that shape behaviour in work environments (Jiancaro, Jamieson, and Mihailidis 2013). CWA is broken down into five stages of analysis: Work Domain Analysis (WDA), Control Strategies Analysis (ConTA), strategies analysis (StrA), social organization and co-operation analysis (SOCA), and work competencies analysis (WCA) (Vicente 1999). \\n\\nThough the CWA framework includes five phases, not all stages are necessarily required in each analysis; the CWA method serves are a toolkit for practitioners and the analysis phases chosen should match the inherent system constraints (McIlroy and Stanton 2015).\\n\\n2.1 Work Domain Analysis\\n\\nAs the first phase of CWA, WDA describes the system's work domain in its entirety in order to display the functional means-ends relationships between system functions and components. Through an AH, the work domain is analysed and broken down into various levels of abstraction. The Abstraction Decomposition Space (ADS) can be used in conjunction with the AH to break down the analysis into different levels of resolution (Vicente 1999). Each type of model details investigations of the work domain and highlight underlying functional structures that must be respected in order for a system to achieve its intended focus; it is the documentation of the functional ecology (Kilgore, St-Cyr, and Jamieson 2009). WDA allows a practitioner to understand what needs to be done by the system, and helps under why the system exists.\\n\\n2.2 Control Task Analysis\\n\\nConTA is the second phase of the CWA framework and is a formative phase that describes how tasks can be undertaken. ConTA allows a practitioner to understand what must be executed and/or processed by the system and controller and describes these goals regardless of who is supposed to conduct the activity, or how. Because CWA is a formative framework, the ConTA highlights when activities can be carried out, and how they are likely to be carried out (McIlroy and Stanton 2015). \\n\\nConTA uses Rasmussen's DL trees (1974). DLs capture the flow of information processing associated with individual control tasks, and enable the use of shortcuts to describe expert and novice decision making patterns (Vicente 1999). DLs are represented by a series of data-processing (rectangles) and knowledge states (circles) that represent information processing patterns. Consecutive states of knowledge are separated by mental activities to transform one state of knowledge to the next. ConTA requires information about the state of the work domain, and outputs the required actions on the work domain (Vicente 1999).\\n\\nThe relationship between work domain and task analysis can be conceived as partnership. At one end, work domain analysis identifies information requirements that are event- and time-independent, providing a basis for supporting worker adaptation to novelty and change. On the other end, task analysis identifies information requirements that are event- and time-dependent, thus providing an efficient basis for supporting worker performance to anticipated situations. In other words, work domain analysis is ecological and helps understand which tasks may be performed by the user whereas task analysis describes those actions (Hajdukiewicz and Vicente 2004) \\n\\nConTA allows a practitioner to take an expert user into consideration, and allows a human actor to engage in a constructive learning process (Vicente 1999). ConTA anticipates user learning and adaptation as a constructive learning process. In this context, experts do not retrieve a pre-planned solution from memory when accomplishing a task, but actively generate contextually tailored sequences of cognitive activities that are appropriate in a particular situation (Vicente 1999). ConTA aims to models not only novice cognitive tasks, but also aims to map these expert sequences.\\n\\nTheoretically all users gain experience and eventually become experts. Instead of trying to determine what would be required for a novice to accomplish a task, we can instead try to determine the preconditions have to be satisfied for expert performance. A cornerstone of ConTA is to model processing behaviour towards designing computer-based information systems that deliberately induce and support expert action, which thereby lead to gains in cognitive efficiency (Vicente 1999). DLs are tools design to achieve the objective of discovering and documenting expert cognitive sequences. Through the use of shortcuts, a practitioner can articulate novice and expert paths, and serves as a tool to illuminate ways to induce expert action. \\n\\nExpertise in a DL can be expressed through the creation of 'shunting' effects that bypass higher, abstract levels of thinking. As described by Rasmussen (1974), a trained operator will only occasionally have to move through all the steps of the basic sequence. Shunting results from subconscious or intuitive data processing; \\"mental activity may take place at a symbolic level, resulting directly in a knowledge state later in the sequence\\", or \\"an association based upon previous experience may result in a leap directly from one state of knowledge to another one in the sequence.\\" These shunts evolve in the constructive learning process associated with training and are represented by arrows from data processing activities (e.g. boxes) to more abstract states of knowledge (e.g. circles). \\n\\nIn addition to shunts, DLs also allow for the description of 'leaps', which represent a direct transition from two separate knowledge states (e.g. going from a circle to a circle). Leaps represent intuitive data processing performed by the subconscious and describe associations that bypass more complex higher level reasoning. Leaps rely on the large capacity of holistic perception and recognition, as well as the large data processing capacity of the subconscious functions of generalization and modelling (Rasmussen 1974).\\n\\n2.3 Strategies Analysis\\n\\n\\n\\nThe third phase of CWA is StrA and builds on the control tasks from ConTA by describing the alternate ways each control task may be performed. StrA describes all variety of approaches and ways that tasks can be completed. This analysis is generally represented through the use of IFMs (Kilgore, St-Cyr, and Jamieson 2009). StrA allows a practitioner to understand how the system executes its functions.\\n\\n2.4 Social Organization and Co-operation Analyses\\n\\nThe fourth phase of CWA is SOCA and builds on the analysis performed in StrA by determining the actors performing tasks. The purpose of this analysis is to address and document organizational constraints imposed by jobs roles and definitions (Vicente 1999). This phase adapts the IFMs developed in StrA by colour coding to indicate either technical or human actors involved in the task completion. SOCA allows a practitioner to understand who completes the system functions (Jiancaro, Jamieson, and Mihailidis 2013).\\n\\n2.5 Work Competencies Analysis\\n\\nThe final stage of CWA, WCA, uses Rasmussen's (Rasmussen 1983) SRK taxonomy and describe the cognitive requirements needed to fulfil the system's functions (McIlroy and Stanton 2015). The analysis describes the system actor' and their required skill-based behaviour, rule-based behaviour, and knowledge-based behaviour. WCA allows a practitioner to understand the means and conditions ('by what means') are required to execute the system functions.\\n\\n2.6 Application of Cognitive Work Analysis\\n\\nCWA has proven to be a very versatile and broadly used framework. It has been used for a variety of purposes, including designing automation (e.g. Mazaeva and Bisantz 2007), modelling & designing systems (e.g. Hajdukiewicz 1998; Bisantz et al. 2003; St-Maurice and Burns 2015), assessing training requirements (e.g. Naikar, Sanderson, and Lintern 1999), analyzing information requirements (e.g. Ahlstrom 2005), supporting procurement (e.g Lintern and Naikar 2000; Naikar and Sanderson 2001), and designing effective training for teams (e.g. Naikar et al. 2003; Naikar and Saunders 2003; Naikar, Sanderson, and Lintern 1999). The domains of CWA have included air traffic control and aviation (e.g. Ahlstrom 2005; Naikar et al. 2003; Beevis, Vicente, and Dinadis 1998), power generation (e.g. Sanderson et al. 2005; Lehane, Toleman, and Benecke 2000), naval (e.g. Bisantz et al. 2003; Burns, Bisantz, and Roth 2004), manufacturing (e.g. Higgins 1998; Upton and Doherty 2008), military command and control (e.g. Jenkins et al. 2008; Lintern, Miller, and Baker 2002), petrochemical (e.g. Jamieson and Vicente 2001), transportation (e.g. (Salmon et al. 2007; Birrell et al. 2012; Jansson, Olsson, and Erlandsson 2006). CWA has also been broadly used in healthcare (e.g. Jiancaro, Jamieson, and Mihailidis 2013; Effken et al. 2008; Ashoori et al. 2014; Rezai and Burns 2014), including the analysis of cardiac care teletriage (Burns, Enomoto, and Momtahan 2009), trauma centre redesign (Sarcevic et al. 2010) and nurse decision support (Momtahan and Burns 2004). \\n\\nComparing Complex System Models\\n\\nThere are several reasons to compare similar systems:\\n\\nUnderstanding complex differences between two systems can be informative when there are clear performance differences and no obvious system differences. Identifying different behaviours, processes, values and training can expose important system characteristics that may contribute to good or poor performance;\\n\\nConceptually, comparing current systems states with future system states could be very helpful. These types of comparisons could support new implementations by identifying competency gaps, highlighting problematic values and constraints, and helping to develop training priorities;\\n\\nComparing two complex socio-technical systems in conflict is an interesting use case for system comparisons. A rich analysis and comparison of ecology, abstract values and goals could help parties negotiate and mediate by understanding common ground and areas of difference. This could be useful in various political situations;\\n\\nComparing two systems in parallel has the advantage of considering a bigger range of possibilities and observing a bigger pool of users that are doing similar work. Understanding two system domains would give a practitioner access to more ecological concepts and expose them to a bigger pool of possibilities for creating universal solutions.\\n\\nIn this section, we describe existing system comparison approaches, describe the advantages of comparing CWA models, and describe a specific approach to performing comparisons with CWA. \\n\\n3.1 Comparison Approaches\\n\\nAs a concept, the comparison of systems is not new. A list of different comparison approaches is shown in Table I. Though there are many task analysis techniques available to model and understand the user interface and the user experience  (see Limbourg and Vanderdonckt 2004), only a few tools, such as the Concurrent Task Trees (CTT) (see Patern\\u00f2, Mori, and Galiberti 2001) have been created to support task modelling with comparison features. These tools are useful for teams designing user interfaces and support the need to consolidate branches of knowledge acquisition. This concept is similar to using the Unified Modelling Language (UML), and requiring version control strategies and difference algorithms (see Kelter, Wehren, and Niere 2005). Tackling UML version control can be thought of as a series of model differences and model unions (Alanen and Porres 2003).\\n\\nComparing cognitive tasks in complex systems is different than comparing tasks in user interface design. In cognitive engineering and human factors, a popular technique is Hierarchal Task Analysis (HTA) (see Shepherd, 1998) and deals with the decomposition and analysis of tasks. More specifically, HTA is a goal oriented framework and allows for the modelling of the cognitive and physical processes associated with achieving a system goal by breaking down the processes into sub-goals. As a descriptive framework, HTA is well suited for describing and analysing existing systems or concepts. HTA, though complementary to CWA, is less suited for generating new designs for identified problems (Salmon et al. 2010). Thus, HTA is a cognitive engineering tool that is well suited for analysing cognitive tasks in a descriptive way, but does not enable a rich ecological comparison. In contrast, CWA is effective a supporting the creation of first of kind systems and in this sense is a complimentary approach to HTA.\\n\\nAnother approach that can be used to compare system models is Cognitive Task Analysis (CTA), which can be used to compare performance differences between types of users (see Crandall, Klein, and Hoffman 2006). A good example of comparing complex systems with CTA was done by Mioch, Mistrzyk, & Rister (2010), where two communication methods were studied and compared. In their study, voice control versus datalink communications were analysed separately between a cockpit and ground control. This analysis was done by a semi-formal task analysis and allowed the authors to understand the differences between both approaches. The authors were able to characterize and compare each approaches to communication and make recommendations to improve airline safety. The contrast between these two systems was task-focused, and did not address ecology.\\n\\nAs an approach to comparisons, comparing CWA models is novel. As a formative framework, CWA describes how the system could behave, rather than how the system should or does perform. While the framework covers tasks, CWA also puts those tasks into the context of broader ecology; CWA has the advantage of being able to capture useful information that might normally fall outside 'pure' cognition or software interface. CWA is able to capture differences in functional goals, abstract trade-offs, the types of users, professional values, training requirements and team composition. Without studying the broader ecology, these elements and differentiators could be missed. \\n\\nComparing two systems with CWA is also an interesting approach because it explores how a single system could behave by exploring how systems do behave, and allows our models to be more formative. There is a synergy in exploring two similar system that enriches the set of CWA models. The comparison is 'extra-formative' as it allows the broader consideration of more possibilities and explores more ways in which any one system could behave.\\n\\nOutside the ecological benefits, using CWA to compare specific cognitive processing activities is useful because common tasks in both systems are not necessarily the same. By developing and comparing with ConTA, we can create a common template spanning two systems and explore variations in the processing paths in two similar ecologies. This approach is well within the spirit of Rasmussen's seminal work (1974) which allows for dichotomous representations in DLs. This dichotomy of information, with different processing paths, is already present when comparing novice and expert user performance. The use of shunts and leaps is already common practice to represent differences and this technique could be used to represent differences between systems, instead of differences between types of users. ConTA allows for a rich comparison of control tasks in an ecological context. \\n\\nOur approach to comparing CWA models has been developed over time and was first described in St-Maurice & Burns (2015). Now further refined and including additional stages, our approach to comparing CWA models is based first on defining and establishing the similarities between two systems and then by systematically comparing the results of each phase of CWA.\\n\\n\\n\\n3.2.1 Establishing System Similarity\\n\\nIn order to compare complex socio-technical systems, there must be a logical context to perform a comparison. Obviously it would be illogical to attempt to compare a combat naval vessel's socio-technical ecology to a solar power plant's mechanical operations ecology. However, other examples are less obvious: in what circumstances would it be appropriate to compare medical settings? Could a hospital ER be compared to a walk-in clinic? Could a Canadian clinic be compared to an American clinic? Could a veterinary walk-in clinic be compared to a human walk-in clinic? Can we transfer knowledge from aviation to healthcare?\\n\\nIn our approach we define similarity as two systems with common goals. Some of these shared system goals should be reflected in each system's Functional Purpose (in the WDA phase). To date, we have compared models that have a complete set of identical Functional Purposes, but there is no reason for the functional purposes to be exactly identical in all comparisons. Using common goals ensures logically integrity to the analysis, but also enables common Information-To relationships to Control Tasks and enables the comparison of subsequent phases of CWA. Only by ensuring both systems share some common goals or reasons for existing can control tasks be compared, as they must Act-On the similar work domain (Vicente 1999).\\n\\nOur current definition of similarity is not so strict as to negate or remove sufficient differentiations between WDA models, as priorities and values can still be meaningfully represented for both systems through the remainder of the abstraction hierarchy. \\n\\n3.2 Work Domain Analyses Comparisons\\n\\nAfter ensuring we have two systems which are similar and have 'common goals', the WDA modelling can take place. When creating each AH, the models should reflect their common goals in the Functional Purposes abstraction level. Models should be built using normal strategies, such as interviewing subject matter experts (SMEs), reading texts and observing different types of users. \\n\\nOnce both AHs are complete, there will likely be differences. If systems share an exactly common AH, differences could be explored using the later phases of our approach. Assuming differences do exist, comparing AH models can be done visually with a Venn diagram (see Burns, Bisantz, and Roth 2004). This comparison, broken down by abstraction layers, is a summary sheet which allows the practitioner to highlight similarities and differences between the work domains (St-Maurice & Burns, 2015). This Venn diagram should be accompanied by a comparison table that discusses and comments on each noted difference. \\n\\nThere are several uses for the results of this comparison. First, the comparison allows a practitioner to characterize system differences in a qualitative manner, and provides a practitioner the opportunity to explain any differences in system performance or efficiency through differences in the system ecologies. Differences could be explained by variations in generalized functions or abstract functions and could identify specific constraints that impact either system. The results of the comparison can be very informative to support the design of teams, operations, training and technologies. Conceptually, this comparison allows for the identification of successful elements within systems. It can offer insight regarding how those successful elements have come to be, and how they could be incorporated into other systems.\\n\\n3.3 Control Task Analyses Comparisons\\n\\nThe next phase of our approach involves comparing ConTA DLs. As a first step, sets of DLs are built using normal methods, such as interviewing SMEs and observing users while performing specific tasks. In a full CWA, every possible task might be analysed. In this case, since there is an interest in performing a comparison, similar tasks should be identified and modelled as a priority. Other tasks could be contrasted as well, based on insight gathered during previous and subsequent comparisons.  \\n\\nConceptually, the idea of comparing similar tasks is to enable the possibility over overlaying both systems onto a common DL. This concept is shown in Figure 1. As our analytical interest is to compare and contrast two systems, a common DL provides a visual opportunity to identify areas of interest. These areas include all points where processing paths diverge in the common DL. We've labelled these sites junctions. Figure 2 shows that a junction exists at the Alert knowledge state, following the Activation information processing activity on the DL. Junctions could appears at any information processing or knowledge state in the DL.\\n\\nThere are several uses identification of junctions. Each junction represents an opportunity for deeper analysis, comparison and potential design changes. Junctions invite a practitioner to investigate and ask deeper questions about the relationships between the ConTA and WDA phases of analysis. Is the reason for a junction in the DL reflected in the AH? In some situations, one system's path in the common DL may be preferable to the other as it indicates a more efficient processing path.\\n\\nGenerally, junctions highlight areas where changes may positively impact a system. The common DL can generate change ideas and concepts could be 'stolen' between the systems under comparison. Junctions highlight an opportunity to explore how one system could behave more like another. \\n\\n3.4 Strategies Analyses Comparisons\\n\\nThe next phase of our approach involves comparing StrA IFMs. Each set of IFMs demonstrates how tasks are performed in each system. Similar to the comparison of DLs during ConTA, this phase of the approach is only viable for tasks that take place in both systems and comparisons should take place after StrA IFMs have been developed for each system on those common tasks. \\n\\tIf IFMs are built independently, it is unlikely that strategy names, their descriptions will match identically and form a perfect comparison. In order for this comparison to be useful, strategy characteristics and their triggers need to be abstracted to comparable terminology. For example, if two strategies involve taking paper notes during a process, this characteristic (e.g. 'paper notes') would be used to compare strategies. The comparison would show which strategies from the domain that uses the specific strategy characteristic. If these strategy of using 'papers notes' was triggered by experience, this would also be noted in a table. The approach leaves practitioners with a summary of strategy characteristics and triggers that apply to either system and allows for a rich contrast for each task. If appropriate, the intersections and commonalities in strategy characteristics could be shown in a Venn diagram.\\n\\nThere are several uses for the results of at StrA comparison. Primarily, the comparison allows a practitioners to understand what strategies exist cross system, what type of strategy characteristics (e.g. attributes) are used throughout the task-type and to assess if new strategies could be introduced between systems to complete common tasks in new ways. The comparison of systems enables a richer StraA analysis within each system and creates questions about strategy triggers and surrounding ecologies: what structures, values or goals are influencing the adoption and triggers strategies between systems? What knowledge could be transferred?\\n\\n3.5 Social Organization and Co-operation Analyses Comparisons\\n\\nThe next phase of our approach involves comparing SOCA IFMs and role descriptions. Developed for each system, this set of IFMs demonstrate who was involved in the performance of each task. These sets of IFMs are again built using normal methods for each system before making comparisons. The comparison is only viable for tasks that take place in both systems.\\n\\nThe actual comparison mechanism between SOCO is a series of Venn diagrams for each comparable strategy showing all possible actors, and which actors are involved in which system. This is supplemented by a table for each strategy analysed, summarizing and highlighting which actors exist in each, or both systems, and how they contribute to various strategies. Another approach is to summarize which users are performing are adopting strategies during StrA, and incorporate that knowledge into the table developed in the previous comparison. A limitation of this comparison is that is can only be performed meaningfully when there are similar strategies, used by different actors. Thus, this comparison will not be practical in all situations and is a tool to be used as necessary. \\n\\nThe results of this comparison can be used to compare team approaches and contrast roles and responsibilities between types of users. Conceptually, team approaches from one system could be used to improve and study team structures from the other system domain. Importantly, the comparison allows for the critical assessment of ideal team structure to support common tasks. \\n\\n3.6 Work Competency Analyses Comparisons\\n\\n\\tWhen comparing WCA, the first step is to create detailed SRK taxonomies for each control task. For each task under study, the task's skill-based, rule-based and knowledge-based behaviours are identified and described. Once complete, the comparison of each SRK taxonomy is shown for information processing step. In a table format, behaviours are aligned to which elements of the SRK taxonomies are unique and overlap. Since it is unlikely that text descriptions in the SRK match exactly verbatim between two independently generated models all behaviours need to be summarized and abstracted before attempting to draw comparisons. \\n\\nThe results of this comparison could help explain performance variances between systems that relate specifically to competency. By understanding which competencies overlap (and which do not) it would be possible to evaluate training programs, assess transferable skills and review worker skill levels. Conceptually, this could highlight specific mentorship and cross-training opportunities between systems.\\n\\nCase Study: Comparing Two Similar Health Care Environments\\n\\nIn this section we use an example to demonstrate how our approach is used to compare two CWA analyses. For each step of our approach we discuss the resulting insights from our comparison, and use the information to characterize complex system differences and similarities. \\n\\n4.1 Analysis Context\\n\\nAs part of a study about information management and data quality in healthcare, a primary healthcare organization called a Family Health Team (FHT) was compared to a local hospital in Ontario. Both organizations were identified as having complex socio-technical systems to codify their data. The rational for making this comparison was to better understand factors that contribute to data quality and the successful codification of data. As a premise, hospitals are thought to create higher quality data for analysis, whereas FHTs are thought to produce poorer quality data.\\n\\nTo rationalize a comparison, we confirmed that both systems aim to treat patients effectively, aspire to create useful data for analysis and have reporting requirements to government agencies. We also confirmed there were interesting differences: the hospital uses a different type of medical record system compared FHT (hybrid vs fully electronic); the organizations provide different levels of care (primary care vs secondary care) and are therefore governed differently; and data is coded by different types of employees (e.g. in the hospital Health Information Management Professionals [HIMPs] are responsible for coding data, versus clinicians are responsible at the FHT. Though these differences were obvious, it was not clear how they necessarily contributed to data quality and data codification.\\n\\nThe purpose of the analysis and comparison of the systems was to identify specific ways that the FHT's domain could produce better data. The goal was to compare the FHT to the hospital domain and identify specific attributes that could be transferred from one ecology to the other. Our goal was not to do a full CWA analysis of both systems, but rather to focus on tasks and processes that contributed to the codification and quality of data.\\n\\n4.2 Use of Approach\\n\\nWe followed our approach to compare the two system domains. We focused on demonstrating our approach with all phases of CWA. After performing two WDAs, we identified a similar task which we analysed in detail for ConTA, StrA and WCA. We noted that this task did not involve varying team structures and therefore did not find it necessary to do a detailed SOCO analysis. However, we did notice that different types of users performed similar tasks during our comparison of strategies, and addressed the SOCO phase indirectly during our comparison of StrA. \\n\\nAll AHs, DLs, IFMs and tables created to analyse both domains are available for review as online resources. The results of our comparison approach is discussed below.\\n\\n4.2.1 Similarity\\n\\nWe characterized our systems as similar because they both provided patient care, and aimed to manufacture data regarding the health and the treatment of patients. This similarity was reflected through a common set of functional purposes in the work domain analysis. \\n\\n4.2.2 Work Domain Analyses and Comparisons\\n\\nMethod. Since both system domains were involved in treating patients, a common 'Treating Patients with Medical Records' AH was developed as a subcomponent of both system domains (see AH 1.A and AH 1.B). This AH was abstracted in such a way that it could apply to any healthcare situation. It was created through the analysis of textbooks, health care delivery manuals and interviews with clinicians and physicians within the community over the course of several months. The AH modelled patients flows (e.g. registration, assessment, treatment) and information flows (e.g. creating records, updating records, reviewing records).\\n\\nThe common AH for treating patients was used as component of two separate AHs that modelled the codification of data. One AH was created for the FHT (see AH 2.1) and another AH was created for the hospital (see AH 2.2). These AHs were created in tandem through interviews with directors and program managers over the course of several months. As visible in Figure 3, during the course of creation of each AH, we flagged differences between the AHs using a '*' to identify a system difference, and an 'x' to denote that an element did not appear in the other AH. We took care to ensure the order and positioning of boxes between AHs was consistent to support a simple visual comparison. Following the creation of two AHs, we used our approach to compare both system domains with a Venn diagram (Figure 4) and comparison table (Table II). \\n\\nDiscussion. The FHT and the hospital had notable differences in their Generalized Functions, Abstract Function linkages, and Physical Functions. The Abstract Functions and Functional Purposes overlapped directly as many concepts could be realistically linked and modelled in both domains. While meeting with users, drafting the AH and adding concepts, it generally made sense to add concepts to both AHs. In this way building both WDA's in parallel was helpful and created a better AH for each domain.\\n\\nDifferences in the Generalized Functions represented different organizational structures: in the case of the hospital, doctors were instructed to correct or add material to records during quality assurance. Since the hospital's owned the medical records, the concept of ownership played a role in the codification requirements and practices. In the case of the FHT, doctors were given suggestions about correction or additions, and asked to consider changes. However, in the FHT records were owned by each doctor and they were in control of all changes. In both systems records and codification occurred, but the political ecology and processes of each domain were different. Surprisingly, it appears that coding processes are actually more complex in the FHT compared to processes in the hospital. \\n\\nAnother interesting difference between the two systems is that FHT clinicians were asked to summarize encounters, add codes to their medical records and provide data to a registry, whereas in acute care there is a team of HIMPs that are dedicated to this task. To compensate, FHT clinicians aren't expected to provide rich data using ICD-9 or ICD-10 codes, whereas this is required in hospitals. In the FHT, clinicians are sometimes supported by a data specialist, who provides direction in the coding process. \\n\\nIn our FHT AH, the act of coding data and inputting codes into medical records is not linked to the 'Professional Values and Training' abstract function. This was an intentional model feature. In the future, it might be possible to engage FHT clinicians into the codification process by helping them understand the value of coding and ensuring they are able to incorporate these values into their professional practice. Several community driven data initiatives discussed during interviews aim to pursue this goal. In hospitals, since clinicians are not asked to code, incorporating abstraction into professional practice does not appear to be a useful goal. \\n\\n4.2.3 Control Task Analyses and Comparisons\\n\\nMethod. In order to compare control tasks between both system domains, a set of tasks needed to be identified. By referring to the AHs and the Generalized Function layer, the 'Summarize Encounter' function was selected for further analysis as it was present in both system domains and preliminary discussions led us to believe these tasks were very similar. \\n\\nAt the FHT, the specific task under study was 'Record Encounter' (See DL 2.1). To complete this task users had to review their own records and notes (or work from memory) and summarize their encounters into a specialized registry that collects data for government reporting purposes. These clinicians were not physicians but all kept medical records within a physician's office, were part of a physician's team and interacted directly with patients on a daily basis. The finish the task, users signed into a website, entered data into required fields, and submitted their data.\\n\\nIn the hospital environment, the specific task under study was 'Abstract Encounter' (see DL 2.2). To complete this task HIMPs had to review patient records and abstract (e.g. summarize) the information. To complete the task, HIMPs opened a software application, entered data into required fields and submitted data. \\n\\nFor each task, users were interviewed and observed to generate accurate DLs. For the FHT task, it was possible to characterize cognitive task flows for three groups: novice users, intermediate users and expert users. For the hospital task, there were novices and experts, but no obvious intermediate group. \\n\\nDiscussion. In our approach, we anticipated overlaying the two system DLs into a single model for comparison. In this case, this was not practical because the tasks were not sufficiently similar in nature and the overlaying the DLs did not make logical sense for a comparison. When we analysed the control task in higher detail, the procedures and tasks were similar from a skill perspective (discussed in our WCA comparison later), but the information processing mechanisms were unique at the higher Interpret and Evaluate information processing levels. In the case of the FHT task, users processed time management and work priorities at the higher levels of the control task, since these users needed to balance clinical assessments with coding responsibilities. In the case of the hospital task, users processed information about special coding cases and special requirements a higher levels. This was based on specific diagnoses and users had to identify ways to complete the task as completely as possible given a large set of coding requirements.\\n\\nInstead of overlaying different system domains onto a common DL, we overlaid different groups of users onto a common DL With the 'Record Encounter' task we were able to identify two interesting junction sites that depicted possible opportunities for system changes. Our analysis of these two junction sites in the FHT environment are shown in Figure 5 and Figure 6. In the 'Abstract Encounter' task, there was no obvious junction between groups of users. In this case, both novices and experts cycled through the DL but for different reasons and at different information processing stages; it was not valuable to overlay this information. \\n\\nIn the first junction (Figure 5), it was apparent that intermediate users were more engaged in their data codification processes and spent more time evaluating the value of their work and deciding how to manage their time and trade-offs. In contrast, novice users did not consider the value of their task and blindly completed the work, while expert users understood their work value heuristic, no longer engaged in an evaluation and had predetermined priorities regarding their data. By putting all this paths onto a single DL for comparison, it appears that intermediate users may engage in the deepest thinking about their data quality. The DLs clarified that novice users should be interrupted when they have reached the Goal State knowledge-state, and Expert users could benefit from support to encourage deeper thinking before they begin to engage in the Formulate Procedure information processing activity. \\n\\nThe second junction (Figure 6) existed because novice users do not enter their data in bulk and therefore do not to go through an Observation knowledge-state to understand what work must be done. In contrast, expert users tended to bulk enter data and required the additional process of reviewing a sheet or report to understand what work needed to be completed to complete their work. Based on this knowledge, it would be advantageous to encourage expert users to work like novice users (e.g. enter data on the same day), as this would reduce the cognitive load and complexity of the task. \\n\\n4.2.4 Strategies and Social Organization Analyses and Comparisons\\n\\nMethod. We continued our analysis of the 'Record Encounter' and 'Abstract Encounter' tasks. After we created IFMs for each task (see IFM 2.1 and IFM 2.2), we abstracted the strategy characteristics into categories to enable comparisons. We noted that different users were performing the tasks in each environment and adopted the social organization comparison paradigm by noting which users were performing tasks and adopting strategies in each domain.  Table III provides an overview of our results by linking strategy characteristics to triggers (e.g. why this strategy was used), strategy adopters (e.g. users using the strategy) and the specific strategies from the StrA that link to the characteristic. \\n\\nDiscussion. Our analysis showed several strategy characteristics that were unique and common. Primary are strategies were schedule oriented as a result of codification being a secondary task to patient care and are artefacts of time management requirements and workload decision making. Hospital strategies aimed to improve task efficiency and enhance accurately. Hospital artefacts were driven by optimization needs and a desire to avoid quality assurance loopbacks. \\n\\nBulk data entry was a strategy characteristic from both environments. In the hospital, bulk entry of data into the abstracting system is policy driven and a function of workflow. Data entry is delayed by approximately 6 weeks and there is a consistent lag between real-time events and reporting capabilities. At the FHT, bulk entry by clinicians is a strategy to cope with workload but is against policy and is also the least efficient approach because of additional cognitive requirements (e.g. checking which patients have already been inputted and referring back to documentation instead of reporting from memory). The most desirable strategy in each domain was different, though interviews with FHT managers indicated that only half of the encounters entered into the system respected same-day entry policy.\\n\\nAt the FHT, clinicians performed data entry. This is arguable more efficient: clinicians can use their memory and cognition to record information, whereas HIMPs need to review notes and familiarize themselves with each individual episode of care. The benefit, however, of the HIMP is a built-in quality assurance process that occurs through the secondary interpretation of events. By assigning the task to a non-clinician who does not know the patient, there is a verification of information and the removal of bias. The execution of the task by different parties is a key difference in this context and results in data quality differences.\\n\\n\\tIn the hospital abstracting task, experts use paper to take notes and before using a computerized interface to input data. Advanced abstracters suggested that anyone with experience would use this approach. This suggests that there is room to provide the computerized interface to support the task and avoid the need to work with paper to take notes during the task.\\n\\n4.2.5 Work Competencies Analyses and Comparisons\\n\\nMethod. We continued our analysis of the 'Record Encounter' and 'Abstract Encounter' tasks and developed an SRK taxonomy for each information processing and knowledge state from ConTA (See SRK 2.1 and SRK 2.2). After each WCA was completed, we created a chart summarizing our findings for each level of the taxonomy at each information processing step. As shown in Table IV, we abstracted a summary for each behaviour based on the WCA and identified which specific behaviours were unique to a SRK and which behaviour were common. \\n\\nDiscussion. When we chose the 'Record Encounter' and 'Abstract Encounter' tasks for comparison, the tasks appeared similar: users were signing into computerized systems, entering data into fields and submitting the data into a database. The reason these tasks appeared similar for analysis is reflected in common skill-based behaviours at the lower cognitive levels in the taxonomy. \\n\\n\\tThe reasons that these tasks were quite different, however, was reflected in the rule-based behaviours and knowledge-based behaviours. Rules based behaviour were also similar at lower ends of the cognitive tasks (e.g. following organizational policies and mandates) and following mandatory field rules in the user interface. At higher levels, cognitive tasks required different rules based behaviours (e.g. interpreting policies vs reading coding project definitions). Knowledge based behaviour were completely different between the two SRKs, which clarified that clinicians and HIMPs do not have the same training and work competencies to perform their respective tasks. Despite similar ecologies, the tasks require different types of training and cognitive supports.\\n\\n4.3 Summary of Findings\\n\\nOur reason for conducting a CWA on both healthcare environments and performing a comparison was to transfer knowledge form the hospital's effective (presumed) codification system and transfer knowledge into the FHT processes. The analyses of both system domains in parallel enabled a richer understanding of each environment that may not have been achieved independently. It became apparent through our comparison that there is a two-way street for knowledge transfer and there are opportunities to improve performance in both domains. \\n\\nDuring our comparison of two similar tasks, we reinforced the old adage from systems design that underneath a user interface and similar 'strokes and clicks', there is a rich ecology that influences and distinguishes the actions of users: look beyond the user interface! In this case seemingly similar tasks took place is different contexts, with different priorities and required different competencies.\\n\\n4.3.1 Knowledge Transfer to Primary Care.\\n\\nAfter comparing WDAs, the issue of record ownership appear to play an important role in the work domain. In the hospital, records were owned by the institution. This had impacts on the Generalized Functions and enables the hospital to request specific changes and engage in quality assurance for documentation. The FHT could simplify some of its processes by changing its governance structure and owning the medical records.\\n\\nAfter analysing paths in ConTA, the FHT could find ways to encourage intermediate user behaviour. Interventions could be incorporated at special information processing stages to increase engagement with data\\n\\nBased on the comparison of StrA, it is clear that having a HIMP in the FHT environment to perform coding tasks could increase quality assurance of clinical documentation and avoid attempts to cognitively balance workloads and priorities. Based on our analyses, making this adjustment would require significant changes throughout the ecology to be successful. \\n\\n4.3.2 Knowledge Transfer to Hospitals.\\n\\nBased on the comparison of WDAs and StrA, there may be an opportunity to ask clinicians in the hospital to codify some data. This could be done with the assistance of a Data Specialist, who could introduce a priority code list. The advantage of this approach would be that the hospital could record preliminary data closer to the real-time event, rather than waiting 6 weeks. A two-tiered approach would provide the benefits of the FHT processes (e.g. data that is closer to real-time) and the benefits of the hospital (e.g. quality assurance and accuracy through task optimization). \\n\\nConclusions\\n\\nWe have described an approach to compare complex socio-technical systems through the use of CWA. While there are several reasons to conduct a comparison, we have demonstrated that understanding complex differences between two systems can be informative for identifying potential performance differences and transferring knowledge. In a case study, our approach was successful in identifying different team structures, training needs and cognitive trades-offs that could be exchanged between both systems to improve performance. Our approach was able to articulate specific differences between the ecologies.\\n\\n\\tOur approach is novel and it requires further refinement, debate and case studies applications. Future work will include using this approach to compare other types of system and developing a stronger relationship between our comparison paradigm to the design of systems and user interfaces. Since this approach takes the broader system ecologies into consideration during through a systematic analysis, it would be an excellent approach to use to attempt to transfer knowledge between increasingly disparate ecologies.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nReferences\\n\\nAhlstrom, Ulf. 2005. \\"Work Domain Analysis for Air Traffic Controller Weather Displays.\\" Journal of Safety Research 36 (2). Elsevier: 159\\u201369.\\n\\nAlanen, Marcus, and Ivan Porres. 2003. \\"Difference and Union of Models.\\" UML 2003 - The Unified Modeling Language. Modeling Languages and Applications 2863 (527): 2\\u201317. doi:10.1007/978-3-540-45221-8_2.\\n\\nAshoori, Maryam, Catherine M Burns, Barbara d'Entremont, and Kathryn Momtahan. 2014. \\"Using Team Cognitive Work Analysis to Reveal Healthcare Team Interactions in a Birthing Unit.\\" Ergonomics 57 (7). Taylor & Francis: 973\\u201386.\\n\\nBeevis, D, K J Vicente, and N Dinadis. 1998. \\"An Exploratory Application of Ecological Interface Design to Aircraft Systems.\\" In Proceedings of the NATO RTO Symposium on Collaborative Crew Performance in Complex Operational Systems. DTIC Document.\\n\\nBirrell, Stewart A, Mark S Young, Daniel P Jenkins, and Neville A Stanton. 2012. \\"Cognitive Work Analysis for Safe and Efficient Driving.\\" Theoretical Issues in Ergonomics Science 13 (4). Taylor & Francis: 430\\u201349.\\n\\nBisantz, Ann M, Emilie Roth, Bart Brickman, Laura Lin Gosbee, Larry Hettinger, and James McKinney. 2003. \\"Integrating Cognitive Analyses in a Large-Scale System Design Process.\\" International Journal of Human-Computer Studies 58 (2). Elsevier: 177\\u2013206.\\n\\nBurns, Catherine M., Ann M. Bisantz, and Emilie M. Roth. 2004. \\"Lessons From a Comparison of Work Domain Models: Representational Choices and Their Implications.\\" Human Factors: The Journal of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society 46 (4): 711\\u201327. doi:10.1518/hfes.46.4.711.56810.\\n\\nBurns, Catherine M, Yukari Enomoto, and Kathryn Momtahan. 2009. \\"A Cognitive Work Analysis of Cardiac Care Nurses in Teletriage.\\" In Applications of Cognitive Work Analysis, 149\\u201374. Boca Raton: CRC Press.\\n\\nClay-Williams, Robyn, and Lacey Colligan. 2015. \\"Back to