a5803090-e721-40b6-844d-6d59276812ad	e92fa032-845e-4ce9-ad71-3810ca14f7a9	it-Wireframe-Your-Generative-AI-Solution-Design-Storyboard.pptx	{"name": "it-Wireframe-Your-Generative-AI-Solution-Design-Storyboard.pptx", "content_type": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation", "size": 24000775, "data": {"knowledge_id": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}, "collection_name": "adbeade6-cb53-42c9-88cc-adf0f39ec6df"}	1768338233	7762d309fb9ba73f96d122afab7ecc11bd4a81dc2ba6e722bd61671edaa395bb	{"status": "completed", "content": "WireframeYour Generative AI Solution Design\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's design methodology to align technical solutions with organizational needs. \\n\\n\\n\\nAnalyst perspective\\n\\nGenerative AI technologies are opening the door to new types of solutions and user experiences. While exploring different ideas and concepts, it is useful to wireframe concepts to aid discussion with both technical and business stakeholders. For service providers, communicating ideas and documenting opportunities with customers should span social, human, and technical considerations. Ensure these areas are captured in early discussions to accelerate ideation and drive profitable projects forward. \\n\\nInfo-Tech's methodology to wireframe generative AI solution designs will help you systematically consider organizational, team, user, model, data, software, and hardware elements in potential solutions. The methodology is a means to engage, align, and communicate with decision-makers, ensuring everyone is on the same page prior to making an investment.\\n\\nInfo-Tech's solution library exemplifies its methodology through a deep dive into different solution designs. The solution library is intended to showcase some novel opportunities for solutions that leverage the unique capabilities of generative AI. You can use the library as a starting point to leverage the methodology or to kick off ideation with customers. \\n\\nInfo-Tech's approach to wireframing a solution design is not one-size-fits-all. Rather, it is another tool for your toolbox that can help you generate value as a trusted technology service provider.\\n\\nDr. Justin St-Maurice\\n\\nPrincipal Research Director\\n\\nTechnology Services\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n\\nYour Challenge\\n\\nCommon Obstacles\\n\\nInfo-Tech's Approach\\n\\nYou recognize the ability of generative AI to revolutionize user experiences but struggle to design innovative solutions that leverage the technology. \\n\\nYou don't have a formalized solution design methodology to integrate generative AI effectively into your solutions or a systematic process to analyze requirements.\\n\\nYou don't know how to balance technical innovation with organizational needs, and mismatches have hindered deployments or resulted in failed projects. \\n\\nYou don't align solutions with specific end-user requirements or organizational contexts, creating a gap between technology delivery and user expectations. \\n\\nYou don't design with technical specifications and human requirements equally in mind and don't know how to navigate complex sociotechnical design.\\n\\nYou don't focus on the human-technology intersection of solution design and struggle to simultaneously communicate requirements to business stakeholders and technology specialists.\\n\\nAlign human needs and technology outcomes with the support of a human-tech ladder and systematically analyze requirements and constraints at multiple levels of need.\\n\\nIdentify challenges and unknowns during solution development and frame them as learning outcomes that scaffold concepts to be understood, applied, and leveraged for creative innovation. \\n\\nLeverage Info-Tech's solution library to understand the design methodology while exploring new concepts and ideas for generative AI technology. \\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nDesign solutions with a sociotechnical lens. Consider not only the technology but also the social systems within which the solution will be embedded to maximize its adoption, usefulness, and strategic alignment.\\n\\n\\n\\nLarge language models (LLMs) are closed systems of interconnected parameters. The most recent ancestor of LLM technology is simple autocorrect technology on cellphones. In the last decade, the technology has gone from taking small text inputs to predict the mostappropriate word to come next in a sentence to accepting millions of words (prompts) to predict the content of entire essays. The exact mechanisms that allow an LLM to accept a prompt, understand it, and generate a unique response are not understood (Futurism, 2024).\\n\\nSolutions leveraging generative AI can deliver experiences that were previously impossible\\n\\nUnleash novel ideas with the unprecedented interactive capabilities of generative AI (Gen AI).\\n\\nPreviously impossible? \\n\\nOld technology, more parameters\\n\\nContext-aware content generation: Gen AI produces rich, context-aware content adapted to cultural nuances, social contexts, and user needs. \\n\\nBrainstorming and decision-making support: Gen AI can analyze and synthesize huge amounts of data to provide insights and assessments that support brainstorming activities and decision-making.\\n\\nPersonalization at scale: Gen AI can personalize user experiences in real time by catering to individual preferences, needs, and behaviors. \\n\\nChatGPT prompt [June 2024]: Draw me a picture of an LLM. Emphasize the chaotic nature of the LLM, its social interface and its advanced technology underpinnings.\\n\\n\\n\\nGen AI increases solution complexity, increasing the need to systematically document requirements.\\n\\nGEN AI SOLUTIONS ARE COMPLEX SOCIOTECHNICAL SYSTEMS.\\n\\nGen AI solutions are built on LLMs that combine algorithms, data, and infrastructure to dynamically interact with users. These models are powered by chaotic cultural norms and aggregated human knowledge. \\n\\nLLMs bridge the boundary between AI and human behavior in unprecedented ways. With a virtually infinite number of input parameters, LLMs influence and are influenced by each interaction they have. The subjectivity of interactions introduces unique design constraints.\\n\\nTechnology service providers (TSPs) need to document and manage multiple interconnected requirements to successfully drive new experiences with Gen AI. The need to document requirements and align stakeholders grows exponentially alongside the complexity of the technology. \\n\\nPoorly documented requirements are the number one cause of IT project failure.\\n\\n(Statista, 2015)\\n\\n\\n\\nIt's a new type of human/computer interaction\\n\\nWHY IS INTERACTING WITH GEN AI SOLUTIONS CHALLENGING?\\n\\nThey produce complex sociotechnical impacts. Generally, information systems interact with people and impact multiple domains through complex interdependencies. Healthcare systems, for example, simultaneously impact data, patient care, physician collaboration, and regulatory requirements. Gen AI components further complicate these interactions.\\n\\nThey are dynamic, evolving pieces of technology. The underlying LLM models evolve with new data sets and will change with societal shifts in values, culture, and knowledge. At their core, they are not rule-based solutions and are difficult to manage with traditional technology controls.\\n\\nThey are nondeterministic systems. Gen AI is not designed to simply handle predetermined inputs. Its strength is its ability to accept input from any user and flexibly cater to different requests. Gen AI can infinitely customize experiences, and the integrity of such solutions requires new types of boundaries. \\n\\nThey need to incorporate responsible principles. While processing inputs, Gen AI solutions need to navigate ethical dilemmas and governance constraints. Data privacy, algorithmic bias, and the responsible use of AI are central to viable designs, where accountability becomes both a technical and a social challenge.\\n\\nReview Get Started With AI in Requirements Management to learn more about the evolving human/computer interface.\\n\\n\\n\\nMisaligning the human/computer experience is a recipe for failure\\n\\nMisalignments between humans and technology occur in both buy and build scenarios. A sociotechnical systems lens is helpful in both approaches to designing integrated solutions. Selecting the right solution ensures that its implementation supports and advances the strategic objectives of the organization, regardless of whether the solution is engineered in-house or purchased off the shelf.\\n\\nMisalignments between technological capabilities and social elements lead to failure, despite the intrinsic quality of the technology or the strategic soundness of the goals.\\n\\nBUY OR BUILD?\\n\\nAccurate models that act contrary to responsible principles will not be trusted. \\n\\nPoor data will degrade the user experience.\\n\\nSimple interfaces incorporated into complex workflows will hinder team productivity.\\n\\nSlow hardware that takes too much time to deliver a response will lower the value to the user.\\n\\n\\n\\nEmbrace a sociotechnical systems approach to drive solution alignment\\n\\nSocial requirements are an important part of solution design. Sociotechnical systems (STS) theory is based on the idea that communities function through technology use, and that people work through software using hardware. \\n\\nSTSs are an intersection of multiple sciences:\\n\\nSociologists see\\u00a0social\\u00a0systems\\n\\nPsychologists\\u00a0see cognitive\\u00a0systems\\n\\nComputer scientists\\u00a0see information\\u00a0systems \\n\\nEngineers\\u00a0see hardware\\u00a0systems\\n\\nAn STS approach sees multiple system types as interconnected and recognizes the union of people and technology as a natural evolution of both social and technical systems (Interaction Design Foundation, 2024).\\n\\nUse an STS approach to:\\n\\nExplore the interrelationships between people, technology, and the organizational environment of solutions.\\n\\nSystematically align humans and technology to manage the interaction between them. \\n\\nIncorporate a balance between technically-advanced solutions and social responsibility by giving equal weight to human and technology elements.\\n\\nInitial ChatGPT prompt [June 2024]: Draw me a picture of a socio-technical system.\\n\\n\\n\\nA design pattern is a description or template for how to solve a software engineering problem in many different situations. A design pattern is generally narrowly focused and offers a detailed, reusable solution (Source Making, 2021).\\n\\nA design methodology offers a structured framework that addresses broader system challenges and is adaptable to the unique requirements and complexities of many situations. A design methodology facilitates a systematic exploration of needs, design, and implementation through a holistic approach (IBM, 2023).\\n\\nUsing systems design methodologies to manage complex sociotechnical systems is a well-known and well-published domain of engineering science.\\n\\nAlign human and technical elements using systems design principles and tools \\n\\nUse Info-Tech's methodology to align the human and technical elements of your innovative Gen AI solutions.\\n\\nIdentify the human or organizational need.\\n\\nDecompose solutions requirements with human and technical lenses.\\n\\nDescribe the human-technology interaction.\\n\\nWhat is a design methodology?\\n\\n\\n\\nInfo-Tech's sociotechnical wireframe methodology for AI solutions\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nDesign solutions with a sociotechnical lens.\\n\\nConsider not only the technology but also the social systems within which the solution will be embedded to manage requirements and constraints.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nCreate innovative\\n\\nGen AI solutions\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nDesign Wireframe Methodology\\n\\nConsider social and technical needs.\\n\\n\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo develop a core understanding of the solution value from a human perspective and ensure the solution is rooted in addressing real, specific human or organizational needs.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA problem statement that clearly and concisely describes the issue being addressed by the solution.\\n\\nProblem statements should be supported by concrete data. \\n\\nProblem statements should not prematurely suggest solutions.\\n\\nPotential activities\\n\\nInterview users and key stakeholders.\\n\\nDistribute surveys to get insights on organizational needs and pain points.\\n\\nAnalyze current systems and workflows to identify gaps and areas for improvement.\\n\\nReview social, technological, economic, and environmental factors that influence the need for the solution.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nDevelop a problem statement\\n\\nFocus on understanding the problem fully before jumping into solutioning. In sociotechnical design, technology solutions need to address a specific human, social, or organizational need. \\n\\nWhy create a problem statement?\\n\\nIt establishes a human-centric focus, emphasizing the user needs and contexts before defining technology requirements, and ensures solutions are tailored to actual human use cases.\\n\\nIt mitigates technology-centric thinking and reduces the risk of developing solutions that are technically sound but fail to address real-world problems. Avoid technology for the sake of technology.\\n\\nIt enhances solution adoption and increases the likelihood of user acceptance and satisfaction by aligning solution functionalities with specific user needs and expectations.\\n\\n\\n\\nSpecific: Clearly define the problem with specific data and insights and avoid vague descriptions. Use quantifiable metrics to highlight the severity and impact of the problem.Relevant: Ensure the problem is directly related to stakeholder needs and aligns with organizational goals. Make it clear why this problem needs urgent attention.User-centric: Consider the human or societal impact of the problem by showing how the issue affects individuals or communities. Define the human need.Scoped: Scope the problem without making it too broad or too narrow, which would lead to more focused and effective solution development.\\n\\nClearly describe the problem\\n\\nA problem statement should clearly and concisely describe the issue being addressed, outline the impact of the problem, and hint at possible outcomes without suggesting specific solutions prematurely. \\n\\nGood problem statements\\n\\nBad problem statements\\n\\n\\n\\nSupport your statement with data\\n\\nA problem statement should include references to data and be grounded in facts. \\n\\nExamples from different industries:\\n\\nHealthcare: \\"Hospital readmission rates for heart failure patients have increased by 20% over the last year, leading to higher healthcare costs and reduced patient satisfaction. A solution is needed to identify contributing factors and reduce these rates.\\"\\n\\nEducation: \\"Local high school students are showing a 30% lower proficiency in math compared to national averages, affecting their readiness for college-level courses and future employment opportunities.\\"\\n\\nTechnology: \\"Our company's software deployment process takes, on average, 30% longer than the industry benchmark, leading to delays in updates, decreased productivity, and client dissatisfaction.\\"\\n\\nRetail: \\"Customer foot traffic in our main store has declined by 15% quarter-over-quarter, significantly impacting sales and threatening long-term business sustainability.\\"\\n\\n\\n\\nSpecific, relevant, user-centric, and scoped\\n\\nExample of a well-written problem statement for an LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library:\\n\\n\\"Public libraries play a pivotal role in engaging communities with great and diverse literature, but with over 130 million books worldwide, finding a good book can be daunting. Advanced readers in particular face challenges in discovering new titles that resonate with their varied interests, especially readers from different cultural backgrounds. There is a need for an effective system within public libraries that can navigate the literary landscape without influence from marketplaces that can intelligently match readers with books that not only pique their interest but also expand their cultural understanding.\\"\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution \\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo structure and define the solution in a way that aligns technological capabilities with human needs and organizational objectives, ensuring that the solution is both technologically feasible and human-centered.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA solution with detailed requirements and constraints. Based on systematic analysis and according to the human-tech ladder lens, the solution:\\n\\nProvides an opportunity for input from a wide range of stakeholders.\\n\\nDefines a successful solution.\\n\\nActivities\\n\\nHold brainstorming sessions (e.g. whiteboarding sessions, tabletop exercises) with business and technical leaders.\\n\\nUse multiple iterations of activities to finalize the solution details based on input.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage a human-tech ladder to define requirements\\n\\nWhat is a human-tech ladder?\\n\\nVicente (2003) presented a human-tech ladder to describe technology uses at different levels of abstraction, including physical, psychological, team, organizational, and social levels. This methodology has been used in areas such as aviation, nuclear power generation, and healthcare to make technology safe for human interaction and useful for end users.\\n\\nInfo-Tech's adaptation of the human-tech ladder decomposes AI solutions into their social and technological components to emphasize and manage the complexity of integrating AI systems within social and technical contexts. The modified ladder introduces layers specifically dedicated to AI, data, software, and hardware to help development a wholistic understanding of solution requirements involving AI.\\n\\nThe human-tech ladder can help you systematically consider both the social (human) and technical challenges at each stage of solution design and technology implementation to ensure a more holistic and integrated approach to developing complex sociotechnical systems.\\n\\n\\n\\nLeverage the human-tech ladder to deliver great solutions\\n\\nWhy use the human-tech ladder?\\n\\nSystematically assess potential challenges and specific requirements from multiple perspectives. Each level is a different type of challenge to manage and requires different competencies. Remember that managing people, policies, and organizational behavior is a different discipline than optimizing bits, bytes, and performance.\\n\\nSimultaneously integrate solutions into multiple complex systems. Acknowledge and consider multiple impacts of the solution's introduction and ensure that systems are aligned to drive an effective implementation.\\n\\nInvolve and engage multiple stakeholders and decision-makers in the design process and ensure that the needs and expectations of various stakeholders are met. Improve satisfaction among users, teams, and organizational leaders by designing solutions with their specific requirements in mind.\\n\\n\\n\\nSystematically consider human and technical challenges\\n\\nHumanfactors\\n\\nOrganization: How will the solution align with organizational strategies and goals?\\n\\nTeam: How will the solution impact team collaboration, dynamics, and roles?\\n\\nUser: How will users interact with the solution?\\n\\nHardware\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nModel\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nData\\n\\nUser\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nModel: How will the underlying models and algorithms process and interpret data?\\n\\nData: How will underlying data support the solution accurately and consistently? \\n\\nSoftware: How will the solution integrate with other systems and components?\\n\\nHardware: How will the solution interact with the real world? \\n\\nTechnologyconstraints\\n\\n\\n\\nBrainstorm ideas and concepts to address your problem statement \\n\\nDon't try to put a square peg into a round hole, and don't incorporate Gen AI into every solution.\\n\\nInfo-Tech's methodology, for illustrative purposes, implicitly assumes that Gen AI is the preferred solution to a problem, enabling a review of the incorporation of Gen AI into solution wireframes followed by a series of examples around an LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library.\\n\\nIS GEN AI THE RIGHT SOLUTION TO YOUR PROBLEM?\\n\\nGenerate novel concepts and business models\\n\\nBalance the value against costs and estimate an ROI\\n\\nAdopt Design Thinking in Your Organization\\n\\nhelps bridge design thinking with innovation.\\n\\nLaunch Your AIProof of Value\\n\\nexplores the balance between technical feasibility and business value.\\n\\n\\n\\nDefine your solution requirements\\n\\nOrganizational criteria\\n\\nTeam criteria\\n\\nModel criteria\\n\\nData criteria\\n\\nHardware criteria\\n\\nUser criteria\\n\\nSoftware criteria\\n\\nOrganizational constraints\\n\\nTeam constraints\\n\\nUser constraints\\n\\nModel constraints\\n\\nData constraints\\n\\nSoftware constraints\\n\\nHardware constraints\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nDecompose solutions using the human-tech ladder\\n\\nDefine solution requirements\\n\\nUser\\n\\nBrainstorm\\n\\nideas andconcepts\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nDecomposed requirements\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Respect intellectual property laws and ethically source book content and metadata. Augment the library team's capability to deliver high-quality customer service, both online and offline. Allow users of any age to comfortably and securely talk about their book preferences. Be able to ask users interactive questions in a friendly way to understand their preferences on genres and favorite books. Use validated, opensource book content or a metadata database. Provide a seamless experience and integrate with the existing book reservation system. Run with minimal costs in the cloud and scale without excessive cost increases.\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo describe the solution in enough detail to demonstrate the human-technical interactions to business and technical stakeholders and gain buy-in for the human and technical elements of the solution.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nA solution diagram depicting the human-technology interaction with details of the core human actions, technology functions, components, and experiences.\\n\\nNovel aspects of the solution do not need to be fully defined if the intended behavior is clearly understood. \\n\\nThe solution diagram should tell the story in one page.\\n\\nActivities \\n\\nMap out activities and functions with various stakeholders.\\n\\nDescribe specific workflow and/or priority use cases.\\n\\nBreak down the solution into technical components.\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nDevelop the human-technology story\\n\\nDocument the human-technology experience.\\n\\nBreak down the technical components.\\n\\nTell the human-technology story. \\n\\nMap out human activities and technology functions.\\n\\nList human activities involved in using the system.\\n\\nMap human activities to specific technology functions to describe how technology supports or enhances human activities. \\n\\nUse a flowchart or use cases (or other techniques) to describe the intended interactions between users and technology.\\n\\nInclude decision points, loops, and conditional paths that reflect human-technology interactions.\\n\\nBreak down technology into abstract technical components (e.g. servers, databases, LLMs, user interfaces).\\n\\nDescribe the relationship between the technical components.\\n\\nConsolidate your diagrams and draw connections between human activities, technology functions, and technology components.\\n\\nUse the final diagram as a visual narrative to explain how users interact with the system.\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nDon't shy away from novel solutions and focus on the end-product experience. If it's unclear how a technology function will deliver a specific experience or whether a technology even exists to meet the need, include it in the solution diagram anyway.\\n\\n\\n\\nOutline core activities and functions\\n\\nHuman activities\\n\\nTechnology functions\\n\\nMap out human activities and technology functions.\\n\\nAsk for book recommendations through an interactive natural language prompt.\\n\\nReview suggestions and select books to read.\\n\\nPick up books from library.\\n\\nProcess natural language requests and provide recommendations.\\n\\nAnalyze user selections and update user preference model. \\n\\nTrigger process to prepare books for pickup.\\n\\nList human activities involved in using the system.\\n\\nMap human activities to specific technology functions to describe how technology supports or enhances human activities. \\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\n\\n\\nDocument the expected experience\\n\\nDocument the human-technology experience.\\n\\nUse a flowchart or use cases (or other techniques) to describe the intended interactions between users and technology.\\n\\nInclude decision points, loops, and conditional paths that reflect human-technology interactions.\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\n\\n\\nDescribe the technology components\\n\\nBook reservation system\\n\\nLibrary database\\n\\ne.g. book location and availability data\\n\\nBreak down the technical components.\\n\\nTrigger\\n\\nQuery\\n\\nBreak down technology into abstract technical components (e.g. servers, databases, LLMs, user interfaces).\\n\\nDescribe the relationship between the technical components.\\n\\nInternet\\n\\nAPIs\\n\\nRAG\\n\\nWeb browser\\n\\nWeb server\\n\\nLLM\\n\\nBook metadata\\n\\ne.g. any HTML5-compliant web browser\\n\\ne.g. SaaS or on-prem web service\\n\\ne.g. ChatGPT-4 , Claude, Gemini\\n\\ne.g. opensource book metadata database\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\n\\n\\nAlign stakeholders with a one-page story\\n\\nUser engages LLM using natural language to talk about books and receives recommendations. User can request book reservationsduring the exchange.\\n\\nBook reservation system\\n\\nSingle-page web application\\n\\nTell the human-technology story. \\n\\nChat interface\\n\\nConsolidate your diagrams and draw connections between human activities, technology functions, and technology components.\\n\\nUse the final diagram as a visual narrative to explain how users interact with the system.\\n\\nThe book reservation system manages policies and procedures to make the book available physically or digitally.\\n\\nLLM\\n\\nThe LLM interfaces with databases to make recommendations based on availability and personal preference. \\n\\nLibrary andbookdatabase\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\n\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives\\n\\nPurpose\\n\\nTo articulate specific problems as learning objectives and proactively approach continuous improvement and innovation as a form of learning.\\n\\nOutputs \\n\\nInterconnected learning objectives reflecting specific concepts that need to be understood and applied before creating an innovative solution. \\n\\nNot all learning outcomes need to be achieved at the same level. Some things only need to be understood, whereas others require a deeper level of expertise and knowledge.\\n\\nFocus on what you need to know and learn to achieve the outcome of the solution.\\n\\nActivities\\n\\nDecompose concepts and learning pathways.\\n\\nReview potential courses and opportunities to learn.\\n\\nResearch and discover materials and learning content.\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to describe the solution requirements and constraints. \\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nDefine the needed learning objectives\\n\\nBuild your innovation capacity by breaking challenges down into manageable learning goals.\\n\\nIdentify areas for growth and prepare your team to tackle novel and complex problems.\\n\\nIdentify the ultimate goals or challenges of your solution, especially items that require novel approaches or innovative thinking. These are \\"Create\\" level outcomes and involve synthesizing new products, ideas, processes, or functionalities from existing knowledge and technologies.\\n\\n1\\n\\nDecompose each \\"Create\\" objective into smaller \\"Apply\\" objectives that focus on the application of knowledge to analyze, evaluate, and solve parts of the broader problem. Apply objectives should represent processes, analyses, or evaluations that are necessary to support the creation of the solution.\\n\\n2\\n\\nIdentify foundational \\"Understand\\" objectives that involve gaining knowledge and comprehension. These are the basic concepts, theories, and skills that team members must master to perform the \\"Apply\\" tasks effectively. Ensure these objectives cover all necessary theoretical and practical knowledge that feeds into higher-level tasks.\\n\\n3\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's learning framework on the next page to break down learning objectives.Find a larger list of learning verbs in the Bloom's Taxonomy Verb Chart.\\n\\n\\n\\nPrioritize learning objectives\\n\\nInfo-Tech Insight\\n\\nDesign integrated systems\\n\\nFocus on the learning process, not the learning content.\\n\\nInnovation is the end-product of a systematic learning journey that builds on intentional levels of cognitive development.\\n\\nApplytechnology concepts\\n\\nInnovative\\n\\nsolutions\\n\\nUnderstandsolution components\\n\\nDefine\\n\\nList\\n\\nRecall\\n\\nRecognize\\n\\nStudy\\n\\nDescribe\\n\\nSummarize\\n\\nReview\\n\\nDiscuss\\n\\nParaphrase\\n\\nImplement\\n\\nExecute\\n\\nUtilize\\n\\nOperate\\n\\nPerform\\n\\nDifferentiate\\n\\nExamine\\n\\nOrganize\\n\\nCompile\\n\\nAnalyze\\n\\nCritique\\n\\nJudge\\n\\nCompare\\n\\nContrast\\n\\nValidate\\n\\nDesign\\n\\nDevelop\\n\\nInvent\\n\\nConstruct\\n\\nArchitect\\n\\nProduce new and original solutionsand applications\\n\\nAssess decisionsand improve designs\\n\\nRecall basic facts and concepts\\n\\nUse concepts in traditional scenarios\\n\\nCombine ideas to tackle complex problems\\n\\nExplain ideas and concepts\\n\\n\\n\\nFrame unknowns as learning objectives \\n\\nApply LLM models to deliver user interactions\\n\\nApply SQL query fundamentals\\n\\nUtilize RAG for dynamic retrieval of book metadata\\n\\nUnderstand copyright and legal requirements for book data\\n\\nGenerate SQL queries against library database\\n\\nIdentify key elements of interactive user interfaces\\n\\nDesign an end-to-end, interactive book recommendation system\\n\\nUnderstand the functionality of recommendation systems\\n\\nTrigger book reservation system from an LLM plugin\\n\\nList the steps of book reservation processes\\n\\n Implement data privacy measures in user interactions\\n\\nCreate advanced data analysis tools to continuously improve recommendations \\n\\n Understand privacy and data protection principles\\n\\nUtilize behavioral data to enhance book recommendations\\n\\nComprehend user preferences and behavioral data concepts\\n\\nIllustrative example: LLM-based book recommendation solution at a public library\\n\\n\\n\\nDecompose learning outcomes further as elements of the human-tech ladder\\n\\nProgressive learning outcomes\\n\\nInnovative\\n\\nsolutions\\n\\nUnderstand Apply Create User Explain common interaction patterns between users and AI systems. Assess designs that minimize user errors and misunderstandings when interacting with AI. Develop UI solutions that clarify AI decisions and outputs for better user comprehension. Model Identify and describe the key algorithms that form the base of the AI model. Analyze methods to streamline model training and improve learning efficiency. Develop strategies and architectures that enable the model to scale effectively with increasing data loads. Data Discuss the importance of data normalization and its impact on model performance. Analyze techniques to maintain data integrity throughout the AI system's lifecycle. Generate methods to ensure data diversity and representation in AI training sets. Software Apply principles of modularity to improve maintainability and scalability of AI software. Evaluate various metrics and tools used for assessing AI software performance. Innovate with DevOps practices to streamline AI software development and operations.\\n\\nExample of evolving learning outcomes by levels of the human-tech ladder.\\n\\n\\n\\nTake advantage of learning opportunities with Info-Tech's AI Workforce Development Program\\n\\n\\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's systems design methodology to:\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution.\\n\\nDesign successful Gen AI solutions that integrate Gen AI into the social systems within which it will be used.\\n\\nSystematically engage key stakeholders around core aspects of the solution's implementation.\\n\\nDocument solutions across sociotechnical domains to align business interests with technology implementation.\\n\\nFrame unknowns and challenges as learning objectives.\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to describe the solution. \\n\\nCreate innovative Gen AI solutions\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's solution library to:\\n\\nDeepen your understanding of Info-Tech's design methodology by referencing concrete examples.\\n\\nExplore new concepts for the use of Gen AI in your business solutions and grow your understanding of potential use cases.\\n\\nLaunch conversations with customers to explore innovation opportunities.\\n\\nArchitect the solution at the human-tech intersection.\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library\\n\\nDeepen your understanding of the methodology\\n\\nand explore new solution design concepts.\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1001\\n\\nContext\\n\\nSolution concept summary\\n\\nExpense report assistant\\n\\nSolution features\\n\\nA CIO at an MSP is transitioning to a CTO role and wants to grow internal development capabilities for Gen AI solutions. The CIO has identified an expense report assistant as a viable project that could be commercialized. The CIO wants to test development, QA, and DevOps processes.\\n\\nThe expense report assistant will capture financial data from individual users, generate summary reports for review via email, and submit claims by integrating with existing expense systems. The solution will learn and adapt to different user types and user preferences without the need for direct customization and will learn to query users for clarification on expenses only when necessary. The solution will reduce the overhead associated with filing expense reports and improve their accuracy. \\n\\nLLM capability requirements\\n\\nChatGPT prompt [July 2024]: Draw the target user experience: [\\u2026]\\n\\nMust accurately handle financial calculations\\n\\nMust be able to put expenses into context of trips, travel dates, and geography and understand exchange rates\\n\\nMust be able to integrate with financial and email systems to augment and automate workflows\\n\\nMust adapt to individual user reporting preferences\\n\\nIntegrates with existing financial solutions to streamline the reporting process by minimizing the need to enter structured data on forms\\n\\nAdapts to different expense contexts and user preferences to enhance accuracy and streamline the user experience\\n\\nEmulates the interactivity of an executive assistant by communicating via email to clarify how expenses should be filed and ensure data accuracy and completeness\\n\\nAdjusts to negative and positive reinforcement provided by users and system administrators\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1001\\n\\nExpense report assistant\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nInefficient and time-consuming manual reporting interrupts productivity, is prone to errors, and increases administrative overhead for managers with large teams. On average, employees spend approximately 30 minutes completing a single expense report. Often, managers and the finance department spend approximately 30 minutes per report detecting errors, communicating corrections, and reprocessing submissions. With hundreds of expense reports submitted monthly, there is a need to accurately capture financial data with minimal intervention and reduce the total report processing time to no more than ten minutes per report.\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   39\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1001\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution. \\n\\nExpense report assistant\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Adhere to financial regulations and internal security policies to protect sensitive financial data. Enhance the capabilities of the CTO's team through a collaborative, hands-on development experience. Provide an intuitive and accessible interface for users of varying technical skills to submit and review expense reports. Consistently produce accurate financial reports and adapt to various expense contexts. Integrate with existing financial databases and ERP systems to pull and push data seamlessly. Integrate seamlessly with existing financial and ERP systems to streamline operations. Run efficiently in the cloud, providing scalability and minimizing costs.\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1001\\n\\nArchitect the solution and align needs with technology \\n\\nAnalyst note: Context window management in asynchronous use cases needs to be incorporated into the design.\\n\\nExpense report assistant\\n\\nContext window manager(Context per user)\\n\\nFinancial management system/ accounting system\\n\\nEmailservice\\n\\nLLM\\n\\nThe user interacts with the assistant via email and receives reminders to capture media (e.g. receipts). An app synchronizes captured media.\\n\\nAPIorRPA\\n\\nThe best available technology is used to submit expenses into the corporate finance system, which could be a combination of API calls and robotic process automation (RPA) tasks.\\n\\nFile synchronizationservice\\n\\nDocument database\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1002\\n\\nContext\\n\\nUse case summary\\n\\nEmergency response advisor\\n\\nSolution features\\n\\nAn advisory firm supports a large state agency. In emergencies, the agency has a mandate to coordinate resources, plan service interruptions and communicate with stakeholders. A consultant at the firm suggested the agency automate information analysis with an emergency response advisor.\\n\\nThe emergency response advisor (ERA) will be activated when the risk of a natural disaster is high. The ERA will integrate with a variety of data sources to interpret and synthesize complex data from news media, social media, video peripherals, sensors, and onsite staff. The ERA will provide real-time situational awareness by monitoring inputs and interpreting the information with reasoning skills. The ERA will make explainable recommendations to the agency to assign resources and communicate action.\\n\\nLLM capability requirements\\n\\nChatGPT prompt [July 2024]: Draw this target user experience in a funny way: [\\u2026.]\\n\\nAdapts to various types of incoming data, whether structured, semistructured, or unstructured, providing accurate situational forecasts\\n\\nOffers real-time situational awareness by processing data from news reports and social media and live updates from field responders, ensuring immediate, informed decision-making\\n\\nPredicts the impact of disasters and recommends the best course of action for resource allocation and disaster response\\n\\nProvides detailed explanations of recommendations to validate logic and reasoning\\n\\nMust interpret and contextualize diverse data inputs\\n\\nMust make logical inferences on real-time data to predict potential developments and outcomes\\n\\nMust be able to explain inferences and be reliable in emergencies where accuracy and speed are critical\\n\\nMust easily scale and accept bursts of volume without deteriorating performance\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1002\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nEmergency response advisor\\n\\nDuring real-time emergencies, the sheer volume and complexity of incoming data is difficult to interpret and correlate. Feeds from news reports and social media and real-time updates from emergency responders can quickly overwhelm analysts and decision-makers. During a major crisis, such as a flood, data from these sources can exceed 500,000 data points per hour*, delaying decision-making and putting the public at risk. There is a need to quickly synthesize real-time data to improve situational awareness to support decision-making, forecast possible scenarios, and help coordinate resources to reduce risks to human life and property.\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n*Illustrative, hypothetical data\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   43\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1002\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution. \\n\\nEmergency response advisor\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Comply with legal regulations and ethical standards related to data use and privacy during emergencies. Enhance the team's capability to deliver high-quality crisis management services both on-prem and remotely. Allow users of varying technical skills to access and interpret real-time data securely and comfortably. Interact with users to gather additional context and improve its understanding of the situation. Have access to various data sources, including real-time updates, historical data, and social media feeds. Integrate seamlessly with existing disaster response systems and tools. Run efficiently in the cloud with minimal costs and scalable infrastructure.\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1002\\n\\nArchitect the solution and align needs with technology \\n\\nEmergency response advisor\\n\\nAccountable\\n\\ndecision-makers\\n\\nHigh-reasoningadvisor LLM\\n\\nDecisions-makers and onsite responders review interpretation of data and determine appropriate action.\\n\\nOnsite responders\\n\\nPolling clock\\n\\nNewsmedia\\n\\nData is analyzed at polling intervals.\\n\\nSocialmedia\\n\\nData is collected into an unstructured database for review.\\n\\nEventdatabase\\n\\nVoice-to-textmodel\\n\\nWeatherdata\\n\\nMedia is analyzed and converted to text.\\n\\nImage-to-textmodel\\n\\nPublic cameras\\n\\nAnalyst note: Real-time systems need to be updated and triggered by an event, timer, or poll to process new data.\\n\\nBulletins& alerts \\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1003\\n\\nContext\\n\\nUse case summary\\n\\nDynamic training delivery\\n\\nSolution features\\n\\nAn MSP needs to train users at its largest customer and wants to provide highly customized, engaging content. Webinar-style training sessions have been more engaging and successful than traditional eLearning modules, and the MSP wants to automate this type of interactive delivery. \\n\\nUsers join a simulated webinar where they can request specific content through a chat interface. After starting, the content stream is updated in real-time according to user requests and input and appears as if the webinar host is responding directly to their needs. This experience is facilitated by breaking a prerecorded webinar into consumable segments, precompiling transition videos with a video-to-video model, and leveraging an LLM to dynamically reorganize the video stream feed.\\n\\nLLM capability requirements\\n\\nChatGPT prompt[October 2024]: Draw a one-panel comic of an AI giving a webinar.\\n\\nAnalyzes prerecorded webinars and segments them into logical, individually consumable components based on the content's structure and thematic breakpoints\\n\\nGenerates seamless transitions between video segments, creating a vast array of possible viewing paths for nonlinear exploration of content\\n\\nEnables interactions with the webinar content through a chat window, the requesting of specific content or deep dives, and the dynamic reorganization of video segments to suit user preferences in real time\\n\\nMust convert text-based requests into arbitrary video stream sequences\\n\\nMust decompose webinar recordings into logical pieces\\n\\nMust generate multiple last-frame to first-frame video segments\\n\\nMust adopt a consistent and engaging persona during interactions with users\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1003\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nDynamic training delivery\\n\\nWebinar training lacks the flexibility to cater to the diverse needs of individual participants and forces all users to follow a fixed content flow that may not address their specific interests or knowledge gaps. Feedback indicates that 70% of participants feel that traditional webinars do not adequately cover their areas of interest, leading to a 40% lower engagement rate compared to other delivery methods.* There is a need for a dynamic training delivery system that allows users to request custom content and receive tailored responses in real time to enhance user engagement and learning outcomes. \\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n*Illustrative, hypothetical data\\n\\nInfo-Tech Research Group   |   47\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1003\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution. \\n\\nDynamic training delivery\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Comply with educational standards and data privacy regulations to protect user information. Provide training to the team on using and managing AI and LLM technologies for content delivery. Provide a personalized learning experience by allowing users to request specific content and receive tailored responses. Accurately analyze and segment webinars into logical components and generate seamless transitions. Integrate with various content sources, including prerecorded webinars and supplementary materials. Integrate seamlessly with existing learning management systems (LMS) and training platforms. Run efficiently in the cloud to provide scalability and minimize operational costs.\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1003\\n\\nArchitect the solution and align needs with technology \\n\\nAnalyst note: LLMs can modify files dynamically, allowing them to be used in novel ways to created new experiences.\\n\\nDynamic training delivery\\n\\nThe video player shows a modified stream of content based on the natural language requests in the chat interface.\\n\\nLearner\\n\\nLive streamingplaylist\\n\\nSingle-page web application\\n\\nLive replay\\n\\nmode\\n\\nVideo player\\n\\nDynamic\\n\\nplaylist\\n\\nupdates\\n\\nAPI\\n\\nThe streaming server pulls from prerecorded segments and transitions and broadcasts content according to the live streaming playlist order.\\n\\nChat interface\\n\\nThe learner starts a prerecorded webinar and requests customizations to the content, length, and detail at any time through an interactive chat moderator. \\n\\nLLM\\n\\nMedia fragments\\n\\nThe LLM responds to user chats and updates the live streaming playlist to align content with requests. \\n\\nStreaming server\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1004\\n\\nContext\\n\\nUse case summary\\n\\nStrategy builder tool\\n\\nSolution features\\n\\nABC Advisory specializes in digital strategy development with low-maturity customers. The company has a standard strategy template it completes with customers as part of a workshop, which it supplements with additional surveys, interviews, and stakeholder engagements. \\n\\nThe strategy builder tool (SBT) takes inputs from workshops, asks clarifying questions, and identifies inconsistencies. After reviewing preliminary notes with ABC Advisors, the SBT creates an engagement plan and a list of stakeholders before sending targeted emails and messages to collect additional insights and opinions. The SBT incorporates responses from its automated channels with additional notes and transcripts taken during interviews and generates a draft strategy document for review with customers. \\n\\nLLM capability requirements\\n\\nChatGPT prompt[July 2024]:\\n\\nDraw this target user experience in an abstract way: [\\u2026.].\\n\\nCombines information from workshop activities, responses to automated messages, interview transcripts, and other collateral to draft a comprehensive strategy document for review with customers\\n\\nIncorporates safeguards to mitigate the influence of inappropriate or hateful comments during stakeholder canvasing, ensuring ethical and unbiased inputs\\n\\nDrafts and sends solicitation emails and messages to stakeholders, efficiently managing basic data collection and engagement activities\\n\\nMust incorporate safeguards to mitigate the influence of inappropriate or hateful data collected during stakeholder canvasing\\n\\nMust include mechanisms to detect and correct biases in data processing\\n\\nMust create solicitation emails and process responses to collect data\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1004\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nStrategy builder\\n\\nGenerating comprehensive and unbiased strategies requires broad engagement and input from stakeholders. When done manually, the process is time-consuming and inefficient, taking an average of 50 hours per plan and resulting in 20% of plans showing significant bias from subjective data collection and poorly executed interviews.* There is a need to consistently collect data from a diverse group of stakeholders honestly, ethically, and without bias. Streamlining interviews, surveys, and data collation can reduce the average time it takes to create a strategy and ensure the development of effective, unbiased strategies for customers.\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n*Illustrative, hypothetical data.\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1004\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution. \\n\\nStrategy builder\\n\\nThe solution is required to: Adhere to ethical guidelines and regulatory compliance in data collection and strategic planning. Provide training to the team on using the SBT effectively and understanding AI-driven strategic planning. Offer an easy-to-use interface for consultants to input data, review drafts, and interact with the tool. Generate honest, ethical, and unbiased strategies with safeguards against inappropriate or harmful data. Ensure secure data handling practices to protect sensitive business information. Integrate seamlessly with existing tools and systems used by ABC Advisory for data collection and strategic planning. Run efficiently in the cloud to provide scalability and cost-effectiveness.\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1004\\n\\nArchitect the solution and align needs with technology \\n\\nAnalyst note: Email integration is an interesting approach to incorporating asynchronous workflows into existing processes and systems.\\n\\nStrategy builder\\n\\nExternalstakeholders\\n\\nEmail LLM\\n\\nWorkshop activity and interview data\\n\\nStakeholderlist\\n\\nThe solution communicates\\n\\nvia email by drafting and sending messages and extracting data from responses.\\n\\nEmailservice\\n\\nThe strategy LLM creates a list of stakeholders to canvas.\\n\\nDraft strategy\\n\\nStrategy LLM\\n\\nCRM\\n\\nWhen conditions are met, the LLM generates a draft strategy. Conditions could include time intervals, number of external responses, or a generation request.\\n\\nInterview, activity, and survey data\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1005\\n\\nContext\\n\\nUse case summary\\n\\nInteractive tour guide\\n\\nSolution features\\n\\nNo, Picasso did not steal the Mona Lisa, but he was briefly implicated in an investigation surrounding its 1911 theft from the Louvre\\u2026\\n\\nThe National Museum of Art has a large collection of world class artifacts on display. Visitor expectations, interests, and schedules vary considerably, and the museum wants to offer personalized and interactive tour experiences in multiple languages. \\n\\nVisitors download the museum app and enjoy a personalized and interactive tour guide in the language of their choice. They can communicate with the AI through a headset by typing questions or selecting common questions from a list. The AI guide uses natural language to answer questions, explain exhibits, and recommend tour paths based on individual interests, real-time location data, and current hall volumes. Visitors receive accurate and customized information throughout their visit.\\n\\nChatGPT prompt[October 2024]:\\n\\nDraw me a picture of this user experience using a geometric style inspired by cubism: [\\u2026]\\n\\nLLM capability requirements\\n\\nMust accurately interpret and respond to requests from visitors in natural language\\n\\nMust interpret guest behavior and adjust recommendations and information depth\\n\\nMust maintain an engaging experience and persona and incorporate humor when appropriate\\n\\nMust support multiple languages\\n\\nEngages visitors with an animated avatar on a mobile app that accepts voice input\\n\\nAccurately interprets and responds to visitor inquiries ranging from general information requests to specific exhibit questions\\n\\nAdjusts recommendations and information verbosity based on visitor input and behavior, offering a personalized experience\\n\\nProvides immediate and engaging responses that feel natural to the end user\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1005\\n\\nDescribe the human or organizational need for the solution\\n\\nInteractive museum tour\\n\\nProviding personalized and culturally sensitive museum tours to diverse visitors is challenging due to the difficulty of finding staff who can speak multiple languages and understand various cultural contexts. Only 20% of staff are fluent in more than one language, and visitor feedback indicates a 30% lower satisfaction rate among non-native language speakers.* This results in a gap in meeting the expectations of international visitors and those from different cultural backgrounds. There is a need for a multilanguage and culturally sensitive solution that can improve engagement and satisfaction through customized, interactive tour experiences and answer inquiries, explains exhibits, and recommend tour paths in real time.\\n\\nSpecific\\n\\nRelevant\\n\\nUser-centric\\n\\nScoped\\n\\n*Illustrative, hypothetical data\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1005\\n\\nUse the human-tech ladder to define the solution. \\n\\nInteractive museum tour\\n\\nThen solution is required to: Comply with accessibility standards and provide equal experiences for all visitors, regardless of language or physical ability. Provide training to museum staff on how to assist visitors in using the AI guide and troubleshoot any issues. Offer an intuitive interface for visitors to interact with the AI guide, ensuring ease of use. Accurately interpret and respond to diverse visitor inquiries and comments. Integrate with real-time location data and visitor flow information to provide accurate and timely recommendations. Integrate seamlessly with existing museum systems, including exhibit information databases and visitor management systems. Run efficiently both in the cloud to provide scalability and on local servers for real-time processing needs.\\n\\nOrganization\\n\\nTeam\\n\\nUser\\n\\nModel\\n\\nData\\n\\nSoftware\\n\\nHardware\\n\\n\\n\\nSolution Library ID: 1005\\n\\nArchitect the solution and align needs with technology \\n\\nInteractive museum tour\\n\\nLLM context window has the user's coordinates and query and the fact sheets necessary to generate a response.\\n\\nContext window with memory\\n\\nAPIresponse\\n\\nLLM\\n\\ngenerator\\n\\nFact sheets\\n\\nAPIrequest\\n\\nContext window with memory\\n\\nLLMretriever\\n\\nLocation coordinates\\n\\nLocation coordinates\\n\\nUser query\\n\\nUser engages with a friendly avatar through the museum's mobile app.\\n\\nUser query\\n\\nInteractive Avatar\\n\\nVisitor\\n\\nThe mobile app transfers location and user query information into the context window.\\n\\nLookup\\n\\nRelevant documents\\n\\nRAG implementation\\n\\nMobile device\\n\\nMuseumfact sheets\\n\\nAnalyst note: RAG gives you the ability to manage and curate your source data. The data is injected into the prompt window.\\n\\nThe solution retrieves curated museum fact sheets about artifacts, exhibits, exhibit halls, and the building.\\n\\n\\n\\nNext Steps\\n\\nUse Info-Tech's design methodology to align technical solutions with organizational needs. \\n\\n\\n\\nNext step\\n\\nWireframe designs as part of your AI journey\\n\\nIdentify relevant capabilities to support your AI use case and streamline your vendor selection process to find the right implementation partner.\\n\\nCut through the hype surrounding AI to optimize investments for leveraging this technology to drive business outcomes.\\n\\nAssess the capabilities of different LLMs for your design needs by using metrics and benchmarks.\\n\\nWireframe Your Generative AI Solution DeSIGN\\n\\nLeverage Metrics and Benchmarks to Evaluate LLMs\\n\\nGET READY TO DELIVER AI SERVICES\\n\\nAdopt Design Thinking in Your Organization\\n\\nLaunch Your AI Proof of Concept\\n\\nBuild Your AI Strategic Roadmap\\n\\nGet ready to support your customers with AI service offerings. Evaluate LLMs as part of your service delivery.\\n\\nBLUEPRINT\\n\\nBLUEPRINT\\n\\nWORKSHOP\\n\\nWORKSHOP\\n\\nLeverage the capabilities of design thinking to balance exploration (i.e. discovering new business models) and exploitation (i.e. leveraging existing business models).\\n\\nCAD\\n\\nCAD\\n\\nUse this CAD to transform ideas into wireframe diagrams to facilitate communication and engagement with stakeholders.\\n\\n\\n\\nRelated Info-Tech research\\n\\nIdentify and Select Pilot AI Use Cases\\n\\nAdopt Generative AI in Solution Delivery\\n\\nEstablish a core working group including business champions and identify who will own the pilot process from start to finish.\\n\\nGive AI a purpose in your organization by aligning it to your organization's definition of business value.\\n\\nDevelop a streamlined process to evaluate potential use cases and select your first AI pilot project.\\n\\nDiscuss how proven Gen AI capabilities can be applied to your solution delivery practice to achieve the outcomes and priorities stakeholders expect. Lessons learned sow the foundation for future Gen AI scaling.\\n\\nAssess Gen AI readiness in your solution delivery teams. Clarify the roles, processes, and tools needed for the implementation, use, and maintenance of Gen AI.\\n\\nNeed help using Gen AI to build solutions?\\n\\nGenerative AI Use Case Library for the Technology Service Provider Industry\\n\\nConsider use cases, business scenarios, and case studies in different categories to kick off brainstorming.\\n\\nAlign use cases with a business reference architecture to determine which capabilities can be enhanced through AI innovation.\\n\\nNeed use case ideas?\\n\\nNeed help picking a good use case?\\n\\n\\n\\nOur AI Marketplace is updated weekly!\\n\\nRelated Info-Tech services \\n\\n\\n\\nAdditional support\\n\\nDr. Justin St-MauricePrincipal Research Director\\n\\nTechnology ServicesInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nTo accelerate this project, engage your team with an Info-Tech industry expert. Book an analyst call, guided implementation or Workshop today!\\n\\nThe following sample activities can be facilitated by Info-Tech analysts with your team.\\n\\nCustomize Level 2 Business Capability Maps\\n\\nAI Service Capability Assessment\\n\\nUsing the business capability map as an accelerator, Info-Tech analysts will work with relevant stakeholders to modify and validate the business capability map to suit your organization's context.\\n\\nInfo-Tech analysts will work with relevant stakeholders to review the various capability assessment tools and identify which AI service domain is most appropriate for your business.\\n\\n\\n\\nContributors, reviewers, and experts\\n\\nDr. Catherine BurnsAdvanced Interface Design LabUniversity of Waterloo\\n\\nDr. Yuri KagolovskyProfessor (retired)Conestoga College\\n\\nPeter MeyersAI Advisory LeadMSS Business Transformation Advisory\\n\\nStephen MatusiakChief Technology OfficerHD Mutual Insurance\\n\\nIvan BrockTechnical CounselorInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nVince MirabelliPrinciple Research DirectorInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nRob GarmaiseVP, Artificial Intelligence ResearchInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nJohn AnnandPractice Lead, Global ServicesInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nMartin BufiResearch DirectorInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\nBrian ClarkConsulting DirectorInfo-Tech Research Group\\n\\n\\n\\nBibliography\\n\\nArchibald, Clarence. \\"How to Write a Problem Statement: An In-Depth Guide With Examples.\\" Plannit AI, 13 Feb 2024. \\n\\nBaxter, Gordon and Ian Sommerville. \\"Sociotechnical Systems: From Design Methods to Systems Engineering.\\" Interacting with Computers, Volume 23, Issue 1, Jan 2011, pp. 4-17.\\n\\nGreer, Melvin. \\"RAG: Infusing Realism and Domain Expertise into LLMs, But Could GAN Be the Answer?\\"Intel, 4 Mar 2024. \\n\\n\\"How to Write an Effective Problem Statement for Your Research Paper.\\" Elsevier, n.d. \\n\\n\\"Identifying Criteria and Constraints.\\" NASA, n.d. \\n\\nLakner, Kitti and Erik Roth. \\"We Spent Nearly a Year Building a Generative AI Tool. These Are the 5 (Hard) Lessons We Learned.\\" Fast Company, 11 Jun 2024.\\n\\n\\"Leading Reasons for Software Project Failure According to Developers Worldwide, as of 2015.\\"\\u00a0Statista, 15 Aug 2015. \\n\\nMcGrath, Amanda and Alexandra Jonker. \\"What Is Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)?\\" IBM, 2 Dec 2023.\\n\\nShabatura, Jessica. \\"Bloom's Taxonomy Verb Chart.\\" University of Arkansas, 18 Sep 2014.\\n\\nShvets, Alexander. \\"Dive Into Design Patterns.\\" Source Making, 2021.\\n\\n\\"Sociotechnical Systems.\\" Interaction Design Foundation, 17 Jun 2024. \\n\\nTangermann, Victor. \\"Sam Altman Admits That OpenAI Doesn't Actually Understand How Its AI Works.\\" Futurism, 6 Jun 2024.\\n\\nVicente, Kim. \\"The Human Factor,\\" Random House, 2003.\\n\\n"}	1768338281	/app/backend/data/uploads/a5803090-e721-40b6-844d-6d59276812ad_it-Wireframe-Your-Generative-AI-Solution-Design-Storyboard.pptx	null
